{"title_page": "Agony (1992 video game)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Agony\n|image = Agony Coverart.jpg\n|caption = Cover art by [[Roger Dean (artist)|Roger Dean]]\n|developer = Art & Magic\n|publisher = [[Psygnosis]]\n|designer = Yves Grolet\n|released = {{vgrelease|EU|1992}}\n|genre = [[Scrolling shooter]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Amiga]]\n}}\n\n'''''Agony''''' is a [[scrolling shooter|horizontally scrolling shooter]] with a surreal fantasy background. It was released by [[Psygnosis]] in 1992 for the [[Amiga]].<ref name=\"lemon\">{{cite web |title=Agony |url=http://www.lemonamiga.com/?game_id=40 |website=Lemon Amiga}}</ref> ''Agony'' features a barn owl flying its way through six worlds filled with monsters. The owl uses various waves of echolocation which the player fires at the enemies.\n\n==Plot==\nAccording to the manual backstory, the sun-wizard master Acanthropsis discovers the \"Cosmic Power\" with a toll on his life. Before dying he teaches it to his disciples, Alestes and Mentor. Alestes has been transformed into a barn owl, and has to pass through Mentor's traps and monsters in order to reach the Cosmic Power.\n\n==Development==\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe game makes great use of many Amiga features such as scales of colors done with raster lines, [[halfbrite]] graphics mode for the between-level pictures, three layers of parallax scrolling using dual-playfield mode, in-game palette swapping and continuous flashing of the background palette to simulate additional colors. Featuring three floppies, the game ran on all Amiga computers. In common with other Amiga titles, the music was created with [[sampling (music)|sampled sounds]].\n\n==Music==\nThe theme song is by [[Tim Wright (Welsh musician)|Tim Wright]], a classically themed, piano-led instrumental. The title song was adapted without giving him proper credit by the keyboardist of [[Dimmu Borgir]] in the song \"Sorgens Kammer\" for their ''[[Stormbl\u00e5st]]'' album.<ref name=\"without credit\">[http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony/files/notes.txt ''Agony'' notes at Psygnosiss]</ref> The band did not know about this. Following several months of communication between Wright and Dimmu Borgir, and in a nod to the composer, the band did not include the track on a later re-recording of ''Stormbl\u00e5st''.<ref name=\"re-recording\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071203213746/http://www.punktv.ca/?c=104&a=1612 Re-recording information at Punk TV]</ref> The title song is also slightly different from the version that Wright originally submitted to Art & Magic. Franck Sauer advised Wright that he could source improved piano sounds for the piece, and requested permission to change them. Wright agreed, but did not hear the end result before the game went to the final master, and consequently some notes within the piece were transposed; this 'mistake' was also covered by [[Dimmu Borgir]].<ref name=\"without credit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://francksauer.com/index.php/games/test/15-games/published-games/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10:agony&catid=15:published-games ''Agony''] page from the game's artist Franck Sauer\n* [http://hol.abime.net/?id=3209 ''Agony''] at Amiga Hall of Light\n* [http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony ''Agony''] at Psygnosis.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agony (Video Game)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amiga-only games]]\n[[Category:Europe-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Psygnosis games]]\n[[Category:Horizontally scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jeroen Tel]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Tim Wright]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Agony\n|image = Agony Coverart.jpg\n|caption = Cover art by [[Roger Dean (artist)|Roger Dean]]\n|developer = Art & Magic\n|publisher = [[Psygnosis]]\n|designer = Yves Grolet\n|released = {{vgrelease|EU|1992}}\n|genre = [[Scrolling shooter]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Amiga]]\n}}\n\n'''''Agony''''' is a [[scrolling shooter|horizontally-scrolling shooter]] with a surreal fantasy background. It was released by [[Psygnosis]] in 1992 for the [[Amiga]].<ref name=\"lemon\">{{cite web |title=Agony |url=http://www.lemonamiga.com/?game_id=40 |website=Lemon Amiga}}</ref> ''Agony'' features a barn owl flying its way through six worlds filled with monsters. The owl uses various waves of echolocation which the player fires at the enemies.\n\n==Plot==\nAccording to the manual backstory, the sun-wizard master Acanthropsis discovers the \"Cosmic Power\" with a toll on his life. Before dying he teaches it to his disciples, Alestes and Mentor. Alestes has been transformed into a barn owl, and has to pass through Mentor's traps and monsters in order to reach the Cosmic Power.\n\n==Development==\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe game makes great use of many Amiga features such as scales of colors done with raster lines, [[halfbrite]] graphics mode for the between-level pictures, three layers of parallax scrolling using dual-playfield mode, in-game palette swapping and continuous flashing of the background palette to simulate additional colors. Featuring three floppies, the game ran on all Amiga computers. In common with other Amiga titles, the music was created with [[sampling (music)|sampled sounds]].\n\n==Music==\nThe theme song is by [[Tim Wright (Welsh musician)|Tim Wright]], a classically themed, piano-led instrumental. The title song was adapted without giving him proper credit by the keyboardist of [[Dimmu Borgir]] in the song \"Sorgens Kammer\" for their ''[[Stormbl\u00e5st]]'' album.<ref name=\"without credit\">[http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony/files/notes.txt ''Agony'' notes at Psygnosiss]</ref> The band did not know about this. Following several months of communication between Wright and Dimmu Borgir, and in a nod to the composer, the band did not include the track on a later re-recording of ''Stormbl\u00e5st''.<ref name=\"re-recording\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071203213746/http://www.punktv.ca/?c=104&a=1612 Re-recording information at Punk TV]</ref> The title song is also slightly different from the version that Wright originally submitted to Art & Magic. Franck Sauer advised Wright that he could source improved piano sounds for the piece, and requested permission to change them. Wright agreed, but did not hear the end result before the game went to the final master, and consequently some notes within the piece were transposed; this 'mistake' was also covered by [[Dimmu Borgir]].<ref name=\"without credit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://francksauer.com/index.php/games/test/15-games/published-games/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=10:agony&catid=15:published-games ''Agony''] page from the game's artist Franck Sauer\n* [http://hol.abime.net/?id=3209 ''Agony''] at Amiga Hall of Light\n* [http://www.psygnosis.org/games/agony ''Agony''] at Psygnosis.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agony (Video Game)}}\n[[Category:1992 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amiga-only games]]\n[[Category:Europe-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Psygnosis games]]\n[[Category:Horizontally scrolling shooters]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Jeroen Tel]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Tim Wright]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "Dgpop", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agony_(1992_video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Charles James Fox (editor)", "text_new": "'''Charles James Fox''' BA (c. 1827 \u2013 14 March 1903) was a newspaper editor and owner in Australia.\n\n==History==\nLittle is known of his earlier life, but he was brought up as a Roman Catholic and graduated BA from [[St John's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207718251 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=15 January 1870 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe emigrated to Adelaide, South Australia,{{when}} and married Mary Ann Toole on 31 October 1866.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article77132998 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Border Watch]] |location=South Australia |date=3 November 1866 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was Latin master at [[John Lorenzo Young]]'s [[Adelaide Educational Institution]] from 1868<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207677000 |title=Adelaide Educational Institution |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=3 October 1868 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> to 1871<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158948072 |title=Examinations |newspaper=[[The Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=23 December 1871 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=11 |via=Trove }}</ref> or later.\n\nFox was involved in various Catholic lay organizations: he was hon. sec. of the committee to erect a memorial to Fr. [[Johann Nepomucene Hinter\u00f6cker|J. N. Hinterocker]] SJ (c. 1820\u20131872)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28689568 |title=Topics of the Day |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=South Australia |date=19 October 1872 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }} Hinterocker and Julian Tenison Woods were both noted as scientist-priests.</ref>\nHe succeeded [[Benjamin Hoare]] as editor of ''[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]]'' in Jamuary 1870.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158940250 |title=The Week's News |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=22 January 1870 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=7 |via=Trove }}</ref> \nin which paper he notably criticised [[Laurence Sheil|Bishop Sheil]]'s excommunication of [[Mary MacKillop]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224362588 |title=The Bishop and the Sisters of Saint Joseph |newspaper=[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]] |location=South Australia |date=7 October 1871 |access-date=25 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }} Fox was one of many who consistently misspelled the bishop's name as \"Shiel\".</ref> and was ousted from the South Australian Catholic Association, of which he was president.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207700123 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express and Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=19 October 1871 |access-date=25 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> and founding member.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224541386 |title=SA Catholic Association |newspaper=[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1870 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nHe retired as editor around August 1875.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224368200 |title=Topics |newspaper=[[The Harp and Southern Cross]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1875 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref> to concentrate on an agency he was running at 71 [[King William Street, Adelaide]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224368200 |title=Mr C. J. Fox |newspaper=[[The Harp and Southern Cross]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1875 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIn 1883 he moved to Hobart, Tasmania, where he edited the ''[[Tasmanian Mail]]''. He left for New South Wales in June 1888<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163542592 |title=Shipping |newspaper=[[Tasmanian News]] |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=20 June 1888 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref> \n\nHe purchased the ''[[The Northern Argus (Narrabri)|Northern Argus]]'' of [[Narrabri, New South Wales]], which he ran as proprietor and editor. \nOn 29 August 1890 fire destroyed the building, owned by a Mr. Spencer, and its contents, all of which were owned by Fox: a steam engine and two presses, good quality type and consumables.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18994612 |title=Burning of e Newspaper Office at Narrabri. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 September 1890 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=7 |via=Trove }}</ref> Despite rumors, an inquest found no evidence of arson. Fox had a court case pending in which he was being sued for publishing a libel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71185570 |title=Narrabri Newspaper Case |newspaper=[[Australian Town and Country Journal]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=20 December 1890 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=14 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed editor of the \"funny and harmless old rag\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42940376 |title=Notes & Notices |newspaper=[[Morning Post (Cairns)]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=25 November 1899 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref> the ''[[Cairns Argus]]'' in May 1899,<ref>{{cite news|title=Telegraphic News |date= 24 May 1899 |newspaper=The Northern Miner |location=Charters Towers, Queensland, Australia |page=3 |access-date=28 April 2020 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article84868256 |via=Trove}}</ref> and was still editor in February 1903, when he sprained his ankle as the result of a fall and was hospitalised in [[Townsville]]. He died there a week later.\n\n[[Frank Fox (author)|Frank Fox]] (born 10 August 1874), author and editor of ''[[The Lone Hand (magazine)|The Lone Hand]]'' (and much else) was a son.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fox, Charles James}}\n[[Category:1827 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles James Fox''' BA (c. 1827 \u2013 14 March 1903) was a newspaper editor and owner in Australia.\n\n==History==\nLittle is known of his earlier life, but he was brought up as a Roman Catholic and graduated BA from [[St John's College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207718251 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express And Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=15 January 1870 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe emigrated to Adelaide, South Australia,{{when}} and married Mary Ann Toole on 31 October 1866.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article77132998 |title=Family Notices |newspaper=[[The Border Watch]] |location=South Australia |date=3 November 1866 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was Latin master at [[John Lorenzo Young]]'s [[Adelaide Educational Institution]] from 1868<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207677000 |title=Adelaide Educational Institution |newspaper=[[The Express And Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=3 October 1868 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> to 1871<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158948072 |title=Examinations |newspaper=[[The Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=23 December 1871 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=11 |via=Trove }}</ref> or later.\n\nFox was involved in various Catholic lay organizations: he was hon. sec. of the committee to erect a memorial to Fr. [[Johann Nepomucene Hinter\u00f6cker|J. N. Hinterocker]] SJ (c. 1820\u20131872)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28689568 |title=Topics of the Day |newspaper=[[The South Australian Advertiser]] |location=South Australia |date=19 October 1872 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }} Hinterocker and Julian Tenison Woods were both noted as scientist-priests.</ref>\nHe succeeded [[Benjamin Hoare]] as editor of ''[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]]'' in Jamuary 1870.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article158940250 |title=The Week's News |newspaper=[[Adelaide Observer]] |location=South Australia |date=22 January 1870 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=7 |via=Trove }}</ref> \nin which paper he notably criticised [[Laurence Sheil|Bishop Sheil]]'s excommunication of [[Mary MacKillop]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224362588 |title=The Bishop and the Sisters of Saint Joseph |newspaper=[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]] |location=South Australia |date=7 October 1871 |access-date=25 April 2020 |page=6 |via=Trove }} Fox was one of many who consistently misspelled the bishop's name as \"Shiel\".</ref> and was ousted from the South Australian Catholic Association, of which he was president.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article207700123 |title=General News |newspaper=[[The Express And Telegraph]] |location=South Australia |date=19 October 1871 |access-date=25 April 2020 |page=2 |via=Trove }}</ref> and founding member.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224541386 |title=SA Catholic Association |newspaper=[[The Irish Harp and Farmers' Herald]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1870 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\nHe retired as editor around August 1875.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224368200 |title=Topics |newspaper=[[The Harp and Southern Cross]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1875 |access-date=27 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref> to concentrate on an agency he was running at 71 [[King William Street, Adelaide]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article224368200 |title=Mr C. J. Fox |newspaper=[[Harp And Southern Cross]] |location=South Australia |date=5 November 1875 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=5 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nIn 1883 he moved to Hobart, Tasmania, where he edited the ''[[Tasmanian Mail]]''. He left for New South Wales in June 1888<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article163542592 |title=Shipping |newspaper=[[Tasmanian News]] |location=Tasmania, Australia |date=20 June 1888 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref> \n\nHe purchased the ''[[The Northern Argus (Narrabri)|Northern Argus]]'' of [[Narrabri, New South Wales]], which he ran as proprietor and editor. \nOn 29 August 1890 fire destroyed the building, owned by a Mr. Spencer, and its contents, all of which were owned by Fox: a steam engine and two presses, good quality type and consumables.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18994612 |title=Burning of e Newspaper Office at Narrabri. |newspaper=[[The Maitland Mercury And Hunter River General Advertiser]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=2 September 1890 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=7 |via=Trove }}</ref> Despite rumors, an inquest found no evidence of arson. Fox had a court case pending in which he was being sued for publishing a libel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71185570 |title=Narrabri Newspaper Case |newspaper=[[Australian Town And Country Journal]] |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=20 December 1890 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=14 |via=Trove }}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed editor of the \"funny and harmless old rag\",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article42940376 |title=Notes & Notices |newspaper=[[Morning Post (Cairns)]] |location=Queensland, Australia |date=25 November 1899 |access-date=28 April 2020 |page=3 |via=Trove }}</ref> the ''[[Cairns Argus]]'' in May 1899,<ref>{{cite news|title=Telegraphic News |date= 24 May 1899 |newspaper=The Northern Miner |location=Charters Towers, Queensland, Australia |page=3 |access-date=28 April 2020 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article84868256 |via=Trove}}</ref> and was still editor in February 1903, when he sprained his ankle as the result of a fall and was hospitalised in [[Townsville]]. He died there a week later.\n\n[[Frank Fox (author)|Frank Fox]] (born 10 August 1874), author and editor of ''[[The Lone Hand (magazine)|The Lone Hand]]'' (and much else) was a son.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fox, Charles James}}\n[[Category:1827 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "miscapitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_James_Fox_(editor)"}
{"title_page": "Paul Martin (illustrator)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on over two dozen covers of ''[[Collier's]]'' and ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' during the 1920s. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York]] area from 1909 to 1931.<ref>The span would be inclusive, except for 1927.</ref> Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as commercially, rather than creativity inspired.<ref>''Artists, Advertising, and the Borders of Art'' by Bogart, 1995 pp. 1-3, 47-55, 78. Their stature was just slightly above, that of the advertising artists. The majority lacked job security.</ref> Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral-interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic element to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22O.Henry%22&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photo), 26 (description). It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EbJMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=Illustrated+World,+March+1920&source=bl&ots=O0TRSyQGMX&sig=#v=onepage&q=%22Great%20White%22&f=false Flasher]. ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689-91.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click banner>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature. (Their art director likely saw it as a distraction.)</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''[[Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies' Home Journal]]'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing together, in those two racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no proof it was used. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921, [[wikt:gravure|gravure]] section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. (See Ref #253.) It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Litho, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as officially known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts''. Copeland, lead editor, 1902 vol. 3 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 278. Excerpt: \"As the [[Great Depression|depression]] deepened, net sales of the company plummeted.\" It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]], [[wikt:AKA|aka]] U.S. Royal (1940).<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> Their international branch acquired a majority stake in [[Englebert (tyre manufacturer)|Englebert]] (1958). Their worldwide names were condensed/simplified into [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal]] (1966).<ref>See Babcock book, 1966 pp. 97 (aka), xv, 410-11 (names).</ref> They merged with Goodrich, and became known as [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986). Its tire division was sold to [[Michelin]] (1990).<ref>The deal was struck 1989. Finalized 1990.</ref> The Fisk Tire brand had a dormant period after 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> This brand was revitalized by [[Michelin]], and produced exclusively for [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2014).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort.\" Editor Dave Zielasko in collaboration with Al Olsen.</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Rubber Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debut 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''Editor & Publisher'' (mag), March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12 (R. G. Bath's quote). \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized.\" The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317 (quote).</ref><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]] notices the new look, after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, that could be framed.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. These were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were all subtitled, \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These were giveaway items, with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He worked as a brokerage clerk, before starting art school in 1902.</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spaldings'', 1911 p. 173 (doubles). ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BCzwbV-L7D4C&pg=RA10-PA72&lpg=RA10-PA72&dq=%22paul+martin%22#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false Parable]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print). [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked among the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]], from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #236.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY metro area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\" (Viewable online at news.hrvh.org. Select: \"Browse by title.\")</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists). ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to [[American Lithographic Co. v. Werkmeister|American Lithographic]]. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist.\")</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref>''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This cover image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The local model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once. Keywords are sometimes placed after the page number (in parenthesis).\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on over two dozen covers of ''[[Collier's]]'' and ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' during the 1920s. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York]] area from 1909 to 1931.<ref>The span would be inclusive, except for 1927.</ref> Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as commercially, rather than creativity inspired.<ref>''Artists, Advertising, and the Borders of Art'' by Bogart, 1995 pp. 1-3, 47-55, 78. Their stature was just slightly above, that of the advertising artists. The majority lacked job security.</ref> Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral-interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic element to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22O.Henry%22&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photo), 26 (description). It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EbJMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=Illustrated+World,+March+1920&source=bl&ots=O0TRSyQGMX&sig=#v=onepage&q=%22Great%20White%22&f=false Flasher]. ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689-91.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click banner>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature. (Their art director could have seen it as a distraction.)</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''[[Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies' Home Journal]]'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing together, in those two racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no proof it was used. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921, [[wikt:gravure|gravure]] section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. (See Ref #253.) It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Litho, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as officially known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts''. Copeland, lead editor, 1902 vol. 3 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 278. Excerpt: \"As the [[Great Depression|depression]] deepened, net sales of the company plummeted.\" It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]], [[wikt:AKA|aka]] U.S. Royal (1940).<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> Their international branch acquired a majority stake in [[Englebert (tyre manufacturer)|Englebert]] (1958). Their worldwide names were condensed/simplified into [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal]] (1966).<ref>See Babcock book, 1966 pp. 97 (aka), xv, 410-11 (names).</ref> They merged with Goodrich, and became known as [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986). Its tire division was sold to [[Michelin]] (1990).<ref>The deal was struck 1989. Finalized 1990.</ref> The Fisk Tire brand had a dormant period after 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> This brand was revitalized by [[Michelin]], and produced exclusively for [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2014).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort.\" Editor Dave Zielasko in collaboration with Al Olsen.</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Rubber Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debut 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''Editor & Publisher'' (mag), March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12 (R. G. Bath's quote). \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized.\" The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317 (quote).</ref><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]] notices the new look, after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, that could be framed.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. These were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were all subtitled, \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These were giveaway items, with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He worked as a brokerage clerk, before starting art school in 1902.</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spaldings'', 1911 p. 173 (doubles). ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=BCzwbV-L7D4C&pg=RA10-PA72&lpg=RA10-PA72&dq=%22paul+martin%22#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false Parable]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print). [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked among the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]], from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #236.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY metro area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\" (Viewable online at news.hrvh.org. Select: \"Browse by title.\")</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists). ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to [[American Lithographic Co. v. Werkmeister|American Lithographic]]. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist.\")</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref>''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This cover image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The local model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once. Keywords are sometimes placed after the page number (in parenthesis).\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "name_user": "JimPercy", "label": "safe", "comment": "reworded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Martin_(illustrator)"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Saragarhi", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|1897 last stand battle in the British Raj}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Saragarhi\n| partof      = the [[Tirah Campaign]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = Burnt-out interior of Saragarhi as it looked on 14 September, 1897\n| date        = 12 September, 1897\n| place       = [[Tirah]], [[North-West Frontier Province (1901\u201355)|North-West Frontier Province]], [[British India]] (modern day [[Pakistan]])\n| coordinates = {{coord|33|33|15|N|70|53|15|E|display=title,inline}}\n| result      = Afghan tactical victory, British India strategic victory<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite journal| last = Kumar| first = MP Anil| title = Rezang La stands out| journal = Indian Defence Review| accessdate = 29 July 2019| date = 8 July 2018| url = http://www.indiandefencereview.com/spotlights/rezang-la-stands-out/0/}}</ref>\n* The Indian soldiers fought long enough to allow reinforcements to arrive\n* Subsequent strategic victory for British India\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|British Raj}}\n| combatant2  = [[Afridi]] and [[Orakzai]] Tribes\n| commander1  = {{flagdeco|British Raj}} Ishar Singh{{KIA}}\n| commander2  = Gul Badshah\n| units1      = {{flagdeco|British Raj}} [[36th Sikhs]]\n| units2      = [[Afridi]]s and [[Orakzai]]s\n| strength1   = 21<ref name=\"londongaz\">{{London Gazette |issue=26937 |date=11 February 1898 |page=863 }}</ref>\n| strength2   = 10,000<ref name=\"LansfordTom\">{{cite book |author=Tom Lansford |title=Afghanistan at War: From the 18th-Century Durrani Dynasty to the 21st Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XxwIDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA408&lpg=PA408&dq=600+killed+saragarhi&source=bl&ots=-3QStqxh3a&sig=ACfU3U2z65FIc2c1n4pDl8fVjLhWA089wQ&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiE_7T1_aPnAhXfAZ0JHX4HBEs4HhDoATAAegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=600%20killed%20saragarhi&f=false |year=2017 |page=408 |quote=The Orakzais were joined by Afridis swelling their numbers to more than 10000. Groups of the tribesmen attacked Sangar on the night of September 11. The post was on a high ridge and well fortified. Although there were only 44 Sikh troops, the garrison repulsed the attack. The following morning, the natives attacked Saragarhi. The garrison numbered 21 Sikhs, led by Havildar Ishar Singh. Instead of withdrawing to one of the other posts, the Sikhs decided to remain in an effort to maintain communication between the two forts.}}</ref><ref name=\"SharmaGautam\">{{cite book |author1=Sharma, Gautam |title=Valour and Sacrifice: Famous Regiments of the Indian Army |date=1990 |publisher=[[Allied Publishers]] |isbn=978-8170231400 |page=185 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xLrTzZd0j1kC&pg=PA185#v=twopage&q&f=false |accessdate=22 February 2019 |quote=A mass attack came on Saragarhi on September 12 and the 21 strong detachment fought one of the most unequal engagements in the history of warfare. There were fierce onslaughts by the 10,000 Orakzai and Afridi tribesmen. The outnumbered defenders returned the fire in a most determined manner. After a series of abortive attempts, the tribesmen managed to reach the wall of the post by using an ingenious method. Effecting a breach, they were face to face with the brave Sikhs, most of whom had been wounded.}}</ref>{{small|(According to the ''Digest of Service of 36 Sikh'', 10,000 was the number of attackers on the entire Samana ridge; the actual force that attacked Sargarhi numbered 1,000 1,500.)}}<ref name=\"HSPanag_2019\">{{Cite web |url=https://theprint.in/opinion/what-akshay-kumars-kesari-wont-tell-you-the-real-military-account-of-battle-of-saragarhi/ |title=What Akshay Kumar\u2019s Kesari won\u2019t tell you: The real military account of Battle of Saragarhi |last=Panag |first=H S |author-link=Harcharanjit Singh Panag |date=28 March 2019 |website=The Print |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| casualties1 = 21 killed <ref name=\"londongaz\"/>\n| casualties2 = 180 killed, many wounded<ref name=\"Chand_1984\">{{cite book |author=Chand N. Das |title=Traditions and Customs of the Indian Armed Forces |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmXfAAAAMAAJ |year=1984 |publisher=Vision |oclc=11252358 |page=35 |quote=On September 12, 1897, the signal post at Saragarhi was assailed by about 6,000 tribesmen. [...] The tribesmen's casualties were very heavy and they admitted to have lost 180 killed and many more wounded.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Sikh Courier International Volumes 38-42 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JWNRAAAAYAAJ |year=1998 |publisher=Sikh Cultural Society of Great Britain |page=48 |quote=The tribals later admitted to a figure of 180 dead and many more wounded. Some of the details of the closing phases of the fight were pieced together from, the heliograph messages, what could be seen from fort Lockhart and the tribals.}}</ref>{{asterisk}}\n| notes       = {{asterisk}} 600 Afghan bodies were found at the battlefield. Some of them were killed by the artillery fire from the British Indian relief party that recaptured the fort.<ref name=\"Frontier_1897\"/><ref name=\"Sharma\"/><!-- Please note that many articles state that \"The Afghans later admitted they had lost 4,800 men during the engagement.\" The 4800 deaths were not exclusive to Battle of Saragarhi, but the entire campaign -->\n}}\n[[File:Battle of Saragarhi.png|right|306px|thumb|The map of the battle site]]\n'''The Battle of Saragarhi''' was fought before the [[Tirah Campaign]] on 12 September, 1897 between the [[British Raj]] and [[Afghan|Afghan tribesmen]].<ref name=\"stewart\">{{cite book |last1=Stewart |first1=Jules |title=On Afghanistan's Plains: The Story of Britain's Afghan Wars |date=15 August 2011 |publisher=I.B. Tauris}}</ref> On 12 September 1897, estimated 12,000 - 24,000 Orakzai and Afridi tribesmen were seen near Gogra, at Samana Suk and round Saragarhi, cutting off Fort Gulistan from Fort Lockhart. The Afghans attacked the outpost of Saragarhi where thousands of Afghans swarmed and surrounded the fort, preparing to assault it.<ref name=\"haughton\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armycampaigns/indiancampaigns/tirahhaughton.pdf |title=Life of Lieu. Col. John Haughton |last=Yate |first=Major A.C. |date=1900 |page=126 |quote=When day broke on the 12th, the Orakzai-Afridi \"lashkar\" was seen to be in force near Gogra on the east, at the Samana Suk on the west, and round the Saragarhi post, thus severing Gulistan from Fort Lockhart.(Their total number has been variously estimated at from twelve to twenty thousand.)It was, therefore, no longer possible for Colonel Haughton to carry aid to Saragarhi or Guhstan, as he had done twice before. The enemy turned the brunt of their attack on the little post of Saragarhi.}}</ref> The soldiers in the fort, who were all Sihks and led by [[Havildar]] Ishar Singh, chose to fight to the death, in what is considered by some military historians as one of history's greatest [[last stand]]s.<ref name=\"bbcn\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-16027179|publisher=[[BBC News]]|title=India polo match honours Sikhs' 1897 Saragarhi battle|author=Pandey, Geeta|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=19 July 2012}}</ref> The post was recaptured two days later by another British Indian contingent.\n\nThe 4th battalion of the [[Sikh Regiment]] of [[Indian Army]] commemorates the battle every year on 12 September, as ''Saragarhi Day''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/the-21-sikhs-of-saragarhi-114091101117_1.html|title=The 21 Sikhs of Saragarhi|first=Jaisal|last=Singh|date=13 September 2014|publisher=|via=Business Standard}}</ref>\n\n==Situation==\nSaragarhi was a small village in the border district of [[Kohat District|Kohat]], situated on the [[Samana Range]], in present-day Pakistan. On 20 April 1894, the [[36th Sikhs]] of the [[British Indian Army]] was created, under the command of Colonel J. Cook.<ref name=\"pall\">Pall, S.J.S. \"The story of Valiant Sikhs\", Amritsar, B. Chattar Singh (2004) p. 98</ref> It was entirely composed of [[Jat Sikhs]].<ref name=\"Sharma\">{{cite book |author1=Sharma, Gautam |title=Valour and Sacrifice: Famous Regiments of the Indian Army |date=1990 |publisher=[[Allied Publishers]] |isbn=978-8170231400 |page=185 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xLrTzZd0j1kC&pg=PA185#v=twopage&q&f=false |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> In August 1897, five companies of the 36th Sikhs under Lieutenant Colonel John Haughton were sent to the northwest frontier of [[British Raj|British India]] (modern-day [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]) and were stationed at Samana Hills, Kurag, Sangar, Sahtop Dhar and Saragarhi.\n\nThe British had partially succeeded in getting control of this volatile area, but tribal [[Pashtuns]] continued to attack British personnel from time to time. Thus a series of forts, originally built by [[Ranjit Singh]], the ruler of the [[Sikh Empire]], were consolidated. Two of the forts were Fort Lockhart (on the Samana Range of the [[Hindu Kush]] mountains), and Fort Gulistan ([[Sulaiman Range]]), situated a few miles apart. Fort Lockhart is located at 33.5562N 70.9188E.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-3831266&fid=4661&c=pakistan|title=Fort Lockhart Geo Location|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Due to the forts not being visible to each other, Saragarhi was created midway, as a [[heliograph]]ic communication post. The Saragarhi post, situated on a rocky ridge, consisted of a small block house with loop-holed ramparts and a signalling tower.\n\nA general uprising by the Afghans began there in 1897, and between 27 August and 11 September many vigorous efforts by Pashtuns to capture the forts were thwarted by the 36th Sikhs. In 1897, insurgent and inimical activities had increased, and on 3 and 9 September [[Afridi]] tribesmen, allied with the Afghans, attacked Fort Gulistan. Both the attacks were repulsed, and a relief column from Fort Lockhart, on its return trip, reinforced the signalling detachment positioned at Saragarhi, increasing its strength to three [[non-commissioned officers]] (NCOs) and eighteen [[Other ranks (UK)|other ranks]] (ORs).\n\n==The battle==\n[[File:Sikh Regt Soldiers.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Sikh soldiers, c. 1890]]\nDetails of the Battle of Saragarhi are considered fairly accurate, because Gurmukh Singh signalled events to Fort Lockhart by [[heliograph]]<ref name=1908NZStar>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article65010542 |title=Defense of Saragarhi PosT|newspaper=[[The Camperdown Chronicle|Camperdown Chronicle (Vic. : 1877\u20131954)]] |location= |date=5 December 1907 |accessdate=1 September 2014 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> as they occurred.<ref name=\"pall\"/>\n* Around 09:00, approximately 6,000\u201310,000 Afghans reach the signalling post at Saragarhi.\n* [[Sepoy]] Gurmukh Singh signals to Colonel Haughton, situated in Fort Lockhart, that they are under attack.\n* Haughton states he cannot send immediate help to Saragarhi.\n* The soldiers in Saragarhi decide to fight to the last to prevent the enemy from reaching the forts.\n* Sepoy Bhagwan Singh is the first soldier to be killed and [[Naik (military rank)|Naik]] Lal Singh is seriously wounded.\n* Naik Lal Singh and Sepoy Jiwa Singh reportedly carry the body of Bhagwan Singh back to the inner layer of the post.\n* The Afghans break a portion of the wall of the picket.\n* Haughton signals that he has estimated that there are between 10,000 and 14,000 Pashtuns attacking Saragarhi.\n* The leaders of the Pashtun forces reportedly make promises to the soldiers to entice them to surrender.\n* Reportedly two determined attempts are made to rush open the gate, but are unsuccessful.\n* Later, the wall is breached.\n* Thereafter, some of the fiercest hand-to-hand fighting occurs.\n* In an act of outstanding bravery, Havildar Ishar Singh orders his men to fall back into the inner layer, whilst he remains to fight. However, this is breached and all but one of the defending soldiers are killed, along with many of the Pashtuns.\n* Sepoy Gurmukh Singh, who communicated the battle to Haughton, was the last surviving Sikh defender. He is stated to have killed 20 Afghans, the Pashtuns having to set fire to the post to kill him. As he was dying, he was said to have yelled repeatedly the Sikh battle cry \"[[Bole So Nihal]], [[Sat Sri Akal]]!\" (\"One will be blessed eternally, who says that God is the ultimate truth!\").\n\nHaving destroyed Saragarhi, the Afghans turned their attention to Fort Gulistan, but they had been delayed too long, and reinforcements arrived there in the night of 13\u201314 September, before the fort could be captured.<ref name=\"londongaz\"/> The Pashtuns later admitted that they had lost about 180 killed<ref name=\"ioss\">Major General Jaswant Singh [http://www.sikhstudies.org/Periodicals.asp?TtlCod=471 Letter to H.M. Queen Elizabeth II] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012192736/http://www.sikhstudies.org/Periodicals.asp?TtlCod=471 |date=12 October 2007 }} Institute of Sikh Studies (1999) - accessed 30 March 2008</ref> and many more wounded<ref name=\"defending\">Subramanian, L. M. (2006). [http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/ARMY/history/kargil/238-Defending-Saragarhi.html Defending Saragarhi, 12 September 1897], Bharat Rakshak. Accessed 21 April 2016.</ref> during the engagement against the 21 Sikh soldiers, but some 600 bodies<ref name=\"Sharma\"/><!-- Please note that many articles, based on the same source, state that \"The Afghans later admitted they had lost 4,800 men during the engagement.\" The 4800 deaths were not exclusive to Battle of Saragarhi, but the entire campaign --> are said to have been seen around the ruined post when the relief party arrived (however, the fort had been retaken, on 14 September, by the use of intensive artillery fire,<ref name=\"Frontier_1897\">\"The Frontier War,\" ''Daily News'', London (16 Sep 1897)</ref> which may have caused some casualties). The total casualties in the entire campaign, including the Battle of Saragarhi, numbered around 4,800.\n\n===Weapons Used===\nThe weapons given and used by the [[British Indian Army|Indian troops]] were of an older generation compared to the small arms issued to British troops. This was intentionally done after the [[Indian Mutiny of 1857]] to prevent any further mutinies and uprisings from getting out of hand.<ref name=\"vohra\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sundayguardianlive.com/news/9464-book-review-forgotten-battle-saragarhi-brought-life-amarinder-singh |title=Book Review: The forgotten battle of Saragarhi brought to life by Amarinder Singh |last=Vohra |first=Pankaj |date=20 May 2017 |website=SundayGuardianLive |url-status=live }}</ref> The Afghans used the original and copy of Martini-Henry rifles. The Martini\u2013Henry was copied on a large scale by North-West Frontier Province gunsmiths. The chief manufacturers were the Adam Khel Afridi, who lived around the Khyber Pass. The Khyber Pass gunsmiths first acquired examples of the various British service arms during nineteenth-century British military expeditions in the [[North-West Frontier (military history)|North-West Frontier]], which they used to make copies.<ref>Ian Skennerton, ''The Lee-Enfield Story'' (1993). Arms & Militaria Press, Gold Coast QLD (Australia) {{ISBN|1-85367-138-X}}</ref>.\n\n===Commemorative tablet===\nThe inscription of a commemorative tablet reads:\n\n{{quote|The Government of India have caused this tablet to be erected to the memory of the twenty one non-commissioned officers and men of the 36 Sikh Regiment of the Bengal Infantry whose names are engraved below as a perpetual record of the heroism shown by these gallant soldiers who died at their posts in the defense of the fort of Saragarhi, on the 12 September 1897, fighting against overwhelming numbers, thus proving their loyalty and devotion to their sovereign The Queen Empress of India and gloriously maintaining the reputation of the Sikhs for unflinching courage on the field of battle.}}\n\n=== Order of Merit ===\nThe 21 Sikh non-commissioned officers and soldiers who died in the Battle of Saragarhi were from the [[Majha]] region of [[Punjab (region)|Punjab]] and were posthumously awarded the [[Indian Order of Merit]], at that time the highest gallantry award which an Indian soldier could receive. The corresponding gallantry award was the [[Victoria Cross]]. The award is equivalent to today's [[Param Vir Chakra]] awarded by the [[President of India]].\n\nThe names of the 21 recipients of the gallantry award are:<ref name=\"londongaz\"/><ref>Regimental numbers from [https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/why-the-battle-of-saragarhi-is-among-the-most-epic-battles-of-all-time-244503.html photo of Saragarhi memorial plaque]</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n# [[Havildar]] Ishar Singh (regimental number 165)\n# [[Naik (military rank)|Naik]] Lal Singh (332)\n# [[Lance Naik]] Chanda Singh (546)\n# [[Sepoy]] Sundar Singh (1321)\n# Sepoy Ram Singh (287)\n# Sepoy Uttar Singh (492)\n# Sepoy Sahib Singh (182)\n# Sepoy Hira Singh (359)\n# Sepoy Daya Singh (687)\n# Sepoy Jivan Singh (760)\n# Sepoy Bhola Singh (791)\n# Sepoy Narayan Singh (834)\n# Sepoy Gurmukh Singh (814)\n# Sepoy Jivan Singh (871)\n# Sepoy Gurmukh Singh (1733)\n# Sepoy Ram Singh (163)\n# Sepoy Bhagwan Singh (1257)\n# Sepoy Bhagwan Singh (1265)\n# Sepoy Buta Singh (1556)\n# Sepoy Jivan Singh (1651)\n# Sepoy Nand Singh (1221)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Remembrance and legacy==\n[[File:Saragarhi Memorial Ferozepur.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Saragarhi Memorial [[Gurdwara]], built in 1904]]\n\nThe epic poem \"[[Khalsa Bahadur]]\" is in memory of the Sikhs who died at Saragarhi.<ref>{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Gurdev|editor=Harbans Singh|title=The Encyclopedia of Sikhism|url=http://www.advancedcentrepunjabi.org/eos/KHALSA%20BAHADUR.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903102912/http://www.advancedcentrepunjabi.org/eos/KHALSA%20BAHADUR.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 September 2011|edition=2nd|year=1995|publisher=Punjabi University, Patiala|location=Patiala}}</ref>\n\nThe battle has become iconic of [[Eastern culture|eastern military civilisation]], the [[British Empire]]'s military history and Sikh history.<ref name=\"ashes\">Singh, Kanwaljit & Ahluwalia, H.S. ''Saragarhi Battalion: Ashes to Glory'', India, Lancer International (1987) {{ISBN|81-7062-022-8}}</ref> The modern [[Sikh Regiment]] of the [[Indian Army]] continues to commemorate the Battle of Saragarhi on 12 September each year as the Regimental Battle Honours Day. To commemorate the men the British built two Saragarhi [[Gurudwara]]s: one in [[Amritsar]], very close to the main entrance of the [[Harmandir Sahib|Golden Temple]], and another in [[Firozpur Cantonment]], in the district that most of the men hailed from.\n\n===In Indian schools===\nThe [[Indian military]], in particular the Indian Army, has been pushing for the battle to be taught in India's schools. They want it taught due to the heroism shown by the Indian soldiers to act as inspiration for young children. There were articles like these, printed in the Punjab's longest-established newspaper, ''The Tribune'', in 1999: \"the military action at Saragarhi is taught to students the world over and particularly to students in France.\"<ref>Robin Gupta [http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99mar20/saturday/head2.htm An epic performance: A slice of history] Chandigarh, ''The Tribune'' (20 March 1999) - accessed 19 April 2008</ref> Although there seems to be no evidence for this claim (it is not, for example, on France's national school curriculum<ref>[http://eduscol.education.fr/ French Education Ministry website] - accessed 19 April 2008</ref>) the news was enough to provoke political debate, and the battle has been taught in schools in Punjab since 2000:\n\n{{quote|The decision to include the battle story in the school curriculum was taken last year during a public rally presided over by the Punjab Chief Minister, Mr Parkash Singh Badal. Following this, the State Government had issued a notification that the battle story should be included in the school curriculum from this session. There had been a constant demand from the Sikh Regiment and various ex-servicemen's associations that the battle be included in the school curriculum. A similar request had also been put forward to Mr Badal during the battle's state-level centenary celebrations at Ferozepore in 1997. A subsequent letter sent to the Punjab Government by the Saragarhi Memorial and Ethos Promotion Forum had also urged the State Government that the battle has many inspiring lessons for children. On hearing the acts of valour, the British Parliament had then risen in unison to pay homage to the fallen soldiers.<ref name=\"trib3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000405/cth1.htm|publisher=The Tribune |title=Recounting battle of Saragarhi|author=Vijay Mohan|date=2000-04-05|accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref>}}\n\n===Saragarhi Day===\n{{Infobox holiday |\n|holiday_name=Saragarhi Day\n|image=\n|caption=\n|official_name=Saragarhi Day\n|nickname=\n|observedby=[[India]]<ref name =\"trib2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050914/delhi.htm#11|publisher=The Tribune|title=Battle of Saragarhi remembered|author=Tribune News Service |date=14 September 2005|accessdate=5 November 2007}}</ref> (also observed by [[Sikh]]s worldwide)\n|date=12 September (or nearest weekday)\n|observances=Parades, school history projects, government buildings\n|longtype=national & international\n|type=national & international\n|significance=Honors the 21 military [[Sikh]] soldiers who died at the Battle of Saragarhi\n|relatedto=[[Remembrance Day]]\n}}\nSaragarhi Day is a Sikh military commemoration day celebrated on 12 September every year to commemorate the Battle of Saragarhi.<ref name=\"trib2\"/> Sikh military personnel and civilians commemorate the battle around the world every year on 12 September. All units of the [[Sikh Regiment]] celebrate Saragarhi Day every year as the Regimental Battle Honours Day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shri |title=21 Sikhs clashed with ten thousand Pathans- Battle of saragarhi |url=https://www.wiki.meramaal.com/2019/08/28/21-sikhs-clashed-with-ten-thousand-pathans-battle-of-saragarhi/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=Meramaal |date=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Saragarhi Day in the UK====\n\nThe first recorded public discourse on Saragarhi was delivered by [[John Slim, 2nd Viscount Slim|Viscount Lord Slim]] in 2001 when he delivered the annual Portraits of Courage lecture at the [[Imperial War Museum]]. This was hosted by the Maharaja Duleep Singh Centenary Trust. In May 2002 the Prince of Wales inaugurated the Jawans to Generals exhibition which featured a section on Saragarhi. The exhibition successfully toured the UK and was seen by over 100,000 visitors.\n\nSaragarhi was introduced back into the UK by writer and filmmaker Jay Singh-Sohal and the British Army with the launch of the book ''Saragarhi: The Forgotten Battle'' in 2013 at Old College Royal Military Academy Sandhurst.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/15/the-army-is-not-to-blame-for-a-lack-of-diversity--communities-mu/|title=The army is not to blame for a lack of diversity \u2013 communities must step up|first=Jay|last=Singh-Sohal|date=15 April 2016|publisher=The Telegraph }}</ref> It has since been commemorated each year on its battle honour day by the British Armed Forces. In 2014 the commemoration also took place at Sandhurst at the Indian Army Memorial Room. In 2015 it took place at the Honourable Artillery Company in London,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/new/armed-forces-commemorate-the-battle-of-saragarhi|title=Armed Forces commemorate the Battle of Saragarhi|publisher=}}</ref> where it is also due to take place in 2016.\n\nVarious senior ministers and armed forces generals have paid tribute to Sikh service by mentioning the story of Saragarhi. In April 2016 the Defence Secretary Michael Fallon MP made mention as a special Vaisakhi event at the Ministry of Defence. In June 2016 the Chief of the General Staff Sir Nick Carter did the same at a special British Sikh Association dinner.\n\n===Comparisons with Thermopylae===\n\nThe battle has frequently been compared to the [[Battle of Thermopylae]], where a small [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] force faced a large [[Persian Empire|Persian]] army under [[Xerxes I of Persia|Xerxes I]] in 480 BC.<ref name=\"ashes\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/> In both cases, a small defending force faced overwhelming odds, fighting to the last man and inflicting an extremely disproportionate number of fatalities on the attacking force.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== In popular culture ===\n{{Battle of Saragarhi}}\n\nIn September 2017, ''Saragarhi: The True Story'', a documentary by UK-based journalist-filmmaker Jay Singh-Sohal, was screened at the [[National Memorial Arboretum]] in [[Staffordshire]] to mark the 120th anniversary of the epic frontier battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/saragarhi-saga-captured-on-film-465601|title=Saragarhi saga captured on film|first=Tribune News|last=Service|website=Tribuneindia News Service}}</ref>\n\nA TV series, ''[[21 Sarfarosh - Saragarhi 1897]]'' aired on [[Discovery Jeet]] from 12 February 2018 to 11 May 2018 starring [[Mohit Raina]], [[Mukul Dev]], and Balraj Singh Khehra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/after-roadies-city-lad-to-appear-in-tv-show-on-battle-of-saragarhi-462417|title=After Roadies, city lad to appear in TV show on Battle of Saragarhi|first=Tribune News|last=Service|website=Tribuneindia News Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodmdb.com/television/here-re-some-exclusive-pictures-from-the-sets-of-contiloe-pictures-battle-of-saragarhi|title=Here\u2019re some exclusive pictures from the sets of Contiloe Pictures\u2019 \u2018Battle Of Saragarhi\u2019!|date=18 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/now-the-battle-of-saragarhi-on-tv/articleshow/62028846.cms|title=Now, the Battle of Saragarhi on TV  |publisher=Mumbai Mirror}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2017, there are three [[Bollywood]] films being produced regarding the battle: \n\n* ''Sons of Sardaar: The Battle of Saragarhi''. In July 2016, [[Ajay Devgn]] shared a poster of the film, a sequel to [[Son of Sardaar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/ajay-devgn-shares-sons-of-sardaar-the-battle-of-saragarhi-first-look-diwali-2017-release-planned-2922284.html|title=Ajay Devgn shares Sons of Sardaar: The Battle of Saragarhi first look; Diwali 2017 release planned|publisher=}}</ref> In August 2017, Devgn stated: \"We are working on the script but it won\u2019t happen for another two years because of the scale of the project.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/ajay-devgn-saragarhi-is-set-to-happen-but-in-the-next-three-or-four-years/articleshow/60301262.cms|title=Ajay Devgn: Saragarhi is set to happen but in the next three or four years |publisher=Mumbai Mirror}}</ref> \n* ''[[Battle of Saragarhi (film)|Battle of Saragarhi]]''. In August 2016, [[Randeep Hooda]] shared the first look on his Twitter page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/randeep-hooda-battle-of-saragarhi-first-look-see-pic-2948244/|title=First look of Battle of Saragarhi out. Can you guess who is the actor?|date=1 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref> This film is to be directed by [[Rajkumar Santoshi]], starring Hooda, [[Vikramjeet Virk]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/news/17/jan/vikramjeet-virk-interview-bollywood-interviews.asp|title=Vikramjeet Virk: My character in ''Battle of Sarahragrahi'' is like 'Bhishma Pitamah'|website=glamsham.com}}</ref> and [[Danny Denzongpa]].<ref name=\"punemirror.indiatimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://punemirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/randeeps-battle-is-back-on-track/articleshow/61521850.cms|title=Randeep Hooda's next on Battle Of Saragarhi to kick off in Punjab next week, Danny Denzongpa joins cast|publisher=Pune Mirror}}</ref> The film was shelved after the release of ''Kesari''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/randeep-hooda-on-battle-of-saragarhi-it-hurt-that-the-audience-could-not-see-a-more-authentic-version/articleshow/74766159.cms|title=Randeep Hooda on Battle of Saragarhi: It hurt that the audience could not see a more authentic version|website=Mumbai Mirror}}</ref>\n* ''[[Kesari (film)|Kesari]]''. In March 2019, film titled ''Kesari'', based on the Battle of Saragarhi, directed by [[Anurag Singh (director)|Anurag Singh]], starring [[Akshay Kumar]], was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/article/akshay-kumar-karan-johar-proudly-present-new-film-kesari-based-on-battle-of-saragarhi/104992|title=Akshay Kumar, Karan Johar \u2018proudly present\u2019 new film Kesari, based on Battle of Saragarhi|first=|publisher=Times Now}}</ref> \nWith regards to speculation about multiple films being made about the battle, Hooda stated: \"It is good because there were 21 [[Sikh]] heroes in that battle and each one of them deserved to have a movie made on them. So actually there should be 21 films made on them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2017/mar/16/randeep-hooda-says--battle-of-saragarh-not-shelved-1581762.html|title=Randeep hooda says battle of saragarh not shelved|publisher=}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Saragarhi and the Defence of the Samana Forts'' by Amarinder Singh, New Delhi: Bookwise (India) Pvt. Ltd., 2017 {{ISBN|978-8187330677}}\n* ''Saragarhi: The Forgotten Battle'' by Jay Singh-Sohal, Birmingham: Dot Hyphen Publishers, 2013 ({{ISBN|978-0957054073}})\n* ''Saragarhi Battalion: Ashes to Glory'' by Kanwaljit Singh and H.S. Ahluwalia, New Delhi: Lancer International, 1987 ({{ISBN|81-7062-022-8}})\n* {{cite book |first=Anuj Harshwardhan |last=Sharma |year=2017 |title=Against All Odds at Saragarhi |url=https://www.amazon.in/dp/B077C94TXJ#reader_B077C94TXJ |location=New Delhi |publisher=Star Print-o-Bind |id=BO77C94TXJ (Amazon India) |via=Amazon |postscript=. A novel on the subject.}}\n* ''The Battle of Saragarhi, The Last Stand of the 36th Sikh Regiment'' by  Daljeet Singh Sidhu, Amarjit Virdi, Kindle Edition, 1st\nPublished December 2011 by Gyan Khand Media ({{ISBN13|9788190963749}})\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Saragarhi}}\n* [http://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armycampaigns/indiancampaigns/samana.htm Tirah: Samana (1897)], The British Empire (accessed 30 June 2019)\n* {{Cite news |last=Bhullar |first=Pritam |date=4 October 1998 |title=They Dared to Defy |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/1998/98oct04/sunday/head5.htm |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |location=Chandigarh, India |access-date=30 June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saragarhi}}\n[[Category:1897 in Asia]]\n[[Category:Battles involving British India]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Sikhs]]\n[[Category:British Indian history]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1897]]\n[[Category:Last stand battles]]\n[[Category:Military history of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Military history of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Military of British India]]\n[[Category:September 1897 events]]\n[[Category:Tirah Campaign]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|1897 last stand battle in the British Raj}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Battle of Saragarhi\n| partof      = the [[Tirah Campaign]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = Burnt-out interior of Saragarhi as it looked on 14 September, 1897\n| date        = 12 September, 1897\n| place       = [[Tirah]], [[North-West Frontier Province (1901\u201355)|North-West Frontier Province]], [[British India]] (modern day [[Pakistan]])\n| coordinates = {{coord|33|33|15|N|70|53|15|E|display=title,inline}}\n| result      = Afghan tactical victory, British India strategic victory<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite journal| last = Kumar| first = MP Anil| title = Rezang La stands out| journal = Indian Defence Review| accessdate = 29 July 2019| date = 8 July 2018| url = http://www.indiandefencereview.com/spotlights/rezang-la-stands-out/0/}}</ref>\n* The Indian soldiers fought long enough to allow reinforcements to arrive\n* Subsequent strategic victory for British India\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|British Raj}}\n| combatant2  = [[Afridi]] and [[Orakzai]] Tribes\n| commander1  = {{flagdeco|British Raj}} Ishar Singh{{KIA}}\n| commander2  = Gul Badshah\n| units1      = {{flagdeco|British Raj}} [[36th Sikhs]]\n| units2      = [[Afridi]]s and [[Orakzai]]s\n| strength1   = 21<ref name=\"londongaz\">{{London Gazette |issue=26937 |date=11 February 1898 |page=863 }}</ref>\n| strength2   = 10,000<ref name=\"LansfordTom\">{{cite book |author=Tom Lansford |title=Afghanistan at War: From the 18th-Century Durrani Dynasty to the 21st Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XxwIDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA408&lpg=PA408&dq=600+killed+saragarhi&source=bl&ots=-3QStqxh3a&sig=ACfU3U2z65FIc2c1n4pDl8fVjLhWA089wQ&hl=en&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiE_7T1_aPnAhXfAZ0JHX4HBEs4HhDoATAAegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=600%20killed%20saragarhi&f=false |year=2017 |page=408 |quote=The Orakzais were joined by Afridis swelling their numbers to more than 10000. Groups of the tribesmen attacked Sangar on the night of September 11. The post was on a high ridge and well fortified. Although there were only 44 Sikh troops, the garrison repulsed the attack. The following morning, the natives attacked Saragarhi. The garrison numbered 21 Sikhs, led by Havildar Ishar Singh. Instead of withdrawing to one of the other posts, the Sikhs decided to remain in an effort to maintain communication between the two forts.}}</ref><ref name=\"SharmaGautam\">{{cite book |author1=Sharma, Gautam |title=Valour and Sacrifice: Famous Regiments of the Indian Army |date=1990 |publisher=[[Allied Publishers]] |isbn=978-8170231400 |page=185 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xLrTzZd0j1kC&pg=PA185#v=twopage&q&f=false |accessdate=22 February 2019}} |quote=A mass attack came on Saragarhi on September 12 and the 21 strong detachment fought one of the most unequal engagements in the history of warfare. There were fierce onslaughts by the 10,000 Orakzai and Afridi tribesmen. The outnumbered defenders returned the fire in a most determined manner. After a series of abortive attempts, the tribesmen managed to reach the wall of the post by using an ingenious method. Effecting a breach, they were face to face with the brave Sikhs, most of whom had been wounded.</ref>{{small|(According to the ''Digest of Service of 36 Sikh'', 10,000 was the number of attackers on the entire Samana ridge; the actual force that attacked Sargarhi numbered 1,000-1,500.)}}<ref name=\"HSPanag_2019\">{{Cite web |url=https://theprint.in/opinion/what-akshay-kumars-kesari-wont-tell-you-the-real-military-account-of-battle-of-saragarhi/ |title=What Akshay Kumar\u2019s Kesari won\u2019t tell you: The real military account of Battle of Saragarhi |last=Panag |first=H S |author-link=Harcharanjit Singh Panag |date=28 March 2019 |website=The Print |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n| casualties1 = 21 killed <ref name=\"londongaz\"/>\n| casualties2 = 180 killed, many wounded<ref name=\"Chand_1984\">{{cite book |author=Chand N. Das |title=Traditions and Customs of the Indian Armed Forces |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmXfAAAAMAAJ |year=1984 |publisher=Vision |oclc=11252358 |page=35 |quote=On September 12, 1897, the signal post at Saragarhi was assailed by about 6,000 tribesmen. [...] The tribesmen's casualties were very heavy and they admitted to have lost 180 killed and many more wounded.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Sikh Courier International Volumes 38-42 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JWNRAAAAYAAJ |year=1998 |publisher=Sikh Cultural Society of Great Britain |page=48 |quote=The tribals later admitted to a figure of 180 dead and many more wounded. Some of the details of the closing phases of the fight were pieced together from, the heliograph messages, what could be seen from fort Lockhart and the tribals.}}</ref>{{asterisk}}\n| notes       = {{asterisk}} 600 Afghan bodies were found at the battlefield. Some of them were killed by the artillery fire from the British Indian relief party that recaptured the fort.<ref name=\"Frontier_1897\"/><ref name=\"Sharma\"/><!-- Please note that many articles state that \"The Afghans later admitted they had lost 4,800 men during the engagement.\" The 4800 deaths were not exclusive to Battle of Saragarhi, but the entire campaign -->\n}}\n[[File:Battle of Saragarhi.png|right|306px|thumb|The map of the battle site]]\n'''The Battle of Saragarhi''' was fought before the [[Tirah Campaign]] on 12 September, 1897 between the [[British Raj]] and [[Afghan|Afghan tribesmen]].<ref name=\"stewart\">{{cite book |last1=Stewart |first1=Jules |title=On Afghanistan's Plains: The Story of Britain's Afghan Wars |date=15 August 2011 |publisher=I.B. Tauris}}</ref> On 12 September 1897, estimated 12,000 - 24,000 Orakzai and Afridi tribesmen were seen near Gogra, at Samana Suk and round Saragarhi, cutting off Fort Gulistan from Fort Lockhart. The Afghans attacked the outpost of Saragarhi where thousands of Afghans swarmed and surrounded the fort, preparing to assault it.<ref name=\"haughton\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armycampaigns/indiancampaigns/tirahhaughton.pdf |title=Life of Lieu. Col. John Haughton |last=Yate |first=Major A.C. |date=1900 |page=126 |quote=When day broke on the 12th, the Orakzai-Afridi \"lashkar\" was seen to be in force near Gogra on the east, at the Samana Suk on the west, and round the Saragarhi post, thus severing Gulistan from Fort Lockhart.(Their total number has been variously estimated at from twelve to twenty thousand.)It was, therefore, no longer possible for Colonel Haughton to carry aid to Saragarhi or Guhstan, as he had done twice before. The enemy turned the brunt of their attack on the little post of Saragarhi.}}</ref> The soldiers in the fort, who were all Sihks and led by [[Havildar]] Ishar Singh, chose to fight to the death, in what is considered by some military historians as one of history's greatest [[last stand]]s.<ref name=\"bbcn\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-16027179|publisher=[[BBC News]]|title=India polo match honours Sikhs' 1897 Saragarhi battle|author=Pandey, Geeta|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=19 July 2012}}</ref> The post was recaptured two days later by another British Indian contingent.\n\nThe 4th battalion of the [[Sikh Regiment]] of [[Indian Army]] commemorates the battle every year on 12 September, as ''Saragarhi Day''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/the-21-sikhs-of-saragarhi-114091101117_1.html|title=The 21 Sikhs of Saragarhi|first=Jaisal|last=Singh|date=13 September 2014|publisher=|via=Business Standard}}</ref>\n\n==Situation==\nSaragarhi was a small village in the border district of [[Kohat District|Kohat]], situated on the [[Samana Range]], in present-day Pakistan. On 20 April 1894, the [[36th Sikhs]] of the [[British Indian Army]] was created, under the command of Colonel J. Cook.<ref name=\"pall\">Pall, S.J.S. \"The story of Valiant Sikhs\", Amritsar, B. Chattar Singh (2004) p. 98</ref> It was entirely composed of [[Jat Sikhs]].<ref name=\"Sharma\">{{cite book |author1=Sharma, Gautam |title=Valour and Sacrifice: Famous Regiments of the Indian Army |date=1990 |publisher=[[Allied Publishers]] |isbn=978-8170231400 |page=185 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xLrTzZd0j1kC&pg=PA185#v=twopage&q&f=false |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> In August 1897, five companies of the 36th Sikhs under Lieutenant Colonel John Haughton were sent to the northwest frontier of [[British Raj|British India]] (modern-day [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]) and were stationed at Samana Hills, Kurag, Sangar, Sahtop Dhar and Saragarhi.\n\nThe British had partially succeeded in getting control of this volatile area, but tribal [[Pashtuns]] continued to attack British personnel from time to time. Thus a series of forts, originally built by [[Ranjit Singh]], the ruler of the [[Sikh Empire]], were consolidated. Two of the forts were Fort Lockhart (on the Samana Range of the [[Hindu Kush]] mountains), and Fort Gulistan ([[Sulaiman Range]]), situated a few miles apart. Fort Lockhart is located at 33.5562N 70.9188E.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-3831266&fid=4661&c=pakistan|title=Fort Lockhart Geo Location|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Due to the forts not being visible to each other, Saragarhi was created midway, as a [[heliograph]]ic communication post. The Saragarhi post, situated on a rocky ridge, consisted of a small block house with loop-holed ramparts and a signalling tower.\n\nA general uprising by the Afghans began there in 1897, and between 27 August and 11 September many vigorous efforts by Pashtuns to capture the forts were thwarted by the 36th Sikhs. In 1897, insurgent and inimical activities had increased, and on 3 and 9 September [[Afridi]] tribesmen, allied with the Afghans, attacked Fort Gulistan. Both the attacks were repulsed, and a relief column from Fort Lockhart, on its return trip, reinforced the signalling detachment positioned at Saragarhi, increasing its strength to three [[non-commissioned officers]] (NCOs) and eighteen [[Other ranks (UK)|other ranks]] (ORs).\n\n==The battle==\n[[File:Sikh Regt Soldiers.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Sikh soldiers, c. 1890]]\nDetails of the Battle of Saragarhi are considered fairly accurate, because Gurmukh Singh signalled events to Fort Lockhart by [[heliograph]]<ref name=1908NZStar>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article65010542 |title=Defense of Saragarhi PosT|newspaper=[[The Camperdown Chronicle|Camperdown Chronicle (Vic. : 1877\u20131954)]] |location= |date=5 December 1907 |accessdate=1 September 2014 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> as they occurred.<ref name=\"pall\"/>\n* Around 09:00, approximately 6,000\u201310,000 Afghans reach the signalling post at Saragarhi.\n* [[Sepoy]] Gurmukh Singh signals to Colonel Haughton, situated in Fort Lockhart, that they are under attack.\n* Haughton states he cannot send immediate help to Saragarhi.\n* The soldiers in Saragarhi decide to fight to the last to prevent the enemy from reaching the forts.\n* Sepoy Bhagwan Singh is the first soldier to be killed and [[Naik (military rank)|Naik]] Lal Singh is seriously wounded.\n* Naik Lal Singh and Sepoy Jiwa Singh reportedly carry the body of Bhagwan Singh back to the inner layer of the post.\n* The Afghans break a portion of the wall of the picket.\n* Haughton signals that he has estimated that there are between 10,000 and 14,000 Pashtuns attacking Saragarhi.\n* The leaders of the Pashtun forces reportedly make promises to the soldiers to entice them to surrender.\n* Reportedly two determined attempts are made to rush open the gate, but are unsuccessful.\n* Later, the wall is breached.\n* Thereafter, some of the fiercest hand-to-hand fighting occurs.\n* In an act of outstanding bravery, Havildar Ishar Singh orders his men to fall back into the inner layer, whilst he remains to fight. However, this is breached and all but one of the defending soldiers are killed, along with many of the Pashtuns.\n* Sepoy Gurmukh Singh, who communicated the battle to Haughton, was the last surviving Sikh defender. He is stated to have killed 20 Afghans, the Pashtuns having to set fire to the post to kill him. As he was dying, he was said to have yelled repeatedly the Sikh battle cry \"[[Bole So Nihal]], [[Sat Sri Akal]]!\" (\"One will be blessed eternally, who says that God is the ultimate truth!\").\n\nHaving destroyed Saragarhi, the Afghans turned their attention to Fort Gulistan, but they had been delayed too long, and reinforcements arrived there in the night of 13\u201314 September, before the fort could be captured.<ref name=\"londongaz\"/> The Pashtuns later admitted that they had lost about 180 killed<ref name=\"ioss\">Major General Jaswant Singh [http://www.sikhstudies.org/Periodicals.asp?TtlCod=471 Letter to H.M. Queen Elizabeth II] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012192736/http://www.sikhstudies.org/Periodicals.asp?TtlCod=471 |date=12 October 2007 }} Institute of Sikh Studies (1999) - accessed 30 March 2008</ref> and many more wounded<ref name=\"defending\">Subramanian, L. M. (2006). [http://www.bharat-rakshak.com/ARMY/history/kargil/238-Defending-Saragarhi.html Defending Saragarhi, 12 September 1897], Bharat Rakshak. Accessed 21 April 2016.</ref> during the engagement against the 21 Sikh soldiers, but some 600 bodies<ref name=\"Sharma\"/><!-- Please note that many articles, based on the same source, state that \"The Afghans later admitted they had lost 4,800 men during the engagement.\" The 4800 deaths were not exclusive to Battle of Saragarhi, but the entire campaign --> are said to have been seen around the ruined post when the relief party arrived (however, the fort had been retaken, on 14 September, by the use of intensive artillery fire,<ref name=\"Frontier_1897\">\"The Frontier War,\" ''Daily News'', London (16 Sep 1897)</ref> which may have caused some casualties). The total casualties in the entire campaign, including the Battle of Saragarhi, numbered around 4,800.\n\n===Weapons Used===\nThe weapons given and used by the [[British Indian Army|Indian troops]] were of an older generation compared to the small arms issued to British troops. This was intentionally done after the [[Indian Mutiny of 1857]] to prevent any further mutinies and uprisings from getting out of hand.<ref name=\"vohra\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.sundayguardianlive.com/news/9464-book-review-forgotten-battle-saragarhi-brought-life-amarinder-singh |title=Book Review: The forgotten battle of Saragarhi brought to life by Amarinder Singh |last=Vohra |first=Pankaj |date=20 May 2017 |website=SundayGuardianLive |url-status=live }}</ref> The Afghans used the original and copy of Martini-Henry rifles. The Martini\u2013Henry was copied on a large scale by North-West Frontier Province gunsmiths. The chief manufacturers were the Adam Khel Afridi, who lived around the Khyber Pass. The Khyber Pass gunsmiths first acquired examples of the various British service arms during nineteenth-century British military expeditions in the [[North-West Frontier (military history)|North-West Frontier]], which they used to make copies.<ref>Ian Skennerton, ''The Lee-Enfield Story'' (1993). Arms & Militaria Press, Gold Coast QLD (Australia) {{ISBN|1-85367-138-X}}</ref>.\n\n===Commemorative tablet===\nThe inscription of a commemorative tablet reads:\n\n{{quote|The Government of India have caused this tablet to be erected to the memory of the twenty one non-commissioned officers and men of the 36 Sikh Regiment of the Bengal Infantry whose names are engraved below as a perpetual record of the heroism shown by these gallant soldiers who died at their posts in the defense of the fort of Saragarhi, on the 12 September 1897, fighting against overwhelming numbers, thus proving their loyalty and devotion to their sovereign The Queen Empress of India and gloriously maintaining the reputation of the Sikhs for unflinching courage on the field of battle.}}\n\n=== Order of Merit ===\nThe 21 Sikh non-commissioned officers and soldiers who died in the Battle of Saragarhi were from the [[Majha]] region of [[Punjab (region)|Punjab]] and were posthumously awarded the [[Indian Order of Merit]], at that time the highest gallantry award which an Indian soldier could receive. The corresponding gallantry award was the [[Victoria Cross]]. The award is equivalent to today's [[Param Vir Chakra]] awarded by the [[President of India]].\n\nThe names of the 21 recipients of the gallantry award are:<ref name=\"londongaz\"/><ref>Regimental numbers from [https://www.indiatimes.com/news/india/why-the-battle-of-saragarhi-is-among-the-most-epic-battles-of-all-time-244503.html photo of Saragarhi memorial plaque]</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n# [[Havildar]] Ishar Singh (regimental number 165)\n# [[Naik (military rank)|Naik]] Lal Singh (332)\n# [[Lance Naik]] Chanda Singh (546)\n# [[Sepoy]] Sundar Singh (1321)\n# Sepoy Ram Singh (287)\n# Sepoy Uttar Singh (492)\n# Sepoy Sahib Singh (182)\n# Sepoy Hira Singh (359)\n# Sepoy Daya Singh (687)\n# Sepoy Jivan Singh (760)\n# Sepoy Bhola Singh (791)\n# Sepoy Narayan Singh (834)\n# Sepoy Gurmukh Singh (814)\n# Sepoy Jivan Singh (871)\n# Sepoy Gurmukh Singh (1733)\n# Sepoy Ram Singh (163)\n# Sepoy Bhagwan Singh (1257)\n# Sepoy Bhagwan Singh (1265)\n# Sepoy Buta Singh (1556)\n# Sepoy Jivan Singh (1651)\n# Sepoy Nand Singh (1221)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Remembrance and legacy==\n[[File:Saragarhi Memorial Ferozepur.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Saragarhi Memorial [[Gurdwara]], built in 1904]]\n\nThe epic poem \"[[Khalsa Bahadur]]\" is in memory of the Sikhs who died at Saragarhi.<ref>{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Gurdev|editor=Harbans Singh|title=The Encyclopedia of Sikhism|url=http://www.advancedcentrepunjabi.org/eos/KHALSA%20BAHADUR.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903102912/http://www.advancedcentrepunjabi.org/eos/KHALSA%20BAHADUR.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 September 2011|edition=2nd|year=1995|publisher=Punjabi University, Patiala|location=Patiala}}</ref>\n\nThe battle has become iconic of [[Eastern culture|eastern military civilisation]], the [[British Empire]]'s military history and Sikh history.<ref name=\"ashes\">Singh, Kanwaljit & Ahluwalia, H.S. ''Saragarhi Battalion: Ashes to Glory'', India, Lancer International (1987) {{ISBN|81-7062-022-8}}</ref> The modern [[Sikh Regiment]] of the [[Indian Army]] continues to commemorate the Battle of Saragarhi on 12 September each year as the Regimental Battle Honours Day. To commemorate the men the British built two Saragarhi [[Gurudwara]]s: one in [[Amritsar]], very close to the main entrance of the [[Harmandir Sahib|Golden Temple]], and another in [[Firozpur Cantonment]], in the district that most of the men hailed from.\n\n===In Indian schools===\nThe [[Indian military]], in particular the Indian Army, has been pushing for the battle to be taught in India's schools. They want it taught due to the heroism shown by the Indian soldiers to act as inspiration for young children. There were articles like these, printed in the Punjab's longest-established newspaper, ''The Tribune'', in 1999: \"the military action at Saragarhi is taught to students the world over and particularly to students in France.\"<ref>Robin Gupta [http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99mar20/saturday/head2.htm An epic performance: A slice of history] Chandigarh, ''The Tribune'' (20 March 1999) - accessed 19 April 2008</ref> Although there seems to be no evidence for this claim (it is not, for example, on France's national school curriculum<ref>[http://eduscol.education.fr/ French Education Ministry website] - accessed 19 April 2008</ref>) the news was enough to provoke political debate, and the battle has been taught in schools in Punjab since 2000:\n\n{{quote|The decision to include the battle story in the school curriculum was taken last year during a public rally presided over by the Punjab Chief Minister, Mr Parkash Singh Badal. Following this, the State Government had issued a notification that the battle story should be included in the school curriculum from this session. There had been a constant demand from the Sikh Regiment and various ex-servicemen's associations that the battle be included in the school curriculum. A similar request had also been put forward to Mr Badal during the battle's state-level centenary celebrations at Ferozepore in 1997. A subsequent letter sent to the Punjab Government by the Saragarhi Memorial and Ethos Promotion Forum had also urged the State Government that the battle has many inspiring lessons for children. On hearing the acts of valour, the British Parliament had then risen in unison to pay homage to the fallen soldiers.<ref name=\"trib3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2000/20000405/cth1.htm|publisher=The Tribune |title=Recounting battle of Saragarhi|author=Vijay Mohan|date=2000-04-05|accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref>}}\n\n===Saragarhi Day===\n{{Infobox holiday |\n|holiday_name=Saragarhi Day\n|image=\n|caption=\n|official_name=Saragarhi Day\n|nickname=\n|observedby=[[India]]<ref name =\"trib2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050914/delhi.htm#11|publisher=The Tribune|title=Battle of Saragarhi remembered|author=Tribune News Service |date=14 September 2005|accessdate=5 November 2007}}</ref> (also observed by [[Sikh]]s worldwide)\n|date=12 September (or nearest weekday)\n|observances=Parades, school history projects, government buildings\n|longtype=national & international\n|type=national & international\n|significance=Honors the 21 military [[Sikh]] soldiers who died at the Battle of Saragarhi\n|relatedto=[[Remembrance Day]]\n}}\nSaragarhi Day is a Sikh military commemoration day celebrated on 12 September every year to commemorate the Battle of Saragarhi.<ref name=\"trib2\"/> Sikh military personnel and civilians commemorate the battle around the world every year on 12 September. All units of the [[Sikh Regiment]] celebrate Saragarhi Day every year as the Regimental Battle Honours Day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shri |title=21 Sikhs clashed with ten thousand Pathans- Battle of saragarhi |url=https://www.wiki.meramaal.com/2019/08/28/21-sikhs-clashed-with-ten-thousand-pathans-battle-of-saragarhi/ |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=Meramaal |date=28 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Saragarhi Day in the UK====\n\nThe first recorded public discourse on Saragarhi was delivered by [[John Slim, 2nd Viscount Slim|Viscount Lord Slim]] in 2001 when he delivered the annual Portraits of Courage lecture at the [[Imperial War Museum]]. This was hosted by the Maharaja Duleep Singh Centenary Trust. In May 2002 the Prince of Wales inaugurated the Jawans to Generals exhibition which featured a section on Saragarhi. The exhibition successfully toured the UK and was seen by over 100,000 visitors.\n\nSaragarhi was introduced back into the UK by writer and filmmaker Jay Singh-Sohal and the British Army with the launch of the book ''Saragarhi: The Forgotten Battle'' in 2013 at Old College Royal Military Academy Sandhurst.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/15/the-army-is-not-to-blame-for-a-lack-of-diversity--communities-mu/|title=The army is not to blame for a lack of diversity \u2013 communities must step up|first=Jay|last=Singh-Sohal|date=15 April 2016|publisher=The Telegraph }}</ref> It has since been commemorated each year on its battle honour day by the British Armed Forces. In 2014 the commemoration also took place at Sandhurst at the Indian Army Memorial Room. In 2015 it took place at the Honourable Artillery Company in London,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/new/armed-forces-commemorate-the-battle-of-saragarhi|title=Armed Forces commemorate the Battle of Saragarhi|publisher=}}</ref> where it is also due to take place in 2016.\n\nVarious senior ministers and armed forces generals have paid tribute to Sikh service by mentioning the story of Saragarhi. In April 2016 the Defence Secretary Michael Fallon MP made mention as a special Vaisakhi event at the Ministry of Defence. In June 2016 the Chief of the General Staff Sir Nick Carter did the same at a special British Sikh Association dinner.\n\n===Comparisons with Thermopylae===\n\nThe battle has frequently been compared to the [[Battle of Thermopylae]], where a small [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] force faced a large [[Persian Empire|Persian]] army under [[Xerxes I of Persia|Xerxes I]] in 480 BC.<ref name=\"ashes\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/> In both cases, a small defending force faced overwhelming odds, fighting to the last man and inflicting an extremely disproportionate number of fatalities on the attacking force.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== In popular culture ===\n{{Battle of Saragarhi}}\n\nIn September 2017, ''Saragarhi: The True Story'', a documentary by UK-based journalist-filmmaker Jay Singh-Sohal, was screened at the [[National Memorial Arboretum]] in [[Staffordshire]] to mark the 120th anniversary of the epic frontier battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/saragarhi-saga-captured-on-film-465601|title=Saragarhi saga captured on film|first=Tribune News|last=Service|website=Tribuneindia News Service}}</ref>\n\nA TV series, ''[[21 Sarfarosh - Saragarhi 1897]]'' aired on [[Discovery Jeet]] from 12 February 2018 to 11 May 2018 starring [[Mohit Raina]], [[Mukul Dev]], and Balraj Singh Khehra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/after-roadies-city-lad-to-appear-in-tv-show-on-battle-of-saragarhi-462417|title=After Roadies, city lad to appear in TV show on Battle of Saragarhi|first=Tribune News|last=Service|website=Tribuneindia News Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodmdb.com/television/here-re-some-exclusive-pictures-from-the-sets-of-contiloe-pictures-battle-of-saragarhi|title=Here\u2019re some exclusive pictures from the sets of Contiloe Pictures\u2019 \u2018Battle Of Saragarhi\u2019!|date=18 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/now-the-battle-of-saragarhi-on-tv/articleshow/62028846.cms|title=Now, the Battle of Saragarhi on TV  |publisher=Mumbai Mirror}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2017, there are three [[Bollywood]] films being produced regarding the battle: \n\n* ''Sons of Sardaar: The Battle of Saragarhi''. In July 2016, [[Ajay Devgn]] shared a poster of the film, a sequel to [[Son of Sardaar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/ajay-devgn-shares-sons-of-sardaar-the-battle-of-saragarhi-first-look-diwali-2017-release-planned-2922284.html|title=Ajay Devgn shares Sons of Sardaar: The Battle of Saragarhi first look; Diwali 2017 release planned|publisher=}}</ref> In August 2017, Devgn stated: \"We are working on the script but it won\u2019t happen for another two years because of the scale of the project.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/ajay-devgn-saragarhi-is-set-to-happen-but-in-the-next-three-or-four-years/articleshow/60301262.cms|title=Ajay Devgn: Saragarhi is set to happen but in the next three or four years |publisher=Mumbai Mirror}}</ref> \n* ''[[Battle of Saragarhi (film)|Battle of Saragarhi]]''. In August 2016, [[Randeep Hooda]] shared the first look on his Twitter page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/randeep-hooda-battle-of-saragarhi-first-look-see-pic-2948244/|title=First look of Battle of Saragarhi out. Can you guess who is the actor?|date=1 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref> This film is to be directed by [[Rajkumar Santoshi]], starring Hooda, [[Vikramjeet Virk]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/news/17/jan/vikramjeet-virk-interview-bollywood-interviews.asp|title=Vikramjeet Virk: My character in ''Battle of Sarahragrahi'' is like 'Bhishma Pitamah'|website=glamsham.com}}</ref> and [[Danny Denzongpa]].<ref name=\"punemirror.indiatimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://punemirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/randeeps-battle-is-back-on-track/articleshow/61521850.cms|title=Randeep Hooda's next on Battle Of Saragarhi to kick off in Punjab next week, Danny Denzongpa joins cast|publisher=Pune Mirror}}</ref> The film was shelved after the release of ''Kesari''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/randeep-hooda-on-battle-of-saragarhi-it-hurt-that-the-audience-could-not-see-a-more-authentic-version/articleshow/74766159.cms|title=Randeep Hooda on Battle of Saragarhi: It hurt that the audience could not see a more authentic version|website=Mumbai Mirror}}</ref>\n* ''[[Kesari (film)|Kesari]]''. In March 2019, film titled ''Kesari'', based on the Battle of Saragarhi, directed by [[Anurag Singh (director)|Anurag Singh]], starring [[Akshay Kumar]], was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/article/akshay-kumar-karan-johar-proudly-present-new-film-kesari-based-on-battle-of-saragarhi/104992|title=Akshay Kumar, Karan Johar \u2018proudly present\u2019 new film Kesari, based on Battle of Saragarhi|first=|publisher=Times Now}}</ref> \nWith regards to speculation about multiple films being made about the battle, Hooda stated: \"It is good because there were 21 [[Sikh]] heroes in that battle and each one of them deserved to have a movie made on them. So actually there should be 21 films made on them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2017/mar/16/randeep-hooda-says--battle-of-saragarh-not-shelved-1581762.html|title=Randeep hooda says battle of saragarh not shelved|publisher=}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Saragarhi and the Defence of the Samana Forts'' by Amarinder Singh, New Delhi: Bookwise (India) Pvt. Ltd., 2017 {{ISBN|978-8187330677}}\n* ''Saragarhi: The Forgotten Battle'' by Jay Singh-Sohal, Birmingham: Dot Hyphen Publishers, 2013 ({{ISBN|978-0957054073}})\n* ''Saragarhi Battalion: Ashes to Glory'' by Kanwaljit Singh and H.S. Ahluwalia, New Delhi: Lancer International, 1987 ({{ISBN|81-7062-022-8}})\n* {{cite book |first=Anuj Harshwardhan |last=Sharma |year=2017 |title=Against All Odds at Saragarhi |url=https://www.amazon.in/dp/B077C94TXJ#reader_B077C94TXJ |location=New Delhi |publisher=Star Print-o-Bind |id=BO77C94TXJ (Amazon India) |via=Amazon |postscript=. A novel on the subject.}}\n* ''The Battle of Saragarhi, The Last Stand of the 36th Sikh Regiment'' by  Daljeet Singh Sidhu, Amarjit Virdi, Kindle Edition, 1st\nPublished December 2011 by Gyan Khand Media ({{ISBN13|9788190963749}})\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Saragarhi}}\n* [http://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armycampaigns/indiancampaigns/samana.htm Tirah: Samana (1897)], The British Empire (accessed 30 June 2019)\n* {{Cite news |last=Bhullar |first=Pritam |date=4 October 1998 |title=They Dared to Defy |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/1998/98oct04/sunday/head5.htm |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |location=Chandigarh, India |access-date=30 June 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saragarhi}}\n[[Category:1897 in Asia]]\n[[Category:Battles involving British India]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Sikhs]]\n[[Category:British Indian history]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1897]]\n[[Category:Last stand battles]]\n[[Category:Military history of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Military history of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category:Military of British India]]\n[[Category:September 1897 events]]\n[[Category:Tirah Campaign]]\n", "name_user": "Utcursch", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fix ref fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Saragarhi"}
{"title_page": "Polly Arnold", "text_new": "{{short description|British chemist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Polly Arnold\n| birth_name = Polly Louise Arnold\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1972|07|24}}<ref name=whoswho/>\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE|FRS|FRSE|FRSC}}\n| image = Polly Arnold Royal Society.jpg\n| caption = Polly Arnold at the [[Royal Society]] admissions day in London, July 2018\n| education = [[Notting Hill and Ealing High School]]<br>[[Westminster School]]\n| fields = [[Chemistry]]<ref name=gs/>\n| workplaces = {{plain list|\n* [[University of Nottingham]]\n* [[University of Edinburgh]]\n* [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] }}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Oxford]] (BA)<br />[[University of Sussex]] (DPhil)\n| thesis_url = https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.388646\n| thesis_year = 1997\n| thesis_title = Low valent and low co-ordinate complexes of transition metals and lanthanides\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Geoffrey Cloke]]<ref name=pphd/>\n| influences = {{plain list|\n* [[d:Q56256682|Dermot O'Hare]]\n* [[Matthew Rosseinsky]]\n* [[Christopher C. Cummins]] }}\n| awards = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Fulbright scholar]]\n* [[Rosalind Franklin Award]] (2012)\n* [[Corday-Morgan Prize]] (2012)}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.homepages.ed.ac.uk/parnold}}\n}}\n\n'''Polly Louise Arnold''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FRS|FRSE|FRSC}}<ref name=\"frs\">{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/polly-arnold-13795/|website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|author=Anon|year=2018|location=London|title=Professor Polly Arnold OBE FRS}} One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from the royalsociety.org website where: {{quote|\u201cAll text published under the heading 'Biography' on Fellow profile pages is available under [[Creative Commons license|Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License]].\u201d --{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111170346/https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies/|title=Royal Society Terms, conditions and policies|date=2016-11-11}}}}</ref> (born 24 July 1972) is a British chemist and academic. She is director of the chemical sciences division at [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]] and professor of chemistry at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chemistryworld.com/features/polly-arnolds-diversity-of-interests/4010778.article|title=Polly Arnold\u2019s diversity of interests|last=Chapman|first=Kit|date=13 January 2020|website=Chemistry World|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chemistry.berkeley.edu/faculty/chem/polly-arnold|title=Polly L. Arnold {{!}} College of Chemistry|website=chemistry.berkeley.edu|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> She previously held the [[Crum Brown]] Chair of [[Chemistry]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]] and an [[Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council]] (EPSRC) career [[fellow]]ship.<ref name=\"Dept\">{{cite web|title=Professor Polly L Arnold|url=http://www.chem.ed.ac.uk/staff/academic/arnold.html|publisher=University of Edinburgh|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=epsrc>{{cite web|url=https://epsrc.ukri.org/about/people/pollyarnold/|title=Polly Arnold - EPSRC website|website=epsrc.ukri.org}}</ref><ref name=gs>{{Google scholar id}}</ref><ref name=\"whoswho\">{{Who's Who | author=Anon| surname = Arnold | othernames = Prof. Polly Louise | id = U289559 | year = 2019 | doi = | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=orcid>Polly Arnold's {{ORCID}}</ref><ref name=epmc>{{EuropePMC|ORCID= 0000-0001-6410-5838}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nArnold was educated at [[Notting Hill and Ealing High School]] and [[Westminster School]].<ref name=whoswho/> She studied chemistry at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]] (BA) and worked with {{ill|Dermot O\u2019Hare|WD=Q56256682|reasonator=1}} and [[Matthew Rosseinsky]].<ref name=epsrc/> She moved to the [[University of Sussex]] for postgraduate research where her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree was supervised by [[Geoffrey Cloke]].<ref name=pphd>{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=University of Sussex|url=https://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/42697012?style=html|title=Low valent and low co-ordinate complexes of transition metals and lanthanides|first= Polly Louise|last=Arnold|date=1997|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.388646}}|website=jisc.ac.uk|oclc=53644787}}</ref><ref name=epsrc/>\n\n== Research and career==\nArnold's research focuses on exploratory synthetic chemistry, particularly in making complexes that exhibit unusual structure-bonding in early transition metal, and [[lanthanide]] and [[Actinide|actinide chemistry]]. Such knowledge underpins the discovery of catalysts and our understanding of the behaviour of [[nuclear waste]].<ref name=\"FurnoMorley2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Furno|first1=Franck|last2=Morley|first2=Kelly S.|last3=Wong|first3=Ben|last4=Sharp|first4=Barry L.|last5=Arnold|first5=Polly L.|last6=Howdle|first6=Steven M.|last7=Bayston|first7=Roger|last8=Brown|first8=Paul D.|last9=Winship|first9=Peter D.|last10=Reid|first10=Helen J.|title=Silver nanoparticles and polymeric medical devices: a new approach to prevention of infection?|journal=Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy|volume=54|issue=6|year=2004|pages=1019\u20131024|issn=1460-2091|doi=10.1093/jac/dkh478|pmid=15537697|doi-access=free}} {{free access}}</ref><ref name=Dept />\n[[File:DEHHEF.png|thumb|left|Structure of C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>6</sub>[U(Ntms<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub>]<sub>2</sub> from Arnold's lab<ref>{{cite journal|authors=P. L. Arnold, S.M. Mansell, L. Maron, D. McKay|title=Spontaneous reduction and C\u2013H borylation of arenes mediated by uranium(III) disproportionation|journal=Nature Chemistry|year=2012|volume=4|issue=8|page=668|doi=10.1038/nchem.1392|pmid=22824900|hdl=20.500.11820/387cd4f7-3c63-466b-b017-f87f6a345ee1|hdl-access=free}} {{closed access}}</ref>]]\n\nArnold was a [[Fulbright Program]] [[postdoctoral]] fellow at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) where she worked with [[Christopher C. Cummins]] before returning to the UK to a lectureship in 1999.<ref name=frs/> Her research is focused on the design and synthesis of highly reactive f-block complexes that can activate inert small molecules such as [[carbon oxide]]s, [[dinitrogen]], and [[hydrocarbon]]s, and that can provide fundamental information on structure and bonding at the bottom of the [[periodic table]].<ref name=frs/><ref name=\"ArnoldPearson2007\">{{cite journal|last1=Arnold|first1=Polly L.|last2=Pearson|first2=Stephen|title=Abnormal N-heterocyclic carbenes|journal=Coordination Chemistry Reviews|volume=251|issue=5\u20136|year=2007|pages=596\u2013609|issn=0010-8545|doi=10.1016/j.ccr.2006.08.006}} {{closed access}}</ref><ref name=\"ArnoldCasely2009\">{{cite journal|last1=Arnold|first1=Polly L.|last2=Casely|first2=Ian J.|title=F-Block N-Heterocyclic Carbene Complexes|journal=Chemical Reviews|volume=109|issue=8|year=2009|pages=3599\u20133611|issn=0009-2665|doi=10.1021/cr8005203}} {{closed access}}</ref><ref name=\"LiddleEdworthy2007\">{{cite journal|last1=Liddle|first1=Stephen T.|last2=Edworthy|first2=Ian S.|last3=Arnold|first3=Polly L.|title=Anionic tethered N-heterocyclic carbene chemistry|journal=Chemical Society Reviews|volume=36|issue=11|year=2007|pages=1732|issn=0306-0012|doi=10.1039/b611548a}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\nArnold has given lectures around the world, advised the government and industry, and appears regularly on [[mainstream media]] and [[social media]]<ref name=twitter>{{Twitter}}</ref> to discuss the importance and benefits of diversity in the [[Science, technology, engineering and mathematics|science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] (STEM) workforce.<ref name=frs/>\n \n=== Awards and honours ===\nArnold was awarded [[Rosalind Franklin Award]] in 2012 for her scientific achievements, and her suitability as a role model and proposal to promote women in STEM.<ref name=balance>{{cite web|title=A Chemical Imbalance|first=Polly|last=Arnold|year=2012|website=chemicalimbalance.ed.ac.uk|url=http://chemicalimbalance.co.uk/prof-polly-arnold/|publisher=RSE/University of Edinburgh|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> This award was used to fund the creation of the documentary film ''A Chemical Imbalance,'' where she is the executive producer.<ref name=balance/> That same year, she was also awarded the Royal Society of Chemistry's [[Corday-Morgan Prize]] for her \"outstanding contributions to the application of organometallic uranium chemistry to small molecule activation\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/ScienceAndTechnology/Awards/CordayMorganPrizes/2012-Winner-Arnold.asp|title=Corday-Morgan Prize 2012 Winner|website=rsc.org|access-date=2018-12-16}}</ref> In 2012 she was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (FRSE).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rse.org.uk/fellow/polly-arnold/|title=Professor Polly Louise Arnold OBE, FRSE|publisher=[[Royal Society of Edinburgh]]|website=rse.org.uk|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nShe was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2017 Birthday Honours]] for services to chemistry and women in STEM.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61962|supp=y|page=B10|date=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she was awarded the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] (RSC) Sir Geoffrey Wilkinson award for her work on transuranic organometallic chemistry, and is so far, the only woman to have been awarded this award since its inception in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/ScienceAndTechnology/Awards/SirGeoffreyWilkinsonAward/2018-Winner.asp|title=RSC Sir Geoffrey Wilkinson Award 2018 Winner|website=rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref> She was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) in 2018.<ref name=frs/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n{{Rosalind Franklin Award Laureates}}\n{{FRS 2018}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arnold, Polly}}\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:British chemists]]\n[[Category:British women chemists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Female Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Notting Hill & Ealing High School]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British chemist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Polly Arnold\n| birth_name = Polly Louise Arnold\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1972|07|24}}<ref name=whoswho/>\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE|FRS|FRSE|FRSC}}\n| image = Polly Arnold Royal Society.jpg\n| caption = Polly Arnold at the [[Royal Society]] admissions day in London, July 2018\n| education = [[Notting Hill and Ealing High School]]<br>[[Westminster School]]\n| fields = [[Chemistry]]<ref name=gs/>\n| workplaces = {{plain list|\n* [[University of Nottingham]]\n* [[University of Edinburgh]]\n* [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] }}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Oxford]] (BA)<br />[[University of Sussex]] (DPhil)\n| thesis_url = https://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.388646\n| thesis_year = 1997\n| thesis_title = Low valent and low co-ordinate complexes of transition metals and lanthanides\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Geoffrey Cloke]]<ref name=pphd/>\n| influences = {{plain list|\n* [[d:Q56256682|Dermot O'Hare]]\n* [[Matthew Rosseinsky]]\n* [[Christopher C. Cummins]] }}\n| awards = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Fulbright scholar]]\n* [[Rosalind Franklin Award]] (2012)\n* [[Corday-Morgan Prize]] (2012)}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.homepages.ed.ac.uk/parnold}}\n}}\n\n'''Polly Louise Arnold''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FRS|FRSE|FRSC}}<ref name=\"frs\">{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/polly-arnold-13795/|website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|author=Anon|year=2018|location=London|title=Professor Polly Arnold OBE FRS}} One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from the royalsociety.org website where: {{quote|\u201cAll text published under the heading 'Biography' on Fellow profile pages is available under [[Creative Commons license|Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License]].\u201d --{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111170346/https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies/|title=Royal Society Terms, conditions and policies|date=2016-11-11}}}}</nowiki></ref> (born 24 July 1972) is a British chemist and academic. She is director of the chemical sciences division at [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]] and professor of chemistry at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chemistryworld.com/features/polly-arnolds-diversity-of-interests/4010778.article|title=Polly Arnold\u2019s diversity of interests|last=Chapman|first=Kit|date=13 January 2020|website=Chemistry World|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chemistry.berkeley.edu/faculty/chem/polly-arnold|title=Polly L. Arnold {{!}} College of Chemistry|website=chemistry.berkeley.edu|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> She previously held the [[Crum Brown]] Chair of [[Chemistry]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]] and an [[Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council]] (EPSRC) career [[fellow]]ship.<ref name=\"Dept\">{{cite web|title=Professor Polly L Arnold|url=http://www.chem.ed.ac.uk/staff/academic/arnold.html|publisher=University of Edinburgh|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=epsrc>{{cite web|url=https://epsrc.ukri.org/about/people/pollyarnold/|title=Polly Arnold - EPSRC website|website=epsrc.ukri.org}}</ref><ref name=gs>{{Google scholar id}}</ref><ref name=\"whoswho\">{{Who's Who | author=Anon| surname = Arnold | othernames = Prof. Polly Louise | id = U289559 | year = 2019 | doi = | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=orcid>Polly Arnold's {{ORCID}}</ref><ref name=epmc>{{EuropePMC|ORCID= 0000-0001-6410-5838}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nArnold was educated at [[Notting Hill and Ealing High School]] and [[Westminster School]].<ref name=whoswho/> She studied chemistry at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]] (BA) and worked with {{ill|Dermot O\u2019Hare|WD=Q56256682|reasonator=1}} and [[Matthew Rosseinsky]].<ref name=epsrc/> She moved to the [[University of Sussex]] for postgraduate research where her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree was supervised by [[Geoffrey Cloke]].<ref name=pphd>{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=University of Sussex|url=https://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/42697012?style=html|title=Low valent and low co-ordinate complexes of transition metals and lanthanides|first= Polly Louise|last=Arnold|date=1997|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.388646}}|website=jisc.ac.uk|oclc=53644787}}</ref><ref name=epsrc/>\n\n== Research and career==\nArnold's research focuses on exploratory synthetic chemistry, particularly in making complexes that exhibit unusual structure-bonding in early transition metal, and [[lanthanide]] and [[Actinide|actinide chemistry]]. Such knowledge underpins the discovery of catalysts and our understanding of the behaviour of [[nuclear waste]].<ref name=\"FurnoMorley2004\">{{cite journal|last1=Furno|first1=Franck|last2=Morley|first2=Kelly S.|last3=Wong|first3=Ben|last4=Sharp|first4=Barry L.|last5=Arnold|first5=Polly L.|last6=Howdle|first6=Steven M.|last7=Bayston|first7=Roger|last8=Brown|first8=Paul D.|last9=Winship|first9=Peter D.|last10=Reid|first10=Helen J.|title=Silver nanoparticles and polymeric medical devices: a new approach to prevention of infection?|journal=Journal of Antimicrobial Chemotherapy|volume=54|issue=6|year=2004|pages=1019\u20131024|issn=1460-2091|doi=10.1093/jac/dkh478|pmid=15537697|doi-access=free}} {{free access}}</ref><ref name=Dept />\n[[File:DEHHEF.png|thumb|left|Structure of C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>6</sub>[U(Ntms<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub>]<sub>2</sub> from Arnold's lab.<ref>{{cite journal|authors=P. L. Arnold, S.M. Mansell, L. Maron, D. McKay|title=Spontaneous reduction and C\u2013H borylation of arenes mediated by uranium(III) disproportionation|journal=Nature Chemistry|year=2012|volume=4|issue=8|page=668|doi=10.1038/nchem.1392|pmid=22824900|hdl=20.500.11820/387cd4f7-3c63-466b-b017-f87f6a345ee1|hdl-access=free}} {{closed access}}</ref>]]\n\nArnold was a [[Fulbright Program]] [[postdoctoral]] fellow at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) where she worked with [[Christopher C. Cummins]] before returning to the UK to a lectureship in 1999.<ref name=frs/> Her research is focused on the design and synthesis of highly reactive f-block complexes that can activate inert small molecules such as [[carbon oxide]]s, [[dinitrogen]], and [[hydrocarbon]]s, and that can provide fundamental information on structure and bonding at the bottom of the [[periodic table]].<ref name=frs/><ref name=\"ArnoldPearson2007\">{{cite journal|last1=Arnold|first1=Polly L.|last2=Pearson|first2=Stephen|title=Abnormal N-heterocyclic carbenes|journal=Coordination Chemistry Reviews|volume=251|issue=5\u20136|year=2007|pages=596\u2013609|issn=0010-8545|doi=10.1016/j.ccr.2006.08.006}} {{closed access}}</ref><ref name=\"ArnoldCasely2009\">{{cite journal|last1=Arnold|first1=Polly L.|last2=Casely|first2=Ian J.|title=F-Block N-Heterocyclic Carbene Complexes|journal=Chemical Reviews|volume=109|issue=8|year=2009|pages=3599\u20133611|issn=0009-2665|doi=10.1021/cr8005203}} {{closed access}}</ref><ref name=\"LiddleEdworthy2007\">{{cite journal|last1=Liddle|first1=Stephen T.|last2=Edworthy|first2=Ian S.|last3=Arnold|first3=Polly L.|title=Anionic tethered N-heterocyclic carbene chemistry|journal=Chemical Society Reviews|volume=36|issue=11|year=2007|pages=1732|issn=0306-0012|doi=10.1039/b611548a}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n\nArnold has given lectures around the world, advised the government and industry, and appears regularly on [[mainstream media]] and [[social media]]<ref name=twitter>{{Twitter}}</ref> to discuss the importance and benefits of diversity in the [[Science, technology, engineering and mathematics|science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] (STEM) workforce.<ref name=frs/>\n \n=== Awards and honours ===\nArnold was awarded [[Rosalind Franklin Award]] in 2012 for her scientific achievements, and her suitability as a role model and proposal to promote women in STEM.<ref name=balance>{{cite web|title=A Chemical Imbalance|first=Polly|last=Arnold|year=2012|website=chemicalimbalance.ed.ac.uk|url=http://chemicalimbalance.co.uk/prof-polly-arnold/|publisher=RSE/University of Edinburgh|accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> This award was used to fund the creation of the documentary film ''A Chemical Imbalance,'' where she is the executive producer.<ref name=balance/> That same year, she was also awarded the Royal Society of Chemistry's [[Corday-Morgan Prize]] for her \"outstanding contributions to the application of organometallic uranium chemistry to small molecule activation\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/ScienceAndTechnology/Awards/CordayMorganPrizes/2012-Winner-Arnold.asp|title=Corday-Morgan Prize 2012 Winner|website=rsc.org|access-date=2018-12-16}}</ref> In 2012 she was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]] (FRSE).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rse.org.uk/fellow/polly-arnold/|title=Professor Polly Louise Arnold OBE, FRSE|publisher=[[Royal Society of Edinburgh]]|website=rse.org.uk|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nShe was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2017 Birthday Honours]] for services to chemistry and women in STEM.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61962|supp=y|page=B10|date=17 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she was awarded the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] (RSC) Sir Geoffrey Wilkinson award for her work on transuranic organometallic chemistry, and is so far, the only woman to have been awarded this award since its inception in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/ScienceAndTechnology/Awards/SirGeoffreyWilkinsonAward/2018-Winner.asp|title=RSC Sir Geoffrey Wilkinson Award 2018 Winner|website=rsc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref> She was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) in 2018.<ref name=frs/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n{{Rosalind Franklin Award Laureates}}\n{{FRS 2018}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arnold, Polly}}\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:British chemists]]\n[[Category:British women chemists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:LGBT scientists from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Female Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Notting Hill & Ealing High School]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n", "name_user": "Jessicapierce", "label": "safe"