{"title_page": "Vladeck Houses", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Public housing development in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{coord|40.7125|N|73.9817|W|display=title}}\n[[File:Nychales.JPG|thumb|right|Vladeck Houses is the group of six-story buildings in the foreground.]]\n'''Vladeck Houses''' is a [[public housing in the United States|public housing development]] built and maintained by the [[New York City Housing Authority]] on the [[Lower East Side]] of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"nychapage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/developments/manvladeck.shtml|title=Vladeck|work=NYCHA Housing Developments|publisher=New York City Housing Authority|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref>  The development is named after [[Baruch Charney Vladeck]] (1886 - 1938), who was general manager of ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]'', a [[Yiddish language]] newspaper, helped found the [[Jewish Labor Committee]] in 1934, served as its first president, and was a member of the original board of the New York City Housing Authority.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />\n\nBaruch Charney Vladeck Houses is made up of 20 six-story buildings on {{convert|13|acres}}, in which there are 1,523 apartments housing approximately 2,850 people.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />   This complex is bordered by [[Madison St. (Manhattan)|Madison Street]] to its north, Water Street to its south, Gouverneur Street to its west, and Jackson Street to its east.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />  Construction began September 10, 1939, and was finished November 20, 1940.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/about/nycha70_timeline.shtml|title=Timeline|work=About NYCHA|publisher=New York City Housing Authority|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603120749/http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/about/nycha70_timeline.shtml|archive-date=3 June 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nychapage\" />\n\nBaruch Charney Vladeck II Houses consists of 4 six-story buildings on {{convert|2.23|acres}}, in which there are 238 apartments housing approximately 445 people.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />  This complex is bordered by [[Madison Street (Manhattan)|Madison Street]] to its north, [[Cherry Street (Manhattan)|Cherry Street]] to its south, and Jackson Street to its west.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />  Construction began September 10, 1939, and was finished October 25, 1940.<ref name=\"timeline\" /><ref name=\"nychapage\" />\n\nNo one is currently serving as the Resident Association President for Vladeck Houses.<ref name=\"corner\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/residents/manhattanS_ccop.shtml|title=Manhattan South District CCOP Office|work=Residents' Corner|publisher=New York City Housing Authority|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nSince it is on the Lower East Side, Vladeck Houses is serviced by the [[New York Police Department]]'s [[PSA 4]] and is governed by [[Manhattan Community Board 3]].<ref name=\"police\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/html/precincts/precinct_007.shtml|title=NYPD-Precincts|work=Precincts|publisher=New York Police Department|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref><ref name=\"PSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/transit-housing/police-service-area-4.page}}</ref><ref name=\"cb3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/mancb3/html/home/home.shtml|title=Community Board No. 3, Manhattan|work=nyc.gov|publisher=City of New York|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public housing in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings completed in 1940]]\n[[Category:Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings in Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Public housing development in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{coord|40.7125|N|73.9817|W|display=title}}\n[[File:Nychales.JPG|thumb|right|Vladeck Houses is the group of six-story buildings in the foreground.]]\n'''Vladeck Houses''' is a [[public housing in the United States|public housing development]] built and maintained by the [[New York City Housing Authority]] on the [[Lower East Side]] of [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"nychapage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/developments/manvladeck.shtml|title=Vladeck|work=NYCHA Housing Developments|publisher=New York City Housing Authority|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref>  The development is named after [[Baruch Charney Vladeck]] (1886 - 1938), who was general manager of ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]'', a [[Yiddish language]] newspaper, helped found the [[Jewish Labor Committee]] in 1934, served as its first president, and was a member of the original board of the New York City Housing Authority.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />\n\nBaruch Charney Vladeck Houses is made up of 20 six-story buildings on {{convert|13|acres}}, in which there are 1,523 apartments housing approximately 2,850 people.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />   This complex is bordered by [[Madison St. (Manhattan] to its north, Water Street to its south, Gouverneur Street to its west, and Jackson Street to its east.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />  Construction began September 10, 1939, and was finished November 20, 1940.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/about/nycha70_timeline.shtml|title=Timeline|work=About NYCHA|publisher=New York City Housing Authority|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100603120749/http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/about/nycha70_timeline.shtml|archive-date=3 June 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nychapage\" />\n\nBaruch Charney Vladeck II Houses consists of 4 six-story buildings on {{convert|2.23|acres}}, in which there are 238 apartments housing approximately 445 people.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />  This complex is bordered by [[Madison Street (Manhattan)|Madison Street]] to its north, [[Cherry Street (Manhattan)|Cherry Street]] to its south, and Jackson Street to its west.<ref name=\"nychapage\" />  Construction began September 10, 1939, and was finished October 25, 1940.<ref name=\"timeline\" /><ref name=\"nychapage\" />\n\nNo one is currently serving as the Resident Association President for Vladeck Houses.<ref name=\"corner\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nycha/html/residents/manhattanS_ccop.shtml|title=Manhattan South District CCOP Office|work=Residents' Corner|publisher=New York City Housing Authority|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nSince it is on the Lower East Side, Vladeck Houses is serviced by the [[New York Police Department]]'s [[PSA 4]] and is governed by [[Manhattan Community Board 3]].<ref name=\"police\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/nypd/html/precincts/precinct_007.shtml|title=NYPD-Precincts|work=Precincts|publisher=New York Police Department|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref><ref name=\"PSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nypd/bureaus/transit-housing/police-service-area-4.page}}</ref><ref name=\"cb3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/mancb3/html/home/home.shtml|title=Community Board No. 3, Manhattan|work=nyc.gov|publisher=City of New York|accessdate=17 January 2010|location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public housing in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings completed in 1940]]\n[[Category:Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:Residential buildings in Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "Kingsocarso", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladeck_Houses"}
{"title_page": "Hindi Medium", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|2017 film directed by Saket Chaudhary}}\n{{about|the film|the language educational policy in India|National Policy on Education}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Hindi Medium\n| image          = Hindi Medium poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = Two persons dressed in two different styles.\n| director       = [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| producer       = [[Dinesh Vijan]]<br />[[Bhushan Kumar]]\n| writer         = Saket Chaudhary<br />Zeenat Lakhani\n| starring       = [[Irrfan Khan]]<br />[[Saba Qamar]]\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n*'''Songs:'''\n*[[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n*'''Background score:'''\n*[[Amar Mohile]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Laxman Utekar]]\n| editing        = [[A. Sreekar Prasad]]\n| studio         = [[Maddock Films]]<br />[[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| distributor    = [[AA Films]] (India)<br />[[Zee Studios]] (Overseas)\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|5|19|India|2018|4|4|China|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/hindi-medium-film|title=Hindi Medium|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=15 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715085241/https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/hindi-medium-film|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INRConvert|14|c|year=2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-hindi-medium-clocks-22-crores-102-profit/|title=Box Office: Hindi Medium clocks 22 crores and 102% as profit|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924203809/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-hindi-medium-clocks-22-crores-102-profit/|archivedate=24 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = <!--Do not remove-->{{Estimation}}<!--per WT:ICTF consensus--> {{INRConvert|322.4|c|year=2017}} <ref name=\"gross\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/box-office/|title=Hindi Medium Box Office Collection till Now|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715091530/https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/box-office/?movieid=3526|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Hindi Medium''''' is a 2017 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Saket Chaudhary]]. It was produced by [[Dinesh Vijan]] and [[Bhushan Kumar]] under their respective banners [[Maddock Films]] and [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]. The film features [[Irrfan Khan]] and [[Saba Qamar]] in the lead roles, with [[Deepak Dobriyal]] and Dishita Sehgal in supporting roles. Set in Delhi, the plot centres on a couple's struggle to get their daughter admitted to a prestigious [[English-medium education|English-medium]] school in order to rise in society.\n\nThe idea for the film was created by Chaudhary and his co-writer Zeenat Lakhani during the development of his previous film ''[[Shaadi Ke Side Effects]]'' (2014). The film was shot in [[Chandni Chowk]], [[Anand Lok, Jaipur|Anand Lok]], [[Karol Bagh]], and Sangam Vihar. The film's [[soundtrack album]] was composed by the duo [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]], with lyrics by [[Priya Saraiya]] and [[Kumaar]]. The [[Film score|score]] was composed by [[Amar Mohile]]. [[Laxman Utekar]] was the [[Cinematography|cinematographer]], and [[A. Sreekar Prasad]] edited the film.\n\nMade on a [[production budget]] of {{\u20b9|14|link=yes}} [[crore]], ''Hindi Medium'' released on 19 May 2017, and received a generally positive reception from the critics, with particular praise for Khan's and Qamar's performances. The film grossed {{INRConvert|322.4|c}} at the worldwide box office, with a large amount coming from China, becoming one of the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films]] of all time. At the [[63rd Filmfare Awards]], it won [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]], and [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Khan. Due to the success of the film, a spiritual successor, ''[[Angrezi Medium]]'', directed by [[Homi Adajania]], went into development, and was released theatrically on 13 March 2020.\n\n==Plot==\nRaj Batra ([[Irrfan Khan]]) is a boutique owner who lives in [[Connaught Place, New Delhi|Connaught Place, Delhi]], with his wife Mita ([[Saba Qamar]]) and 5-year-old daughter, Pia (Dishita Sehgal). The couple want Pia to be admitted to a prestigious English-medium school in Delhi as they feel that this will enable her to become a part of the elite of society. After browsing through some luxurious hotel-like schools, they zero in on the Delhi Grammar School, ranked the best in the city, but it stipulates that students must stay within a 3-km radius of the school. \n\nThey move to a posh villa in Delhi's upscale [[Vasant Vihar, Delhi|Vasant Vihar]] neighbourhood and try to befriend the neighbours, but face limited success as their (particularly Raj's) gaucheness holds them back. They are introduced to a consultant, Shikha ([[Tillotama Shome]]), who is largely cynical and disparaging of the couple for their flashiness, but nevertheless helps them to prepare for the interview required for admission to various top schools. However, Raj and Mita fail to deliver their tutored answers in the interview, and their application gets rejected due to their limited knowledge of English. \n\nRaj and Mita learn from an employee that his daughter has been admitted through the [[Right to education|Right To Education]] (RTE) quota, a scheme that helps children from poor families to be admitted to prestigious schools. Through a fixer, Raj gets fake certificates and proofs of an address in Bharat Nagar, a slum area of the city. They decide to apply for Pia's admission through that scheme. However, a scam soon surfaces in which it is revealed that rich parents pose as paupers to get their children admitted through the RTE quota. So, after telling their snooty neighbours that they are going on a Europe trip, the Batras move to a dilapidated home in Bharat Nagar for a month and pretend to be impoverished. They strike a friendship with Shyam ([[Deepak Dobriyal]]) and Tulsi (Swati Das), who are hopeful that their son Mohan (Angshuman Nandi) gets to study in Delhi Grammar School through the RTE quota.\n\nWhen school officials come to Bharat Nagar to investigate, they are surprised that the Batras do not seem to be as poor as their appearances would suggest, but Shyam covers up for Raj, saying that they were reduced to penury due to a factory fire. Shyam and Tulsi teach them to live like poor people. Raj accompanies Shyam to work at a food manufacturing plant, while Mita slowly learns to fight for her share of daily needs. The Batras and Shyam's family are hopeful that their children will get admission through random selection; however, while Pia eventually gets admission, Mohan's application is rejected. \n\nThe Batras return to Vasant Vihar. Raj and Mita make a donation to the Bharat Nagar Government School, where Mohan studies, to renovate it and get new books. After watching their son become fluent in English, Shyam and Tulsi search for the identity of the anonymous donor to thank them. However, when he visits the donor's address in Vasant Vihar, Shyam is astonished to see Raj. He finds out the truth about Raj pretending to be poor to enable Pia's admission and leaves to tell Delhi Grammar School's principal ([[Amrita Singh]]) of Raj's deceit.\n\nRaj and Mita rush to Delhi Grammar school to get there before Shyam. Raj asks for Pia's admission to be revoked and tells the truth. The principal rejects doing so, and simply asks him to take his seat in the annual day performance in the auditorium. After some children perform a song-and-dance routine, he gatecrashes the function, reveals they are actually from the Bharat Nagar government school, gives a speech about English in India and education rights, and leaves. On their way out, the Batras bump into the principal of the government school and tell him that they plan to admit their daughter Pia to his school to study with Mohan, which he is only too happy to accept.\n\n==Cast==\nCredits adapted from [[Bollywood Hungama]]:<ref name=\"Hindi Medium Cast & Crew\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/cast/|title=Hindi Medium Cast & Crew|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715091657/https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/cast/?movieid=3526|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n* [[Irrfan Khan]] as Raj Batra\n** Delzad Hiwale as young Raj\n* [[Saba Qamar]] as Mita Batra\n** [[Sanjana Sanghi]] as young Mita\n* Kiran Khoje as Sushila\n* Dishita Sehgal as Pia Batra\n* [[Amrita Singh]] as Principal Lodha\n* [[Deepak Dobriyal]] as Shyam Prakash\n* [[Neelu Kohli]] as Mita's mother\n* Rajeev Gupta as Masterji, Raj's father\n* [[Sumit Gulati]] as Chotu\n* [[Mallika Dua]] as Dolly\n* Kulbir Kaur as Dolly's mother\n* Charu Shankar as Maya\n* [[Tillotama Shome]] as Shikha, a consultant\n* [[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]] as MLA\n* [[Taran Bajaj]] as tout\n* [[Ankur Jain]] as news reader\n* Swati Das as Tulsi\n* [[Neha Dhupia]] as Aarti (special appearance)\n* [[Sanjay Suri]] as Kabir (special appearance)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nMade on a production budget of {{\u20b9|14}} crore, ''Hindi Medium'' was produced by Vijan of Maddock Films and Bhushan Kumar of T-Series. The film was directed by Chaudhary, his third after [[romantic comedy]] films ''[[Pyaar Ke Side Effects]]'' (2006) and ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects''. He came up with the idea of making a film about [[Education in India|India's education system]] with his co-writer Zeenat Lakhani during the development of the latter film. They found the idea too extensive to include in ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects'', so after its release, they decided to incorporate the idea into a separate film. Stating the reason to make ''Hindi Medium'', Chaudhary said, \"The subject is so relevant. We realised that today irrespective of the background of the parent, they still want to have the best education for the children.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/saket-chaudhary-irrfan-khan-is-not-a-pretentious-actor/articleshow/58295973.cms|title=Saket Chaudhary: Irrfan Khan is not a pretentious actor|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715091827/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/saket-chaudhary-irrfan-khan-is-not-a-pretentious-actor/articleshow/58295973.cms|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPre-production work began after the release of ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects''. Chaudhary began working on the story at that time, and he chose Delhi as the film's key location.<ref name=\"Pic: Irrfan Khan flaunts his saree draping skills for Hindi Medium!\">{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/270317/pic-irrfan-khan-flaunts-his-saree-draping-skills-for-hindi-medium.html|title=Pic: Irrfan Khan flaunts his saree draping skills for Hindi Medium!|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511150725/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/270317/pic-irrfan-khan-flaunts-his-saree-draping-skills-for-hindi-medium.html|archivedate=11 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The production crew consisted primarily of people Chaudhary had worked with on ''Pyaar Ke Side Effects'' and ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects'', with the exception of [[production designer]] Mustafa Stationwala\u2014they are editor A. Sreekar Prasad; dialogue writer [[Amitosh Nagpal]]; and cinematographer Laxman Utekar. The score was composed by Amar Mohile.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium Cast & Crew\"/>\n\n[[File:Irrfan Khan May 2015.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A man standing and looking at the camera|It was Khan's choice to cast Qamar in the film]]\nOn 29 May 2016, [[CNN-News18|News18]] reported the casting of [[Saba Qamar]] in the film, which marked her Bollywood debut.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/hindi-medium-irrfan-sabas-unusual-pairing-looks-interesting-1249164.html|title='Hindi Medium' First Look: Irrfan Khan, Saba Qamar's Unusual Pairing Looks Interesting|publisher=[[CNN-News18|News18]]|date=29 May 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116204744/https://www.news18.com/news/movies/hindi-medium-irrfan-sabas-unusual-pairing-looks-interesting-1249164.html|archivedate=16 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Khan had recommended the casting of Qamar to the makers of the film. He said, \"When I saw her YouTube videos, I recommended her to the director and producer and they really liked her\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.samaa.tv/culture/2017/05/youll-never-believe-how-saba-qamar-was-picked-for-hindi-medium/|title=You\u2019ll never believe how Saba Qamar was picked for 'Hindi Medium'|publisher=[[Samaa TV]]|date=16 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715092309/https://www.samaa.tv/culture/2017/05/youll-never-believe-how-saba-qamar-was-picked-for-hindi-medium/|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Speaking about her role, Qamar said, \"I play a person who didn't get an opportunity to fulfil her dreams so she comes up with a scheme about giving the daughter a life that she didn't have\".\nKhan commented that he had accepted the role as it tackled the realistic subject of the challenges of obtaining a good education in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/saba-qamar-and-irrfan-khan-talk-hindi-medium-1.2030834|title=Saba Qamar and Irrfan Khan talk 'Hindi Medium'|newspaper=[[Gulf News]]|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715092428/https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/saba-qamar-and-irrfan-khan-talk-hindi-medium-1.2030834|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nQamar arrived in Mumbai from Pakistan in July 2016, and the film's principal photography began in the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/050716/meet-bollywood-towns-new-guest-from-across-the-border.html|title=Meet Bollywood's new guest from across the border|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414150446/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/050716/meet-bollywood-towns-new-guest-from-across-the-border.html|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1175120|title=My Bollywood debut film is a little like Piku, says Saba Qamar|newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|date=7 April 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903134248/https://images.dawn.com/news/1175120|archivedate=3 September 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was shot in Chandni Chowk, Anand Lok, Karol Bagh, and Sangam Vihar.<ref name=\"Pic: Irrfan Khan flaunts his saree draping skills for Hindi Medium!\"/> The shooting was completed in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/irrfan-khan-film-not-stalled-says-spokesperson-1.1914660|title=Irrfan Khan film not stalled, says spokesperson|newspaper=Gulf News|date=18 October 2016|accessdate=20 November 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120174109/https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/irrfan-khan-film-not-stalled-says-spokesperson-1.1914660|archivedate=20 November 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A song sequence was also filmed in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/irrfan-khan-shoots-in-georgia-for-hindi-medium-117032700317_1.html|title=Irrfan Khan shoots in Georgia for 'Hindi Medium'|newspaper=Business Standard|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329223505/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/irrfan-khan-shoots-in-georgia-for-hindi-medium-117032700317_1.html|archivedate=29 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Qamar commented that she enjoyed working with Khan, and felt safe while shooting in Delhi. In the same interview with Pakistani newspaper ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', she commented that her experience wasn't affected by the nationalist far-right political party [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]]'s hostility towards Pakistan at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1176400/did-you-know-saba-qamar-just-wrapped-up-her-bollywood-debut-in-delhi|title=Did you know? Saba Qamar just wrapped up her Bollywood debut in Delhi|newspaper=Dawn|date=12 October 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004022219/https://images.dawn.com/news/1176400/did-you-know-saba-qamar-just-wrapped-up-her-bollywood-debut-in-delhi|archivedate=4 October 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hindi Medium\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 21 April 2017\n| recorded   = 2016\u20132017\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 21:20\n| label      = [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Meri Pyaari Bindu]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[A Gentleman]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc = {{External media\n| audio1     = {{YouTube|C6AKnuySrHU|Official Audio Jukebox}}}}\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack consists of four compositions \u2014 two original: \"Hoor\" and \"Ek Jindari\", and two recreated: \"Suit Suit\" and \"Oh Ho Ho Ho\". Sachin\u2013Jigar has composed the original songs. \"Suit Suit\", the first song, is written and sung by [[Guru Randhawa]] and [[Arjun (singer)|Arjun]] and composed by Randhawa and [[Rajat Nagpal]]. The second track \"Hoor\" was composed by Sachin\u2013Jigar and sung by [[Atif Aslam]] with lyrics by Priya Saraiya. The track \"Oh Ho Ho Ho\", was composed by [[Sukhbir (musician)|Sukhbir]] and [[Abhijit Vaghani]], sung by Sukhbir, rapped by [[Ikka Singh]] and written by Kumaar. The fourth, \"Ek Jindari\" was written by Kumaar and composed by Sachin\u2013Jigar. It was sung by Taniskaa Sanghvi. The album rights of the film were acquired by T-Series, and it was released on 21 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tseries.com/music/hindi-medium-0|title=Hindi Medium \u2013 Music|publisher=[[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927171841/http://www.tseries.com/music/hindi-medium-0|archivedate=27 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Hindi Medium Music Review\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nJoginder Tuteja of Bollywood Hungama, rated the album a 3 out of 5 stars. He said that \"the music of ''Hindi Medium'' turns out to be better than expected\", and praised the inclusion of recreations of \"Suit Suit\" and \"Oh Ho Ho Ho\" as they were previously popular Punjabi songs.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium Music Review\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/songs/music-critic-review/|title=Hindi Medium Music Review|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213045935/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/songs/music-critic-review/|archivedate=13 December 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> V. Lakshmi of ''[[The Times of India]]'' in a positive review of the album said that, \"by the time the album ends, the listeners are left humming the tunes!\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/album-review-hindi-medium/articleshow/58398794.cms|title=Album Review: Hindi Medium|newspaper=The Times of India|date=28 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517164133/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/album-review-hindi-medium/articleshow/58398794.cms|archivedate=17 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Suanshu Khurana of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' highlighted the song \"Hoor\" as the best song on the album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/hindi-medium-music-review-arjun-kanungo-4642660/|title=Winning Formula|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=6 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707205547/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/hindi-medium-music-review-arjun-kanungo-4642660/|archivedate=7 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 15:43\n| headline= Track listing\n| title1 = Suit Suit\n| extra1 = Guru Randhawa, Arjun\n| lyrics1 = [[Guru Randhawa]], [[Arjun (singer)|Arjun]]\n| music1 = Guru Randhawa, [[Rajat Nagpal]],\n| length1 = 3:10\n| title2 = Hoor\n| extra2 = [[Atif Aslam]]\n| lyrics2 = [[Priya Saraiya]]\n| music2 = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| length2 = 3:57\n| title3 = Oh Ho Ho Ho (Remix)\n| extra3 = Sukhbir\n| lyrics3 = [[Kumaar]]\n| music3 = [[Sukhbir (musician)|Sukhbir]], [[Abhijit Vaghani]]\n| length3 = 4:04\n| title4 = Ek Jindari\n| extra4 = Taniskaa Sanghvi\n| lyrics4 = Kumaar\n| music4 = Sachin\u2013Jigar\n| length4 = 4:31\n|all_writing=|title6=|length6=|title7=|length7=|title8=|length8=|title9=|length9=|title10=|length10=|title11=|length11=|title12=|length12=|title13=|length13=|title14=|length14=|title15=|length15=|title16=|length16=|title17=|length17=|title18=|length18=|title19=|length19=|title20=|length20=}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released worldwide on 19 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/bollywood-news-box-office-irrfan-hindi-medium-arjun-kapoor-shraddha-kapoor-half-girlfriend/18218169|title=Box office jigsaw: It's Irrfan's 'Hindi Medium' vs Arjun Kapoor's 'Half Girlfriend' now|newspaper=[[Mid Day]]|date=4 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822052221/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/bollywood-news-box-office-irrfan-hindi-medium-arjun-kapoor-shraddha-kapoor-half-girlfriend/18218169|archivedate=22 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Hindi Medium'' was declared 'tax-free' in [[Gujarat]], [[Maharashtra]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/190517/hindi-medium-goes-tax-free-in-maharashtra-and-gujarat.html|title=Irrfan Khan's Hindi Medium goes tax free in Maharashtra and Gujarat|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406043940/https://deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/190517/hindi-medium-goes-tax-free-in-maharashtra-and-gujarat.html|archivedate=6 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/hindi-medium-made-tax-free-in-madhya-pradesh-117052900583_1.html|title='Hindi Medium' made tax free in Madhya Pradesh|newspaper=Business Standard|date=29 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822014636/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/hindi-medium-made-tax-free-in-madhya-pradesh-117052900583_1.html|archivedate=22 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/sachin-a-billion-dreams-hindi-medium-tax-free-in-delhi-117060101050_1.html|title='Sachin: A Billion Dreams', 'Hindi Medium' tax-free in Delhi|newspaper=Business Standard|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822014049/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/sachin-a-billion-dreams-hindi-medium-tax-free-in-delhi-117060101050_1.html|archivedate=22 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, following the success of ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' (2016) and ''[[Secret Superstar]]'' (2017) in China, it was announced that ''Hindi Medium'' was to be released in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/secret-superstar-aamir-khans-film-becomes-second-indian-movie-to-cross-rs-500-cr-in-china-next-only-to-his-dangal-4331887.html|title=Secret Superstar: Aamir Khan's film becomes second Indian movie to cross Rs 500 cr in China, next only to his Dangal|newspaper=[[Firstpost]]|date=2 February 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619170120/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/secret-superstar-aamir-khans-film-becomes-second-indian-movie-to-cross-rs-500-cr-in-china-next-only-to-his-dangal-4331887.html|archivedate=19 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Hindi Medium'' released in China on 4 April 2018 to coincide with the [[Qingming Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/irrfan-khan-hindi-medium-sets-china-release-1202721499/|title=Irrfan Khan's 'Hindi Medium' Sets China Release|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828040416/https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/irrfan-khan-hindi-medium-sets-china-release-1202721499/|archivedate=28 August 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film's Chinese title is \u8d77\u8dd1\u7ebf (''Qi Pao Xian''), which means ''The Starting Line''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/chinese-blog-why-hindi-medium-success-in-china-irrfan-khan|title=A Chinese View: Why 'Hindi Medium' Strikes a Chord In China|newspaper=[[The Quint]]|date=12 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628182936/http://www.thequint.com/entertainment/chinese-blog-why-hindi-medium-success-in-china-irrfan-khan|archivedate=28 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nThe makers of the [[Bengali language|Bengali]] film ''[[Ramdhanu]]'' (2014), directed by the duo [[Nandita Roy]] and [[Shiboprosad Mukherjee]], had launched a copyright case against ''Hindi Medium'', claiming that the storyline was similar to their film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/tolly-trio-says-irrfan-starrer-copied-from-ramdhanu-may-move-court/articleshow/57902646.cms|title=Tolly trio says Irrfan-starrer copied from 'Ramdhanu', may move court|newspaper=The Times of India|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208094133/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com//city/kolkata/tolly-trio-says-irrfan-starrer-copied-from-ramdhanu-may-move-court/articleshow/57902646.cms|archivedate=8 December 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In response to this, Chaudhary said, <blockquote>\"We have researched our script over a year and it is based on original material. I would request everyone involved to not rush to a judgement without ascertaining the facts. And the facts can easily be confirmed by watching ''Hindi Medium'' on May 12.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/saket-chaudhary-hindi-medium-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-ramdhanu-remake-refuse-dinesh-vijan/152776|title=Makers refuse the rumours of Irrfan Khan's Hindi Medium being a copy of Ramdhanu!|publisher=[[Times Now]]|date=8 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126180931/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/saket-chaudhary-hindi-medium-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-ramdhanu-remake-refuse-dinesh-vijan/152776|archivedate=26 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref></blockquote> Roy and Mukherjee later withdrew their case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://scroll.in/reel/844880/win-for-hindi-medium-as-bengali-film-ramdhanu-withdraws-plagiarism-charge|title=Win for 'Hindi Medium' as Bengali film 'Ramdhanu' withdraws plagiarism charge|publisher=[[Scroll.in]]|date=24 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715094549/https://scroll.in/reel/844880/win-for-hindi-medium-as-bengali-film-ramdhanu-withdraws-plagiarism-charge|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Saba Qamar and Manish Malhotra grace Masala Awards 2017 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A woman standing with right hand on hip|Qamar (''pictured'') and Khan received praise for their performances]]\n''Hindi Medium'' received a generally positive reception from critics, with particular praise for Khan's and Qamar's performances.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/hindi-medium-review-roundup-irrfan-khans-film-relatable-must-watch-claim-bollywood-critics-727184|title=Hindi Medium review roundup: Irrfan Khan's film is relatable and a must-watch, claim Bollywood critics|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524062305/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hindi-medium-review-roundup-irrfan-khans-film-relatable-must-watch-claim-bollywood-critics-727184|archivedate=24 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRohit Bhatnagar of ''[[Deccan Chronicle]]'' called the film a \"masterpiece\" and praised Khan's and Qamar's acting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/180517/hindi-medium-movie-review-a-magic-you-will-never-forget.html|title=Hindi Medium movie review: A magic you will never forget|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509102943/https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/180517/hindi-medium-movie-review-a-magic-you-will-never-forget.html|archivedate=9 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rachit Gupta of ''[[Filmfare]]'' rated the film 4.5 out of 5 stars and said that it was a \"refreshingly funny and brilliantly insightful film on parenting and education.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/review-hindi-medium-20683.html|title=Review: Hindi Medium|work=[[Filmfare]]|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430202053/http://www.filmfare.com/reviews/review-hindi-medium-20683.html|archivedate=30 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Madhureeta Mukherjee of ''The Times of India'' highlighted the script, and the comedic elements of the film as its strengths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/hindi-medium/movie-review/58716386.cms|title=Hindi Medium review|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321132122/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/hindi-medium/movie-review/58716386.cms|archivedate=21 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rohit Vats of ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' giving 3.5 stars out of 5 stars, commented that \"Khan asks the viewers to take a stand against faulty Indian education system\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-s-film-will-make-you-laugh-cry-and-angry/story-oBbBMOIqLfjt48XL7sIW3K.html|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Irrfan Khan asks you to take a stand against our faulty education system|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008183315/https://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-s-film-will-make-you-laugh-cry-and-angry/story-oBbBMOIqLfjt48XL7sIW3K.html|archivedate=8 October 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Samrudhi Ghosh of ''[[India Today]]'' gave 3 out of 5 stars, praising Khan's and Qamar's performances, said \"''Hindi Medium'' may use over-dramatised events to make its message hit home, but in spite of its hiccups, the film is not bogged down because of the performances and the humour\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/reviews/story/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-978012-2017-05-19|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Irrfan-Saba's performances qualify the film in the cut-off list|newspaper=[[India Today]]|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410005804/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/reviews/story/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-978012-2017-05-19|archivedate=10 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smrity Sharma of ''India.com'' rated the film 2.5 out of 5 stars, and wrote: \"Decent story, humour, a few heart tugging moments and effortless performances by Irrfan Khan, Saba Qamar and Deepak Dobriyal make the movie watchable.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.india.com/showbiz/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-start-a-conversation-that-goes-nowhere-2141244/|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Irrfan Khan, Saba Qamar start a conversation that goes nowhere|newspaper=India.com|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930202602/http://www.india.com/showbiz/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-start-a-conversation-that-goes-nowhere-2141244/|archivedate=30 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shubhra Gupta of ''The Indian Express'' giving 2 out of 5 stars, praised Khan's acting however felt that the writing was \"flat\", and that some of the supporting characters were \"more caricature than real\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-film-saba-qamar-star-rating-4661833/|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Watch it for the glorious Irrfan Khan|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509123134/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-film-saba-qamar-star-rating-4661833/|archivedate=9 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Hindi Medium'' received a generally positive reception from critics outside of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hindi_medium|title=Hindi Medium (2017)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209042456/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hindi_medium/|archivedate=9 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' gave it 4 (out of 5) stars: \"With all its merits, though, the film stumbles near the end with its overly sentimental conclusion.\" The reviewer concluded that \"the film is one of the best Bollywood films\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/hindi-medium|title=Hindi Medium \u2013 Film review|newspaper=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715100357/https://www.timeout.com/london/film/hindi-medium|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> James Marsh of ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' rated it 3.5 stars out of 5 stars, calling it \"a classical comedy of manners full of humour and playful performances\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2161775/hindi-medium-film-review-bollywood-education-comedy-comes-message|title=Hindi Medium film review: Bollywood education comedy comes with a message that will resonate well beyond India|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=29 August 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502054653/https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2161775/hindi-medium-film-review-bollywood-education-comedy-comes-message|archivedate=2 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sadaf Siddique of ''Dawn'' observed: \"Chaudhary gets full marks for novelty, he fails to adequately flesh his ideas out\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1177644|title=Saba Qamar and Irrfan Khan make the most of Hindi Medium's slightly shallow script|newspaper=Dawn|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115153654/https://images.dawn.com/news/1177644|archivedate=15 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\nThe film emerged as a [[sleeper hit]] at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2984|title=\nHindi Medium Emerges A True Sleeper HIT|publisher=[[Box Office India]]|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803202804/http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2984|archivedate=3 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Its worldwide gross was {{INRConvert|108.55|c}} by July 2017.<ref name=\"Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-hindi-medium/|title=Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101003207/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-hindi-medium/|archivedate=1 January 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Within three days of its April 2018 release in China, ''Hindi Medium'' crossed {{INRConvert|100|c}} at the Chinese box office, crossing the {{INRConvert|200|c}} mark worldwide,<ref name=\"China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/china-box-office-hindi-medium-crosses-rs-100-cr-china-beats-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan/|title=China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=7 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225061013/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/china-box-office-hindi-medium-crosses-rs-100-cr-china-beats-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan/|archivedate=25 December 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> becoming Khan's highest-grossing Hindi film, surpassing his 2013 release ''[[The Lunchbox]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html|title=Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide|newspaper=Firstpost|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629203820/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html|archivedate=29 June 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By April 16, 2018, ''Hindi Medium'' had crossed the {{INRConvert|300|c}} mark worldwide, becoming one of the top 20 highest-grossing Indian films of all time.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium box office collection surges past Rs 300 crore after China run; trumps Padmaavat's overseas gross\">{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-box-office-collection-surges-past-rs-300-crore-after-china-run-trumps-padmaavats-overseas-gross-4433401.html|title=Hindi Medium box office collection surges past Rs 300 crore after China run; trumps Padmaavat's overseas gross|newspaper=Firstpost|date=16 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328145146/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-box-office-collection-surges-past-rs-300-crore-after-china-run-trumps-padmaavats-overseas-gross-4433401.html|archivedate=28 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic===\n''Hindi Medium'' collected {{INRConvert|2.81|c}} on its opening day.<ref name=\"Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium\"/> It released on the same day as the much bigger budget film, ''[[Half Girlfriend (film)|Half Girlfriend]]'' (2017), which earned {{INRConvert|10.27|c}} on the first day. Gradually, the film turned to be more successful than the former. After one week, the film grossed {{INRConvert|25.21|c}} at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/lifestyle/off-track/irrfan-khans-hindi-medium-earns-rs-25.21-crores-at-the-box-office-in-first-week/story/253064.html|title=Irrfan Khan's Hindi Medium earns Rs 25.21 crores at the box office in first week|newspaper=[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126180931/https://www.businesstoday.in/lifestyle/off-track/irrfan-khans-hindi-medium-earns-rs-25.21-crores-at-the-box-office-in-first-week/story/253064.html|archivedate=26 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film grossed {{INRConvert|96.65|c}} during its lifetime run in Indian theatres.<ref name=\"Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium\"/> It was one of 2017's top ten most commercially successful Hindi films in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/box-office-list-2017-tiger-zinda-hai-baahubali-2-1130375-2018-01-09|title=Box Office List 2017: Tiger Zinda Hai and Baahubali 2 only blockbusters. 286 films. 257 flops.|newspaper=India Today|date=9 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126134851/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/box-office-list-2017-tiger-zinda-hai-baahubali-2-1130375-2018-01-09|archivedate=26 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Overseas===\nThe film grossed {{INRConvert|14.25|c}} overseas in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/overseas-total-gross.php?year=2017|title=Top Overseas Grossers 2017|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626213637/https://www.boxofficeindia.com/overseas-total-gross.php?year=2017|archivedate=26 June 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following its April 2018 release in China, the film crossed {{INRConvert|200|c}} overseas, becoming the seventh Indian film to cross the {{US$|30 million|long=no}} mark at the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets|overseas box office]]. It also surpassed the overseas gross of 2018's highest-grossing Indian film ''[[Padmaavat]]''.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium box office collection surges past Rs 300 crore after China run; trumps Padmaavat's overseas gross\"/>\n\n===China===\nOn its opening day in China, on 4 April 2018, the film grossed {{INRConvert|22.05|c}}.<ref name=\"China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again\"/> ''Hindi Medium'' surpassed ''Dangal'' and ''Bajrangi Bhaijaan'' to have the second highest opening day for an Indian film in China, behind only ''Secret Superstar''.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide\">{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html|title=Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide|newspaper=Firstpost|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715124615/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html?year=2017|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film's opening three-day gross was {{INRConvert|102.18|c}}.<ref name=\"China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again\"/>\n\nThe film's success is attributed to strong [[word-of-mouth]], helped by a 9.1 rating at the Chinese ticketing website [[Tianjin Maoyan Weiying Culture Media|Maoyan]], as well as Khan's recognition among Chinese audiences from international films such as ''[[Jurassic World]]'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', and ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]''.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide\"/> The film grossed {{INRConvert|223|c}} during its lifetime run at the Chinese box office, which was surpassed by the 2018 film ''[[Andhadhun]]'' released in 2019 in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/box-office/article/andhadhun-box-office-collection-day-15-ayushmann-khurrana-s-film-topples-hindi-medium-total-rs-237-42-crore/402414|title=AndhaDhun China box office collection Day 15: Ayushmann's film topples Hindi Medium, total Rs 237.42 crore|publisher=Times Now|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715124727/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/box-office/article/andhadhun-box-office-collection-day-15-ayushmann-khurrana-s-film-topples-hindi-medium-total-rs-237-42-crore/402414?year=2017|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nAt the [[63rd Filmfare Awards]], the film garnered six nominations, winning for Best Film and Best Actor for Khan. Chaudhary won Best Director and Khan won for Best Actor at the [[19th IIFA Awards]]. It received six nominations at the [[Zee Cine Awards]].\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Award\n!scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n!scope=\"col\"| Category\n!scope=\"col\"| Recipients\n!scope=\"col\"| Result\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\" | [[Filmfare Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[63rd Filmfare Awards|20 January 2018]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| ''Hindi Medium''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"6\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards-2018/nominations|title=Filmfare Awards 2018 \u2013 Winners & Nominees|publisher=[[Filmfare Awards]]|date=20 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715124831/https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards-2018/nominations?year=2017|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actor|Best Actor (Critics)]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Saba Qamar]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Deepak Dobriyal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\" | [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[19th IIFA Awards|22\u201324 June 2018]]\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| ''Hindi Medium''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-nominations-2018-tumhari-sulu-leads-with-7-nods-newton-follows-1855889|title=IIFA Nominations 2018: Tumhari Sulu Leads With 7 Nods, Newton Follows|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=22 May 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625104200/https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-nominations-2018-tumhari-sulu-leads-with-7-nods-newton-follows-1855889|archivedate=25 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iifa.com/awards2018|title=IIFA Awards 2018 Winners|publisher=[[International Indian Film Academy Awards]]|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190312152519/https://www.iifa.com/awards2018|archivedate=12 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Deepak Dobriyal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| [[10th Mirchi Music Awards|28 January 2018]]\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Music Composer of The Year|Music Composer of The Year]]\n| [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]] for \"Hoor\"\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|title=Nominations \u2013 Mirchi Music Awards|publisher=[[Mirchi Music Awards]]|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325084119/http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|archivedate=25 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Screen Awards]]\n| 2 December 2017\n| [[Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/star-screen-awards-2017-vidya-balan-rajkummar-rao-full-winners-list-1099753-2017-12-04|title=Star Screen Awards 2017: Dangal wins big, Vidya Balan-Rajkummar Rao named best actor and actress|newspaper=India Today|date=4 December 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407090920/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/star-screen-awards-2017-vidya-balan-rajkummar-rao-full-winners-list-1099753-2017-12-04|archivedate=7 April 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\" | [[Zee Cine Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 30 December 2017\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Film|Best Film (Viewer's Choice)]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''Hindi Medium''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"6\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zeecineawards.com/timeline/2018/winners/|title=Zee Cine Awards 2018 \u2013 Winners & Nominees|publisher=[[Zee Cine Awards]]|date=30 December 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604203215/http://www.zeecineawards.com/timeline/2018/winners/|archivedate=4 June 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Film|Best Film (Jury's Choice)]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Actor \u2013 Male|Best Actor \u2013 Male]]\n| [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role \u2013 Male|Best Actor in a Supporting Role \u2013 Male]]\n| [[Deepak Dobriyal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]], Zeenat Lakhani\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main article|Angrezi Medium}}\nAfter the success of ''Hindi Medium'', a sequel to the film was planned. Regarding the success of the film, producer Vijan told ''[[Mid Day]]'', \"The response we have got is phenomenal. The entire unit of ''Hindi Medium'', including Irrfan and Saba, who look cool as a couple on-screen, should be repeated in a film. There is definitely scope for a sequel. We would certainly explore it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-hindi-medium-sequel-dinesh-vijan-bollywood-news/18345177|title=Irrfan Khan and Saba Qamar's 'Hindi Medium' to have a sequel|newspaper=Mid Day|date=17 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106184234/https://www.mid-day.com/articles/irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-hindi-medium-sequel-dinesh-vijan-bollywood-news/18345177|archivedate=6 January 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 24 January 2018, Vijan confirmed the sequel to [[Times Now]]. He said, \"We have just finished typing the second part\", with \"Just finishing touches are being put\", however, \"I think you will have to wait for an official announcement for that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/hindi-medium-sequel-scripting-done-announcement-on-star-cast-to-follow-soon/192153|title=Exclusive \u2013 Hindi Medium sequel: Scripting done, announcement on star cast to follow soon|publisher=Times Now|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406060243/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/hindi-medium-sequel-scripting-done-announcement-on-star-cast-to-follow-soon/192153|archivedate=6 April 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2019, it was announced that [[Kareena Kapoor]] has been added to the cast of the sequel to play the role of a police officer and filming will start from April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kareena-kapoor-khan-reportedly-roped-in-to-play-a-cop-in-hindi-medium-sequel-starring-irrfan-khan-6357521.html|title=Kareena Kapoor Khan reportedly roped in to play a cop in Hindi Medium sequel, starring Irrfan Khan|newspaper=Firstpost|date=30 March 2019|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522090029/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kareena-kapoor-khan-reportedly-roped-in-to-play-a-cop-in-hindi-medium-sequel-starring-irrfan-khan-6357521.html|archivedate=22 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 5 April, the sequel's title was announced as ''[[Angrezi Medium]]'' and filming began in [[Udaipur]]. This was completed in July.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/videos/entertainment/hindi/angrezi-medium-wrap-up-homi-adajania-thanks-irrfan-khan-team/amp_videoshow/70205034.cms |title='Angrezi Medium' wrap-up: Homi Adajania gets emotional, hugs Irrfan Khan|date=13 July 2019 |work=The Times of India|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/irrfan-khan-finally-back-to-work-begins-shooting-for-angrezi-medium-in-udaipur-first-photos/394850|title=Irrfan Khan back to work, begins shooting for Hindi Medium sequel, Angrezi Medium in Udaipur \u2013 first photos|publisher=Times Now|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406060234/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/irrfan-khan-finally-back-to-work-begins-shooting-for-angrezi-medium-in-udaipur-first-photos/394850|archivedate=6 April 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 17 February 2020, the film's release date was changed to 13 March 2020 from the earlier release date of 20 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/angrezi-medium-to-release-a-week-earlier-on-march-13-gunjan-saxena-delayed-for-a-month-1647277-2020-02-17|work= India Today|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|title=''Angrezi Medium'' to release a week earlier on March 13, Gunjan Saxena delayed by a month}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Bollywood films of 2017]]\n{{Portalbar|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt5764096}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|hindi_medium}}\n\n{{Saket Chaudhary}}\n{{Filmfare Award for Best Film}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about the education system in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Amar Mohile]]\n[[Category:T-Series films]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|2017 film directed by Saket Chaudhary}}\n{{about|the film|the language educational policy in India|National Policy on Education}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Hindi Medium\n| image          = Hindi Medium poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = Two persons dressed in two different styles.\n| director       = [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| producer       = [[Dinesh Vijan]]<br />[[Bhushan Kumar]]\n| writer         = Saket Chaudhary<br />Zeenat Lakhani\n| starring       = [[Irrfan Khan]]<br />[[Saba Qamar]]\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n*'''Songs:'''\n*[[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n*'''Background score:'''\n*[[Amar Mohile]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Laxman Utekar]]\n| editing        = [[A. Sreekar Prasad]]\n| studio         = [[Maddock Films]]<br />[[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]\n| distributor    = [[AA Films]] (India)<br />[[Zee Studios]] (Overseas)\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|5|19|India|2018|4|4|China|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/hindi-medium-film|title=Hindi Medium|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=15 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715085241/https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/hindi-medium-film|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Hindi]]\n| budget         = {{INRConvert|14|c|year=2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-hindi-medium-clocks-22-crores-102-profit/|title=Box Office: Hindi Medium clocks 22 crores and 102% as profit|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924203809/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-hindi-medium-clocks-22-crores-102-profit/|archivedate=24 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = <!--Do not remove-->{{Estimation}}<!--per WT:ICTF consensus--> {{INRConvert|322.4|c|year=2017}} <ref name=\"gross\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/box-office/|title=Hindi Medium Box Office Collection till Now|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715091530/https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/box-office/?movieid=3526|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Hindi Medium''''' is a 2017 Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Saket Chaudhary]]. It was produced by [[Dinesh Vijan]] and [[Bhushan Kumar]] under their respective banners [[Maddock Films]] and [[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]. The film features [[Irrfan Khan]] and [[Saba Qamar]] in the lead roles, with [[Deepak Dobriyal]] and Dishita Sehgal in supporting roles. Set in Delhi, the plot centres on a couple's struggle to get their daughter admitted to a prestigious [[English-medium education|English-medium]] school in order to rise in society.\n\nThe idea for the film was created by Chaudhary and his co-writer Zeenat Lakhani during the development of his previous film ''[[Shaadi Ke Side Effects]]'' (2014). The film was shot in [[Chandni Chowk]], [[Anand Lok, Jaipur|Anand Lok]], [[Karol Bagh]], and Sangam Vihar. The film's [[soundtrack album]] was composed by the duo [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]], with lyrics by [[Priya Saraiya]] and [[Kumaar]]. The [[Film score|score]] was composed by [[Amar Mohile]]. [[Laxman Utekar]] was the [[Cinematography|cinematographer]], and [[A. Sreekar Prasad]] edited the film.\n\nMade on a [[production budget]] of {{\u20b9|14|link=yes}} [[crore]], ''Hindi Medium'' released on 19 May 2017, and received a generally positive reception from the critics, with particular praise for Khan's and Qamar's performances. The film grossed {{INRConvert|322.4|c}} at the worldwide box office, with a large amount coming from China, becoming one of the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|highest-grossing Indian films]] of all time. At the [[63rd Filmfare Awards]], it won [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]], and [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Khan. Due to the success of the film, a spiritual successor, ''[[Angrezi Medium]]'', directed by [[Homi Adajania]], went into development, and was released theatrically on 13 March 2020.\n\n==Plot==\nRaj Batra ([[Irrfan Khan]]) is a boutique owner who lives in [[Connaught Place, New Delhi|Connaught Place, Delhi]], with his wife Mita ([[Saba Qamar]]) and 5-year-old daughter, Pia (Dishita Sehgal). The couple want Pia to be admitted to a prestigious English-medium school in Delhi as they feel that this will enable her to become a part of the elite of society. After browsing through some luxurious hotel-like schools, they zero in on the Delhi Grammar School, ranked the best in the city, but it stipulates that students must stay within a 3-km radius of the school. \n\nThey move to a posh villa in Delhi's upscale [[Vasant Vihar, Delhi|Vasant Vihar]] neighbourhood and try to befriend the neighbours, but face limited success as their (particularly Raj's) gaucheness holds them back. They are introduced to a consultant, Shikha ([[Tillotama Shome]]), who is largely cynical and disparaging of the couple for their flashiness, but nevertheless helps them to prepare for the interview required for admission to various top schools. However, Raj and Mita fail to deliver their tutored answers in the interview, and their application gets rejected due to their limited knowledge of English. \n\nRaj and Mita learn from an employee that his daughter has been admitted through the [[Right to education|Right To Education]] (RTE) quota, a scheme that helps children from poor families to be admitted to prestigious schools. Through a fixer, Raj gets fake certificates and proofs of an address in Bharat Nagar, a slum area of the city. They decide to apply for Pia's admission through that scheme. However, a scam soon surfaces in which it is revealed that rich parents pose as paupers to get their children admitted through the RTE quota. So, after telling their snooty neighbours that they are going on a Europe trip, the Batras move to a dilapidated home in Bharat Nagar for a month and pretend to be impoverished. They strike a friendship with Shyam ([[Deepak Dobriyal]]) and Tulsi (Swati Das), who are hopeful that their son Mohan (Angshuman Nandi) gets to to study in Delhi Grammar School through the RTE quota.\n\nWhen school officials come to Bharat Nagar to investigate, they are surprised that the Batras do not seem to be as poor as their appearances would suggest, but Shyam covers up for Raj, saying that they were reduced to penury due to a factory fire. Shyam and Tulsi teach them to live like poor people. Raj accompanies Shyam to work at a food manufacturing plant, while Mita slowly learns to fight for her share of daily needs. The Batras and Shyam's family are hopeful that their children will get admission through random selection; however, while Pia eventually gets admission, Mohan's application is rejected. \n\nThe Batras return to Vasant Vihar. Raj and Mita make a donation to the Bharat Nagar Government School, where Mohan studies, to renovate it and get new books. After watching their son become fluent in English, Shyam and Tulsi search for the identity of the anonymous donor to thank them. However, when he visits the donor's address in Vasant Vihar, Shyam is astonished to see Raj. He finds out the truth about Raj pretending to be poor to enable Pia's admission and leaves to tell Delhi Grammar School's principal ([[Amrita Singh]]) of Raj's deceit.\n\nRaj and Mita rush to Delhi Grammar school to get there before Shyam. Raj asks for Pia's admission to be revoked and tells the truth. The principal rejects doing so, and simply asks him to take his seat in the annual day performance in the auditorium. After some children perform a song-and-dance routine, he gatecrashes the function, reveals they are actually from the Bharat Nagar government school, gives a speech about English in India and education rights, and leaves. On their way out, the Batras bump into the principal of the government school and tell him that they plan to admit their daughter Pia to his school to study with Mohan, which he is only too happy to accept.\n\n==Cast==\nCredits adapted from [[Bollywood Hungama]]:<ref name=\"Hindi Medium Cast & Crew\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/cast/|title=Hindi Medium Cast & Crew|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715091657/https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/cast/?movieid=3526|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n* [[Irrfan Khan]] as Raj Batra\n** Delzad Hiwale as young Raj\n* [[Saba Qamar]] as Mita Batra\n** [[Sanjana Sanghi]] as young Mita\n* Kiran Khoje as Sushila\n* Dishita Sehgal as Pia Batra\n* [[Amrita Singh]] as Principal Lodha\n* [[Deepak Dobriyal]] as Shyam Prakash\n* [[Neelu Kohli]] as Mita's mother\n* Rajeev Gupta as Masterji, Raj's father\n* [[Sumit Gulati]] as Chotu\n* [[Mallika Dua]] as Dolly\n* Kulbir Kaur as Dolly's mother\n* Charu Shankar as Maya\n* [[Tillotama Shome]] as Shikha, a consultant\n* [[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]] as MLA\n* [[Taran Bajaj]] as tout\n* [[Ankur Jain]] as news reader\n* Swati Das as Tulsi\n* [[Neha Dhupia]] as Aarti (special appearance)\n* [[Sanjay Suri]] as Kabir (special appearance)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nMade on a production budget of {{\u20b9|14}} crore, ''Hindi Medium'' was produced by Vijan of Maddock Films and Bhushan Kumar of T-Series. The film was directed by Chaudhary, his third after [[romantic comedy]] films ''[[Pyaar Ke Side Effects]]'' (2006) and ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects''. He came up with the idea of making a film about [[Education in India|India's education system]] with his co-writer Zeenat Lakhani during the development of the latter film. They found the idea too extensive to include in ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects'', so after its release, they decided to incorporate the idea into a separate film. Stating the reason to make ''Hindi Medium'', Chaudhary said, \"The subject is so relevant. We realised that today irrespective of the background of the parent, they still want to have the best education for the children.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/saket-chaudhary-irrfan-khan-is-not-a-pretentious-actor/articleshow/58295973.cms|title=Saket Chaudhary: Irrfan Khan is not a pretentious actor|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715091827/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/saket-chaudhary-irrfan-khan-is-not-a-pretentious-actor/articleshow/58295973.cms|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPre-production work began after the release of ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects''. Chaudhary began working on the story at that time, and he chose Delhi as the film's key location.<ref name=\"Pic: Irrfan Khan flaunts his saree draping skills for Hindi Medium!\">{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/270317/pic-irrfan-khan-flaunts-his-saree-draping-skills-for-hindi-medium.html|title=Pic: Irrfan Khan flaunts his saree draping skills for Hindi Medium!|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511150725/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/270317/pic-irrfan-khan-flaunts-his-saree-draping-skills-for-hindi-medium.html|archivedate=11 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The production crew consisted primarily of people Chaudhary had worked with on ''Pyaar Ke Side Effects'' and ''Shaadi Ke Side Effects'', with the exception of [[production designer]] Mustafa Stationwala\u2014they are editor A. Sreekar Prasad; dialogue writer [[Amitosh Nagpal]]; and cinematographer Laxman Utekar. The score was composed by Amar Mohile.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium Cast & Crew\"/>\n\n[[File:Irrfan Khan May 2015.jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A man standing and looking at the camera|It was Khan's choice to cast Qamar in the film]]\nOn 29 May 2016, [[CNN-News18|News18]] reported the casting of [[Saba Qamar]] in the film, which marked her Bollywood debut.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/hindi-medium-irrfan-sabas-unusual-pairing-looks-interesting-1249164.html|title='Hindi Medium' First Look: Irrfan Khan, Saba Qamar's Unusual Pairing Looks Interesting|publisher=[[CNN-News18|News18]]|date=29 May 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116204744/https://www.news18.com/news/movies/hindi-medium-irrfan-sabas-unusual-pairing-looks-interesting-1249164.html|archivedate=16 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Khan had recommended the casting of Qamar to the makers of the film. He said, \"When I saw her YouTube videos, I recommended her to the director and producer and they really liked her\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.samaa.tv/culture/2017/05/youll-never-believe-how-saba-qamar-was-picked-for-hindi-medium/|title=You\u2019ll never believe how Saba Qamar was picked for 'Hindi Medium'|publisher=[[Samaa TV]]|date=16 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715092309/https://www.samaa.tv/culture/2017/05/youll-never-believe-how-saba-qamar-was-picked-for-hindi-medium/|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Speaking about her role, Qamar said, \"I play a person who didn't get an opportunity to fulfil her dreams so she comes up with a scheme about giving the daughter a life that she didn't have\".\nKhan commented that he had accepted the role as it tackled the realistic subject of the challenges of obtaining a good education in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/saba-qamar-and-irrfan-khan-talk-hindi-medium-1.2030834|title=Saba Qamar and Irrfan Khan talk 'Hindi Medium'|newspaper=[[Gulf News]]|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715092428/https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/saba-qamar-and-irrfan-khan-talk-hindi-medium-1.2030834|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nQamar arrived in Mumbai from Pakistan in July 2016, and the film's principal photography began in the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/050716/meet-bollywood-towns-new-guest-from-across-the-border.html|title=Meet Bollywood's new guest from across the border|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414150446/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/050716/meet-bollywood-towns-new-guest-from-across-the-border.html|archivedate=14 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1175120|title=My Bollywood debut film is a little like Piku, says Saba Qamar|newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|date=7 April 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903134248/https://images.dawn.com/news/1175120|archivedate=3 September 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film was shot in Chandni Chowk, Anand Lok, Karol Bagh, and Sangam Vihar.<ref name=\"Pic: Irrfan Khan flaunts his saree draping skills for Hindi Medium!\"/> The shooting was completed in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/irrfan-khan-film-not-stalled-says-spokesperson-1.1914660|title=Irrfan Khan film not stalled, says spokesperson|newspaper=Gulf News|date=18 October 2016|accessdate=20 November 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120174109/https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/irrfan-khan-film-not-stalled-says-spokesperson-1.1914660|archivedate=20 November 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A song sequence was also filmed in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/irrfan-khan-shoots-in-georgia-for-hindi-medium-117032700317_1.html|title=Irrfan Khan shoots in Georgia for 'Hindi Medium'|newspaper=Business Standard|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329223505/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/irrfan-khan-shoots-in-georgia-for-hindi-medium-117032700317_1.html|archivedate=29 March 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Qamar commented that she enjoyed working with Khan, and felt safe while shooting in Delhi. In the same interview with Pakistani newspaper ''[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]'', she commented that her experience wasn't affected by the nationalist far-right political party [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]]'s hostility towards Pakistan at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1176400/did-you-know-saba-qamar-just-wrapped-up-her-bollywood-debut-in-delhi|title=Did you know? Saba Qamar just wrapped up her Bollywood debut in Delhi|newspaper=Dawn|date=12 October 2016|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004022219/https://images.dawn.com/news/1176400/did-you-know-saba-qamar-just-wrapped-up-her-bollywood-debut-in-delhi|archivedate=4 October 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hindi Medium\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 21 April 2017\n| recorded   = 2016\u20132017\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film Soundtrack]]\n| length     = 21:20\n| label      = [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Meri Pyaari Bindu]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[A Gentleman]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc = {{External media\n| audio1     = {{YouTube|C6AKnuySrHU|Official Audio Jukebox}}}}\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack consists of four compositions \u2014 two original: \"Hoor\" and \"Ek Jindari\", and two recreated: \"Suit Suit\" and \"Oh Ho Ho Ho\". Sachin\u2013Jigar has composed the original songs. \"Suit Suit\", the first song, is written and sung by [[Guru Randhawa]] and [[Arjun (singer)|Arjun]] and composed by Randhawa and [[Rajat Nagpal]]. The second track \"Hoor\" was composed by Sachin\u2013Jigar and sung by [[Atif Aslam]] with lyrics by Priya Saraiya. The track \"Oh Ho Ho Ho\", was composed by [[Sukhbir (musician)|Sukhbir]] and [[Abhijit Vaghani]], sung by Sukhbir, rapped by [[Ikka Singh]] and written by Kumaar. The fourth, \"Ek Jindari\" was written by Kumaar and composed by Sachin\u2013Jigar. It was sung by Taniskaa Sanghvi. The album rights of the film were acquired by T-Series, and it was released on 21 April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tseries.com/music/hindi-medium-0|title=Hindi Medium \u2013 Music|publisher=[[T-Series (company)|T-Series]]|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927171841/http://www.tseries.com/music/hindi-medium-0|archivedate=27 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Hindi Medium Music Review\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nJoginder Tuteja of Bollywood Hungama, rated the album a 3 out of 5 stars. He said that \"the music of ''Hindi Medium'' turns out to be better than expected\", and praised the inclusion of recreations of \"Suit Suit\" and \"Oh Ho Ho Ho\" as they were previously popular Punjabi songs.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium Music Review\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/songs/music-critic-review/|title=Hindi Medium Music Review|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=23 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213045935/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/hindi-medium/songs/music-critic-review/|archivedate=13 December 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> V. Lakshmi of ''[[The Times of India]]'' in a positive review of the album said that, \"by the time the album ends, the listeners are left humming the tunes!\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/album-review-hindi-medium/articleshow/58398794.cms|title=Album Review: Hindi Medium|newspaper=The Times of India|date=28 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517164133/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/album-review-hindi-medium/articleshow/58398794.cms|archivedate=17 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Suanshu Khurana of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' highlighted the song \"Hoor\" as the best song on the album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/hindi-medium-music-review-arjun-kanungo-4642660/|title=Winning Formula|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=6 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707205547/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/hindi-medium-music-review-arjun-kanungo-4642660/|archivedate=7 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 15:43\n| headline= Track listing\n| title1 = Suit Suit\n| extra1 = Guru Randhawa, Arjun\n| lyrics1 = [[Guru Randhawa]], [[Arjun (singer)|Arjun]]\n| music1 = Guru Randhawa, [[Rajat Nagpal]],\n| length1 = 3:10\n| title2 = Hoor\n| extra2 = [[Atif Aslam]]\n| lyrics2 = [[Priya Saraiya]]\n| music2 = [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]]\n| length2 = 3:57\n| title3 = Oh Ho Ho Ho (Remix)\n| extra3 = Sukhbir\n| lyrics3 = [[Kumaar]]\n| music3 = [[Sukhbir (musician)|Sukhbir]], [[Abhijit Vaghani]]\n| length3 = 4:04\n| title4 = Ek Jindari\n| extra4 = Taniskaa Sanghvi\n| lyrics4 = Kumaar\n| music4 = Sachin\u2013Jigar\n| length4 = 4:31\n|all_writing=|title6=|length6=|title7=|length7=|title8=|length8=|title9=|length9=|title10=|length10=|title11=|length11=|title12=|length12=|title13=|length13=|title14=|length14=|title15=|length15=|title16=|length16=|title17=|length17=|title18=|length18=|title19=|length19=|title20=|length20=}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released worldwide on 19 May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/bollywood-news-box-office-irrfan-hindi-medium-arjun-kapoor-shraddha-kapoor-half-girlfriend/18218169|title=Box office jigsaw: It's Irrfan's 'Hindi Medium' vs Arjun Kapoor's 'Half Girlfriend' now|newspaper=[[Mid Day]]|date=4 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822052221/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/bollywood-news-box-office-irrfan-hindi-medium-arjun-kapoor-shraddha-kapoor-half-girlfriend/18218169|archivedate=22 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Hindi Medium'' was declared 'tax-free' in [[Gujarat]], [[Maharashtra]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/190517/hindi-medium-goes-tax-free-in-maharashtra-and-gujarat.html|title=Irrfan Khan's Hindi Medium goes tax free in Maharashtra and Gujarat|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406043940/https://deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/190517/hindi-medium-goes-tax-free-in-maharashtra-and-gujarat.html|archivedate=6 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/hindi-medium-made-tax-free-in-madhya-pradesh-117052900583_1.html|title='Hindi Medium' made tax free in Madhya Pradesh|newspaper=Business Standard|date=29 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822014636/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/hindi-medium-made-tax-free-in-madhya-pradesh-117052900583_1.html|archivedate=22 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Delhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/sachin-a-billion-dreams-hindi-medium-tax-free-in-delhi-117060101050_1.html|title='Sachin: A Billion Dreams', 'Hindi Medium' tax-free in Delhi|newspaper=Business Standard|date=1 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822014049/http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/sachin-a-billion-dreams-hindi-medium-tax-free-in-delhi-117060101050_1.html|archivedate=22 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, following the success of ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' (2016) and ''[[Secret Superstar]]'' (2017) in China, it was announced that ''Hindi Medium'' was to be released in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/secret-superstar-aamir-khans-film-becomes-second-indian-movie-to-cross-rs-500-cr-in-china-next-only-to-his-dangal-4331887.html|title=Secret Superstar: Aamir Khan's film becomes second Indian movie to cross Rs 500 cr in China, next only to his Dangal|newspaper=[[Firstpost]]|date=2 February 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619170120/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/secret-superstar-aamir-khans-film-becomes-second-indian-movie-to-cross-rs-500-cr-in-china-next-only-to-his-dangal-4331887.html|archivedate=19 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Hindi Medium'' released in China on 4 April 2018 to coincide with the [[Qingming Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/irrfan-khan-hindi-medium-sets-china-release-1202721499/|title=Irrfan Khan's 'Hindi Medium' Sets China Release|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828040416/https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/irrfan-khan-hindi-medium-sets-china-release-1202721499/|archivedate=28 August 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film's Chinese title is \u8d77\u8dd1\u7ebf (''Qi Pao Xian''), which means ''The Starting Line''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/chinese-blog-why-hindi-medium-success-in-china-irrfan-khan|title=A Chinese View: Why 'Hindi Medium' Strikes a Chord In China|newspaper=[[The Quint]]|date=12 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628182936/http://www.thequint.com/entertainment/chinese-blog-why-hindi-medium-success-in-china-irrfan-khan|archivedate=28 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nThe makers of the [[Bengali language|Bengali]] film ''[[Ramdhanu]]'' (2014), directed by the duo [[Nandita Roy]] and [[Shiboprosad Mukherjee]], had launched a copyright case against ''Hindi Medium'', claiming that the storyline was similar to their film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/tolly-trio-says-irrfan-starrer-copied-from-ramdhanu-may-move-court/articleshow/57902646.cms|title=Tolly trio says Irrfan-starrer copied from 'Ramdhanu', may move court|newspaper=The Times of India|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208094133/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com//city/kolkata/tolly-trio-says-irrfan-starrer-copied-from-ramdhanu-may-move-court/articleshow/57902646.cms|archivedate=8 December 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In response to this, Chaudhary said, <blockquote>\"We have researched our script over a year and it is based on original material. I would request everyone involved to not rush to a judgement without ascertaining the facts. And the facts can easily be confirmed by watching ''Hindi Medium'' on May 12.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/saket-chaudhary-hindi-medium-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-ramdhanu-remake-refuse-dinesh-vijan/152776|title=Makers refuse the rumours of Irrfan Khan's Hindi Medium being a copy of Ramdhanu!|publisher=[[Times Now]]|date=8 April 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126180931/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/saket-chaudhary-hindi-medium-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-ramdhanu-remake-refuse-dinesh-vijan/152776|archivedate=26 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref></blockquote> Roy and Mukherjee later withdrew their case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://scroll.in/reel/844880/win-for-hindi-medium-as-bengali-film-ramdhanu-withdraws-plagiarism-charge|title=Win for 'Hindi Medium' as Bengali film 'Ramdhanu' withdraws plagiarism charge|publisher=[[Scroll.in]]|date=24 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715094549/https://scroll.in/reel/844880/win-for-hindi-medium-as-bengali-film-ramdhanu-withdraws-plagiarism-charge|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Saba Qamar and Manish Malhotra grace Masala Awards 2017 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|200px|alt=A woman standing with right hand on hip|Qamar (''pictured'') and Khan received praise for their performances]]\n''Hindi Medium'' received a generally positive reception from critics, with particular praise for Khan's and Qamar's performances.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/hindi-medium-review-roundup-irrfan-khans-film-relatable-must-watch-claim-bollywood-critics-727184|title=Hindi Medium review roundup: Irrfan Khan's film is relatable and a must-watch, claim Bollywood critics|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524062305/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/hindi-medium-review-roundup-irrfan-khans-film-relatable-must-watch-claim-bollywood-critics-727184|archivedate=24 May 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRohit Bhatnagar of ''[[Deccan Chronicle]]'' called the film a \"masterpiece\" and praised Khan's and Qamar's acting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/180517/hindi-medium-movie-review-a-magic-you-will-never-forget.html|title=Hindi Medium movie review: A magic you will never forget|newspaper=Deccan Chronicle|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509102943/https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/180517/hindi-medium-movie-review-a-magic-you-will-never-forget.html|archivedate=9 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rachit Gupta of ''[[Filmfare]]'' rated the film 4.5 out of 5 stars and said that it was a \"refreshingly funny and brilliantly insightful film on parenting and education.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.filmfare.com/reviews/review-hindi-medium-20683.html|title=Review: Hindi Medium|work=[[Filmfare]]|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430202053/http://www.filmfare.com/reviews/review-hindi-medium-20683.html|archivedate=30 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Madhureeta Mukherjee of ''The Times of India'' highlighted the script, and the comedic elements of the film as its strengths.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/hindi-medium/movie-review/58716386.cms|title=Hindi Medium review|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321132122/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/hindi-medium/movie-review/58716386.cms|archivedate=21 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rohit Vats of ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' giving 3.5 stars out of 5 stars, commented that \"Khan asks the viewers to take a stand against faulty Indian education system\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-s-film-will-make-you-laugh-cry-and-angry/story-oBbBMOIqLfjt48XL7sIW3K.html|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Irrfan Khan asks you to take a stand against our faulty education system|newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008183315/https://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-s-film-will-make-you-laugh-cry-and-angry/story-oBbBMOIqLfjt48XL7sIW3K.html|archivedate=8 October 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Samrudhi Ghosh of ''[[India Today]]'' gave 3 out of 5 stars, praising Khan's and Qamar's performances, said \"''Hindi Medium'' may use over-dramatised events to make its message hit home, but in spite of its hiccups, the film is not bogged down because of the performances and the humour\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/reviews/story/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-978012-2017-05-19|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Irrfan-Saba's performances qualify the film in the cut-off list|newspaper=[[India Today]]|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410005804/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/reviews/story/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-saba-qamar-978012-2017-05-19|archivedate=10 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smrity Sharma of ''India.com'' rated the film 2.5 out of 5 stars, and wrote: \"Decent story, humour, a few heart tugging moments and effortless performances by Irrfan Khan, Saba Qamar and Deepak Dobriyal make the movie watchable.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.india.com/showbiz/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-start-a-conversation-that-goes-nowhere-2141244/|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Irrfan Khan, Saba Qamar start a conversation that goes nowhere|newspaper=India.com|date=18 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930202602/http://www.india.com/showbiz/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-start-a-conversation-that-goes-nowhere-2141244/|archivedate=30 September 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shubhra Gupta of ''The Indian Express'' giving 2 out of 5 stars, praised Khan's acting however felt that the writing was \"flat\", and that some of the supporting characters were \"more caricature than real\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-film-saba-qamar-star-rating-4661833/|title=Hindi Medium movie review: Watch it for the glorious Irrfan Khan|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509123134/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/hindi-medium-movie-review-irrfan-khan-film-saba-qamar-star-rating-4661833/|archivedate=9 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Hindi Medium'' received a generally positive reception from critics outside of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hindi_medium|title=Hindi Medium (2017)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209042456/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hindi_medium/|archivedate=9 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' gave it 4 (out of 5) stars: \"With all its merits, though, the film stumbles near the end with its overly sentimental conclusion.\" The reviewer concluded that \"the film is one of the best Bollywood films\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/hindi-medium|title=Hindi Medium \u2013 Film review|newspaper=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715100357/https://www.timeout.com/london/film/hindi-medium|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> James Marsh of ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' rated it 3.5 stars out of 5 stars, calling it \"a classical comedy of manners full of humour and playful performances\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2161775/hindi-medium-film-review-bollywood-education-comedy-comes-message|title=Hindi Medium film review: Bollywood education comedy comes with a message that will resonate well beyond India|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=29 August 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502054653/https://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2161775/hindi-medium-film-review-bollywood-education-comedy-comes-message|archivedate=2 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sadaf Siddique of ''Dawn'' observed: \"Chaudhary gets full marks for novelty, he fails to adequately flesh his ideas out\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://images.dawn.com/news/1177644|title=Saba Qamar and Irrfan Khan make the most of Hindi Medium's slightly shallow script|newspaper=Dawn|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115153654/https://images.dawn.com/news/1177644|archivedate=15 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Box office==\nThe film emerged as a [[sleeper hit]] at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2984|title=\nHindi Medium Emerges A True Sleeper HIT|publisher=[[Box Office India]]|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803202804/http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2984|archivedate=3 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Its worldwide gross was {{INRConvert|108.55|c}} by July 2017.<ref name=\"Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-hindi-medium/|title=Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=20 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101003207/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/box-office-worldwide-collections-day-wise-breakup-hindi-medium/|archivedate=1 January 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Within three days of its April 2018 release in China, ''Hindi Medium'' crossed {{INRConvert|100|c}} at the Chinese box office, crossing the {{INRConvert|200|c}} mark worldwide,<ref name=\"China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/china-box-office-hindi-medium-crosses-rs-100-cr-china-beats-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan/|title=China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|date=7 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225061013/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/box-office-special-features/china-box-office-hindi-medium-crosses-rs-100-cr-china-beats-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan/|archivedate=25 December 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> becoming Khan's highest-grossing Hindi film, surpassing his 2013 release ''[[The Lunchbox]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html|title=Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide|newspaper=Firstpost|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629203820/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html|archivedate=29 June 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By April 16, 2018, ''Hindi Medium'' had crossed the {{INRConvert|300|c}} mark worldwide, becoming one of the top 20 highest-grossing Indian films of all time.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium box office collection surges past Rs 300 crore after China run; trumps Padmaavat's overseas gross\">{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-box-office-collection-surges-past-rs-300-crore-after-china-run-trumps-padmaavats-overseas-gross-4433401.html|title=Hindi Medium box office collection surges past Rs 300 crore after China run; trumps Padmaavat's overseas gross|newspaper=Firstpost|date=16 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328145146/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-box-office-collection-surges-past-rs-300-crore-after-china-run-trumps-padmaavats-overseas-gross-4433401.html|archivedate=28 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic===\n''Hindi Medium'' collected {{INRConvert|2.81|c}} on its opening day.<ref name=\"Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium\"/> It released on the same day as the much bigger budget film, ''[[Half Girlfriend (film)|Half Girlfriend]]'' (2017), which earned {{INRConvert|10.27|c}} on the first day. Gradually, the film turned to be more successful than the former. After one week, the film grossed {{INRConvert|25.21|c}} at the box office.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/lifestyle/off-track/irrfan-khans-hindi-medium-earns-rs-25.21-crores-at-the-box-office-in-first-week/story/253064.html|title=Irrfan Khan's Hindi Medium earns Rs 25.21 crores at the box office in first week|newspaper=[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126180931/https://www.businesstoday.in/lifestyle/off-track/irrfan-khans-hindi-medium-earns-rs-25.21-crores-at-the-box-office-in-first-week/story/253064.html|archivedate=26 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film grossed {{INRConvert|96.65|c}} during its lifetime run in Indian theatres.<ref name=\"Box Office: Worldwide collections and day wise breakup of Hindi Medium\"/> It was one of 2017's top ten most commercially successful Hindi films in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/box-office-list-2017-tiger-zinda-hai-baahubali-2-1130375-2018-01-09|title=Box Office List 2017: Tiger Zinda Hai and Baahubali 2 only blockbusters. 286 films. 257 flops.|newspaper=India Today|date=9 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126134851/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/box-office-list-2017-tiger-zinda-hai-baahubali-2-1130375-2018-01-09|archivedate=26 November 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Overseas===\nThe film grossed {{INRConvert|14.25|c}} overseas in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/overseas-total-gross.php?year=2017|title=Top Overseas Grossers 2017|publisher=Box Office India|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626213637/https://www.boxofficeindia.com/overseas-total-gross.php?year=2017|archivedate=26 June 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following its April 2018 release in China, the film crossed {{INRConvert|200|c}} overseas, becoming the seventh Indian film to cross the {{US$|30 million|long=no}} mark at the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films in overseas markets|overseas box office]]. It also surpassed the overseas gross of 2018's highest-grossing Indian film ''[[Padmaavat]]''.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium box office collection surges past Rs 300 crore after China run; trumps Padmaavat's overseas gross\"/>\n\n===China===\nOn its opening day in China, on 4 April 2018, the film grossed {{INRConvert|22.05|c}}.<ref name=\"China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again\"/> ''Hindi Medium'' surpassed ''Dangal'' and ''Bajrangi Bhaijaan'' to have the second highest opening day for an Indian film in China, behind only ''Secret Superstar''.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide\">{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html|title=Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide|newspaper=Firstpost|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715124615/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/hindi-medium-records-higher-box-office-opening-than-dangal-bajrangi-bhaijaan-in-china-irrfans-highest-grosser-worldwide-4420391.html?year=2017|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film's opening three-day gross was {{INRConvert|102.18|c}}.<ref name=\"China Box Office: Hindi Medium crosses Rs. 100 cr in China; out beats Dangal and Bajrangi Bhaijaan again\"/>\n\nThe film's success is attributed to strong [[word-of-mouth]], helped by a 9.1 rating at the Chinese ticketing website [[Tianjin Maoyan Weiying Culture Media|Maoyan]], as well as Khan's recognition among Chinese audiences from international films such as ''[[Jurassic World]]'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', and ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]''.<ref name=\"Hindi Medium records higher box office opening than Dangal, Bajrangi Bhaijaan in China; Irrfan's highest grosser worldwide\"/> The film grossed {{INRConvert|223|c}} during its lifetime run at the Chinese box office, which was surpassed by the 2018 film ''[[Andhadhun]]'' released in 2019 in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/box-office/article/andhadhun-box-office-collection-day-15-ayushmann-khurrana-s-film-topples-hindi-medium-total-rs-237-42-crore/402414|title=AndhaDhun China box office collection Day 15: Ayushmann's film topples Hindi Medium, total Rs 237.42 crore|publisher=Times Now|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715124727/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/box-office/article/andhadhun-box-office-collection-day-15-ayushmann-khurrana-s-film-topples-hindi-medium-total-rs-237-42-crore/402414?year=2017|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nAt the [[63rd Filmfare Awards]], the film garnered six nominations, winning for Best Film and Best Actor for Khan. Chaudhary won Best Director and Khan won for Best Actor at the [[19th IIFA Awards]]. It received six nominations at the [[Zee Cine Awards]].\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Award\n!scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n!scope=\"col\"| Category\n!scope=\"col\"| Recipients\n!scope=\"col\"| Result\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\" | [[Filmfare Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[63rd Filmfare Awards|20 January 2018]]\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| ''Hindi Medium''\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"6\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards-2018/nominations|title=Filmfare Awards 2018 \u2013 Winners & Nominees|publisher=[[Filmfare Awards]]|date=20 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715124831/https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards-2018/nominations?year=2017|archivedate=15 July 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actor|Best Actor (Critics)]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Saba Qamar]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Deepak Dobriyal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\" | [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[19th IIFA Awards|22\u201324 June 2018]]\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| ''Hindi Medium''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-nominations-2018-tumhari-sulu-leads-with-7-nods-newton-follows-1855889|title=IIFA Nominations 2018: Tumhari Sulu Leads With 7 Nods, Newton Follows|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=22 May 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625104200/https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/iifa-nominations-2018-tumhari-sulu-leads-with-7-nods-newton-follows-1855889|archivedate=25 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iifa.com/awards2018|title=IIFA Awards 2018 Winners|publisher=[[International Indian Film Academy Awards]]|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190312152519/https://www.iifa.com/awards2018|archivedate=12 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[IIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Deepak Dobriyal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Mirchi Music Awards]]\n| [[10th Mirchi Music Awards|28 January 2018]]\n| [[Mirchi Music Award for Music Composer of The Year|Music Composer of The Year]]\n| [[Sachin\u2013Jigar]] for \"Hoor\"\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|title=Nominations \u2013 Mirchi Music Awards|publisher=[[Mirchi Music Awards]]|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325084119/http://www.mirchimusicawards.com/hindi-2017/nominations/|archivedate=25 March 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Screen Awards]]\n| 2 December 2017\n| [[Screen Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/star-screen-awards-2017-vidya-balan-rajkummar-rao-full-winners-list-1099753-2017-12-04|title=Star Screen Awards 2017: Dangal wins big, Vidya Balan-Rajkummar Rao named best actor and actress|newspaper=India Today|date=4 December 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407090920/https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/star-screen-awards-2017-vidya-balan-rajkummar-rao-full-winners-list-1099753-2017-12-04|archivedate=7 April 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\" | [[Zee Cine Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 30 December 2017\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Film|Best Film (Viewer's Choice)]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''Hindi Medium''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"6\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zeecineawards.com/timeline/2018/winners/|title=Zee Cine Awards 2018 \u2013 Winners & Nominees|publisher=[[Zee Cine Awards]]|date=30 December 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604203215/http://www.zeecineawards.com/timeline/2018/winners/|archivedate=4 June 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Film|Best Film (Jury's Choice)]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Critics Award for Best Actor \u2013 Male|Best Actor \u2013 Male]]\n| [[Irrfan Khan]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role \u2013 Male|Best Actor in a Supporting Role \u2013 Male]]\n| [[Deepak Dobriyal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Zee Cine Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| [[Saket Chaudhary]], Zeenat Lakhani\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main article|Angrezi Medium}}\nAfter the success of ''Hindi Medium'', a sequel to the film was planned. Regarding the success of the film, producer Vijan told ''[[Mid Day]]'', \"The response we have got is phenomenal. The entire unit of ''Hindi Medium'', including Irrfan and Saba, who look cool as a couple on-screen, should be repeated in a film. There is definitely scope for a sequel. We would certainly explore it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-hindi-medium-sequel-dinesh-vijan-bollywood-news/18345177|title=Irrfan Khan and Saba Qamar's 'Hindi Medium' to have a sequel|newspaper=Mid Day|date=17 June 2017|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106184234/https://www.mid-day.com/articles/irrfan-khan-saba-qamar-hindi-medium-sequel-dinesh-vijan-bollywood-news/18345177|archivedate=6 January 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 24 January 2018, Vijan confirmed the sequel to [[Times Now]]. He said, \"We have just finished typing the second part\", with \"Just finishing touches are being put\", however, \"I think you will have to wait for an official announcement for that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/hindi-medium-sequel-scripting-done-announcement-on-star-cast-to-follow-soon/192153|title=Exclusive \u2013 Hindi Medium sequel: Scripting done, announcement on star cast to follow soon|publisher=Times Now|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406060243/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/hindi-medium-sequel-scripting-done-announcement-on-star-cast-to-follow-soon/192153|archivedate=6 April 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2019, it was announced that [[Kareena Kapoor]] has been added to the cast of the sequel to play the role of a police officer and filming will start from April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kareena-kapoor-khan-reportedly-roped-in-to-play-a-cop-in-hindi-medium-sequel-starring-irrfan-khan-6357521.html|title=Kareena Kapoor Khan reportedly roped in to play a cop in Hindi Medium sequel, starring Irrfan Khan|newspaper=Firstpost|date=30 March 2019|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522090029/https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/kareena-kapoor-khan-reportedly-roped-in-to-play-a-cop-in-hindi-medium-sequel-starring-irrfan-khan-6357521.html|archivedate=22 May 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 5 April, the sequel's title was announced as ''[[Angrezi Medium]]'' and filming began in [[Udaipur]]. This was completed in July.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://m.timesofindia.com/videos/entertainment/hindi/angrezi-medium-wrap-up-homi-adajania-thanks-irrfan-khan-team/amp_videoshow/70205034.cms |title='Angrezi Medium' wrap-up: Homi Adajania gets emotional, hugs Irrfan Khan|date=13 July 2019 |work=The Times of India|accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/irrfan-khan-finally-back-to-work-begins-shooting-for-angrezi-medium-in-udaipur-first-photos/394850|title=Irrfan Khan back to work, begins shooting for Hindi Medium sequel, Angrezi Medium in Udaipur \u2013 first photos|publisher=Times Now|date=5 April 2019|accessdate=15 July 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406060234/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/irrfan-khan-finally-back-to-work-begins-shooting-for-angrezi-medium-in-udaipur-first-photos/394850|archivedate=6 April 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 17 February 2020, the film's release date was changed to 13 March 2020 from the earlier release date of 20 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/angrezi-medium-to-release-a-week-earlier-on-march-13-gunjan-saxena-delayed-for-a-month-1647277-2020-02-17|work= India Today|date=17 February 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|title=''Angrezi Medium'' to release a week earlier on March 13, Gunjan Saxena delayed by a month}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Bollywood films of 2017]]\n{{Portalbar|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt5764096}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|hindi_medium}}\n\n{{Saket Chaudhary}}\n{{Filmfare Award for Best Film}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about the education system in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Amar Mohile]]\n[[Category:T-Series films]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindi_Medium"}
{"title_page": "Fulk FitzWarin", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Arms of Fitzwarin.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of FitzWarin: ''Quarterly per fess indented argent and gules'' <ref>Arms of Fulk V FitzWarin, St George's [[Roll of Arms]], 1285, briantimms.com, St George's Roll, part 1, no. E69</ref>]]\n'''Fulk III FitzWarin''' (c. 1160\u20131258), variant spellings, [[List of Latinised names|Latinized]] as ''Fulco filius Warini'', was a powerful [[marcher lord]] seated at [[Whittington Castle]] in [[Shropshire]] on the English border with [[Wales]], and at [[Alveston]] in [[Gloucestershire]]. He rebelled against [[John, King of England|King John]] (1199\u20131216) from 1200 to 1203,<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\">Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British outlaws of literature and history: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), p. 97</ref> mainly over a dispute concerning his familial right to Whittington Castle, and was declared an [[outlaw]]. Between 1221 and 1226 he founded [[Alberbury Priory]] in Shropshire, which was the smallest and last of the three English houses dependent upon the [[Order of Grandmont]].\n\nAfter his death Fulk became the subject of a popular \"ancestral romance\" in French verse, ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', relating his life as an outlaw and his struggle to regain his patrimony from the king.<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club, [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up (London 1855)] (Internet Archive).</ref> This survives in a prose version, and combines historical material with [[legend]]ary and fantastical elements which are heroic rather than strictly biographical. His grandson was [[Fulk V FitzWarin, 1st Baron FitzWarin]] (1251\u20131315).<ref>[[George Cokayne|George Edward Cokayne]] ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', ed. Vicary Gibbs; vol. V, p. 495, Baron FitzWarin</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe patriarch of the Fitz-Warins was considered to be \"Warin of Metz\", from [[Lorraine (duchy)|Lorraine]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\">G.E. Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage'', V, p. 495, note (c)</ref><ref>Suppe, F., 'Fitzwarine family (per. c. 1145-1315)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004), Vol. \"F\", pp.&nbsp;953\u20134.</ref> His son was [[Fulk I FitzWarin]] (d.1170/1) of Whittington and Alveston (\"Fitz-\" being the Norman French equivalent of modern French \"Fils\", i.e. \"son of\"). Fulk's son and heir Fulk II FitzWarin (died 1197) was a [[marcher lord]] of Shropshire,<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins Press 1964), p. 49</ref> and married Hawise le Dinan, a daughter and\nco-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\">G.E. Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage'', V, p. 495, note (c)</ref> Their son was Fulk FitzWarin III.\n\nWarin (Guarine) of Metz the patriarch is however a \"shadowy or [[myth]]ical figure\",<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\"/> about whom little is certain. The later mediaeval romance ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'' gives his name as \"Warin de Meer\". Whatever his true place of origin it is however generally believed that the head of the Warin family came to England during the reign of [[William the Conqueror]] (1066\u20131087). Neither the father nor his sons were, during that reign, [[tenant-in-chief|tenants-in-chief]] (i.e. important [[vassal]]s or [[English feudal barony|feudal barons]]): rather, their grants of lands were obtained from later kings.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 34</ref>\n\nFulk I (died 1170/1) was rewarded by King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189) for his support of the king's mother [[Empress Matilda]] in [[The Anarchy|her civil war]] with [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] (1135\u20131154): in 1153 Henry conferred upon him the royal [[manor]] of [[Alveston]] in Gloucestershire and in 1149 the manor of Whadborough (in [[Loddington, Leicestershire|Loddington]]<ref>J. Nichols, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester'', Vol. 3 part 1: East Goscote Hundred (John Nichols, London 1800), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000032377095&view=1up&seq=476 pp. 332-34] (Hathi Trust).</ref>), Leicestershire. Fulk II [[Feudal land tenure in England|held]] those properties after the death of his father in 1171.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 34, 35</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===The lordship of Whittington===\nAt some time before 1178 Fulk II (d. 1197) married Hawise de Dinan, a wealthy heiress, a daughter and co-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]].<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-qfHDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT49#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 49] (Google).</ref> Josce held [[Ludlow Castle]] in the Welsh Marches for the [[Empress Matilda]], daughter of King [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] (1100\u20131135), during the civil war (the \"[[The Anarchy|Anarchy]]\") between herself and [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]] (1135\u20131154) arising from their struggle for the throne.<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zvzWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PAxi p. xi] (Google, no preview).</ref>\n \nThroughout his lifetime, Fulk II encountered many problems in receiving his patrimony and his other claims to land. These disputes concerned estates his father held [[Tenant-in-chief|in chief]] from the crown, but also others which he had held from [[Honour of Peverel|the Peverel family]] as [[Lord|overlords]]. They included particularly [[Whittington Castle]], held by the Peverels during the reign of King Stephen. Whittington Castle stands on the English side of [[Offa's Dyke]], which before and during the Norman era formed the border between England and [[Wales]]. The site was fortified with a castle by [[William Peverel the Younger]] in 1138 in support of the Empress Matilda.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 35</ref>\n\nIn the late 1140s the [[Marcher lord|lordship]] of [[Whittington, Shropshire|Whittington]], as with [[Oswestry]] and Overton, ceased to be part of England and became a Welsh [[marcher lord]]ship within the [[Kingdom of Powys]].<ref>P. Brown, P. King, and P. Remfry, 'Whittington Castle: The marcher fortress of the Fitz Warin family', ''Shropshire Archaeology and History'' LXXIX (2004), pp. 106\u2013127.</ref> In 1165 [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] granted the castle of Whittington to [[Roger de Powis]], a Welsh leader, and in about 1173 gave him funds for its repair.<ref>D. Stephenson, ''Medieval Powys: Kingdom, Principality and Lordships, 1132-1293'' (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6ERJDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA286#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 286] (Google); citing F. Suppe, 'Roger of Powys, Henry II's Anglo-Welsh Middleman, and His Lineage', ''The Welsh History Review'', Vol. 21 part 1 (2002), pp. 1-23.</ref> Roger de Powis was succeeded by his son Meurig (Maurice), and he in turn by his son Werennoc. \n\nAlthough Fulk II won the right to Whittington in or about 1195, he never received formal legal ''[[seisin]]'', and it remained in Welsh hands at the time of his death in 1197.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 35</ref> After the death of his father, Fulk III maintained his father's claim to Whittington,<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\">Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', p. 52</ref> and in 1197 he offered [[feudal relief|relief]] of \u00a3100 for it as his inheritance. However, on 11 April 1200 [[John, King of England|King John]] granted it to Maurice (son of Roger of Powis), who had offered half that sum. Again, after Maurice's death in August 1200, King John granted it to Maurice's heirs.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 36</ref><ref>If Fulk was really that \"Warin of London\" at whose bidding one William Brunus was killed in 1199 in an affray at Dublin Castle, and who was ordered to undergo trial by fire, some cause for his disfavour might be inferred. See Plea in F. Palgrave (ed.), ''Rotuli Curi\u00e6 Regis'', II: The First Year of King John (Commissioners, 1835), [https://archive.org/details/rotulicuriregis01commgoog/page/n206/mode/2up pp. 172-73] (Internet Archive): transcript, translation and attribution in J.S. Furlong, ''A Treatise on the Law of Landlord and Tenant'', 2 vols (Hodges and Smith, Dublin  1845), II: Appendix Pt. VI, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bYIDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1251#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1251-53] (Google).</ref>\n\n===Rebellions===\nIt is not known why King John refused to recognise Fulk's claim to Whittington as his rightful inheritance, but by April 1201 Fulk was in open rebellion against the King. He was accompanied by approximately fifty-two followers including his brothers William, Phillip and John, by his cousins, and by the family's many tenants and allies in the Marches.<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\"/>\n\nFulk's rebellion is not related in detail by chroniclers, but it was clearly considerable, for in the spring of 1201, when King John crossed into [[Normandy]] and [[Poitou]] to suppress a revolt by the [[Lusignan dynasty|Lusignans]],<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', p. 157</ref> he ordered [[Hubert de Burgh, 1st Earl of Kent|Hubert de Burgh]] with 100 knights to counter the rebellion of Fulk and of William Marsh, a [[Somerset]]shire knight who was raiding shipping off the coast of [[Devon]].<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', pp. 48, 84</ref> In July 1202 Fulk and his men were reported to have taken refuge in [[Stanley Abbey]] in Wiltshire. Another man, Gilbert de Duure, is mentioned in records as \"...having been an outlaw associated with Fulk Fitz Warin\". One other, Eustace de Kivilly, had been pardoned earlier in 1202 by King John for \"being associated with Fulk\".<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 38</ref>\n\n===Settlement and status===\nAfter years as an outlaw, on 11 November 1203 Fulk was pardoned, together with over thirty of his followers including his brothers William, Phillip and John, and their cousins. In October 1204, on payment of a fine of 200 marks, Fulk at last received \"right and inheritance\" in Whittington.<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), p. xii.</ref> The castle thereafter descended in the [[Baron FitzWarin|FitzWarin family]], all subsequent holders bearing the first-name Fulk, until the death of [[Fulk XI FitzWarin, 7th Baron FitzWarin]] (1405\u20131420) in 1420.<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', pp. 51\u201352</ref>\n\nThe high regard in which Fulk III was held by many of the king's barons in 1207 is shown by the names of the men who stood surety for the fine of 1,200 marks demanded of him to marry [[Maud le Vavasour|Maud (Matilda)]], the heiress daughter of Robert le Vavasour and relict of [[Theobald Walter, 1st Chief Butler of Ireland|Theobald Walter]].<ref>T.D. Hardy, ''Rotuli de Oblatis et Finibus in Turri Londinensi Asservati, tempore Regis Johannis'' (Commissioners, 1835), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RqEUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA405#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 405-06] (Google).</ref> The suretors included the Peverels, [[Alan Basset]], [[William de Braose (died 1230)]], a de Lacy, [[William Longesp\u00e9e, 3rd Earl of Salisbury]] and [[Henry de Bohun, 1st Earl of Hereford]].<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 39</ref> On 9 February 1214, when King John again set sail for [[Poitou]], Fulk was among the barons who accompanied him. He is believed then to have been  a vassal of [[Geoffrey FitzGeoffrey de Mandeville, 2nd Earl of Essex|Geoffrey de Mandeville]], Earl of Gloucester.<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', pp. 280, 294.</ref>\n\n===Further confrontations===\nIn 1215 Fulk was one of many giving great trouble to the [[Sheriff of Shropshire]]. Before the accession of the infant king [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] (John's son) in 1216, Fulk's manor of Alveston had already been seized by the crown: in the following year (1217) all of his other lands in Gloucestershire were likewise seized. By 1218, however, Fulk had made peace and his lands were ordered to be restored to him by the king's regents:<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 41, 43</ref> his market at his manor of [[Narborough, Leicestershire]], was withdrawn from him as \"a manifest enemy\" of the king's in 1217,<ref>T.D. Hardy, ''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum in Turri Londinensi Asservati'', 2 vols (Commissioners, 1833), I: 1204-1224, [https://digitale-bibliothek-mv.de/viewer/image/PPN848631250/379/ p. 321] (Mecklenberg Verpommern Digital).</ref> but regranted in 1218. In the latter year the king also granted a fair for his manor of [[Lambourn]] in Berkshire,<ref>Fine Rolls, 3 Henry III, ref C 60/11, [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_011.html nos. 436 and 437], image at [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_011.html m. 1] (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> which Fulk's mother Hawise and her sister Sybil (de Plugenet) had inherited in two parts from Joce de Dinant. Hawise died at about this time.<ref>'Parishes: Lambourn', in W. Page and P.H. Ditchfield (eds), ''A History of the County of Berkshire'', Vol. 4, ed. (London, 1924), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/berks/vol4/pp251-266 pp. 251-66] (British History Online).</ref> \n\nBy 1220 Fulk had regained some favour with the young King Henry III and had been allowed to rebuild and fortify Whittington,<ref>T.D. Hardy (ed.), ''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum in Turri Londinensi Asservati'' (Commissioners, 1833), I: 1204-1224, [https://digitale-bibliothek-mv.de/viewer/fullscreen/PPN848631250/518/ p. 460] (Mecklenberg Verpommern).</ref> and to hold a weekly market and annual two-day fair there.<ref>Fine Rolls, 4 Henry III, ref C 60/12, [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_012.html item 16], image at [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/fimages/C60_12/m09.html m. 9] (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> In 1223 however Whittington Castle fell to [[Llywelyn the Great]], Prince of Wales. Fulk regained it the following year, although his disputes with Llywelyn continued and more of Fulk's lands were seized. By 1228 a truce seems to have been reached between Fulk and Llywelyn following the intervention of the king.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 41-42</ref><ref>I.J. Sanders, 'Fitz Warin lords of Whittington and Alderbury (Salop) and Alveston (Gloucs.)', ''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig '' (1959), [https://biography.wales/article/s-FITZ-WAR-1130 (Welsh Dictionary of National Biography online)].</ref>\n\nThroughout these years Fulk's relations with the King were changeable and seemed to be directly dependent on the state of affairs in Wales. As a marcher lord Fulk's role as a protector of the English border against the Welsh was vital to the English King. He arbitrated several border disputes on behalf of the King and although there were more personal disagreements, there were no more rebellions on the part of Fulk III.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 42, 43, 45</ref>\n\n===Alberbury Priory===\nBetween 1221 and 1226 Fulk began to build his priory at [[Alberbury Priory|Alberbury]] on a moated site at a bend in the [[river Severn]] on the border of England and Wales.<ref>M.J. Angold, G.C. Baugh, M.M. Chibnall, D.C. Cox, D.T.W. Price, M. Tomlinson and B.S. Trinder, 'House of Grandmontine monks: Priory of Alberbury', in A.T. Gaydon and R.B. Pugh, ''A History of the County of Shropshire'', Vol. 2 (V.C.H., London 1973), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol2/pp47-50 pp. 47-50] (British History Online): citing the Alberbury documents in the muniments of All Souls' College, Oxford.</ref> He first intended it as a house of [[Augustinian canons]] following the [[Arrouaise Abbey|Arrouasian rule]], and invited Alan, the Abbot of [[Lilleshall Abbey|Lilleshall]], to establish the convent. However his endowments were found insufficient, and Alan's successor Abbot William renounced any interest in the project.<ref>R. Graham and A.W. Clapham, 'Alberbury Priory', ''Transactions of the Shropshire Archaeological and Natural History Society'', Series 4 vol. XI (1927-1928), pp. 257-303.</ref> Fulk therefore turned instead to the [[Grandmontines|Grandmontine Order]], following the example of [[Walter de Lacy, Lord of Meath|Walter de Lacy]]'s house founded at [[Craswall Priory]] in [[Herefordshire]] c. 1220-1225, but placing Alberbury under the immediate authority of Grandmont Abbey in [[Limousin]].<ref>'The Order of Grandmont and its houses in England', in R. Graham, ''English Ecclesiastical Studies, being Some Essays in Research in Mediaeval History'' (S.P.C.K., London 1929), pp. 209-46.</ref> In addition to the priory site with its lands and rights in Alberbury with Pecknall, a fishery in the Severn, and the right to construct mills, Fulk's endowments included his manor of Whadborough at Loddington in eastern Leicestershire. These were confirmed by King Henry III's charter of 1232.<ref>'Priory of Alberbury, or Abberbury, in Shropshire', in W. Dugdale, ''Monasticon Anglicanum'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nllVAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1031#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1031-1032, Num. I] (Google); ''Calendar of Charter Rolls, Henry III'', 1226-1257 (HMSO 1903), [https://archive.org/details/calendarofcharte01grea/page/172/mode/2up p. 172] (Internet Archive).</ref>\n\n===Estates and suits===\nIn 1226 Maud the wife of Fulk FitzWarin died, which was no doubt a stimulus to the completion of the priory, where she was buried.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\">Emma Cavell, 'The Burial of Noblewomen in Thirteenth-Century Shropshire,' in B. Weiler, J. Burton, P. Schofield and K. St\u00f6ber (eds), ''Thirteenth Century England'' XI (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge 2007), p. 174 & note 2.</ref> In that year Theobald Walter the younger (son of Maud's first marriage) unsuccessfully challenged William Pantolf and Hawise his wife for title to the manor of Narborough in Leicestershire,<ref>T.D. Hardy (ed.), ''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum in Turri Londinensi Asservati'', II: 1224-1227 (Commissioners, 1844), [https://digitale-bibliothek-mv.de/viewer/image/PPN848631404/153/ p. 147 b] (Mecklenberg Verpommern Digital).</ref> a Vavasour hereditament.<ref>W. Farrer and C.T. Clay, ''Early Yorkshire Charters'', XI: The Percy Fee (Cambridge University Press, 1963 edition), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EkB2UdPlD4sC&pg=PA130#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 130] (Google).</ref> Fulke's market at Narborough had received the Kings re-confirmation in 1220, but it is shown in a suit of 1276 that the manor had been given by Maud to her daughter Hawise,<ref>\"Robertus [Vavasor] dedit premissa Matilde filie sue; que dedit premissa Hawisie filie sue\": Plea quoted in 'Narborough', in J. Nichols, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester'', Reprint, 4 volumes in 8 (John Nichols, London 1811/Leicester County Council with S.R. Publishing Ltd., 1971), Vol. 4 Part 2: Sparkenhoe Hundred, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000001252729&view=1up&seq=584 at p. 814] (Hathi Trust).</ref> who by her marriage to Pantolf became Lady of the barony of [[Wem]],<ref>I.J. Sanders, ''English Baronies: A Study of Their Origin and Descent 1086\u20131327'' (Clarendon Press, Oxford 1960), pp. 94-95.</ref>, as the ''FitzWarin Romance'' reminds us.<ref>R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1858), VII, pp. 66-83, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6UtNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA75#v=onepage&q&f=false at pp. 75-76] (Google).</ref> Theobald simultaneously challenged Fulk for the manor of [[Edlington]] in Yorkshire, another part of the same inheritance.<ref>''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum'', II, p. 147 b (as above).</ref> After Pantolf died in 1233, and Fulk paid 600 marks for custody of his heirs and lands,<ref>Fine Rolls, 17 Henry III, ref. C 60/32, [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_032.html item 108], image at [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/fimages/C60_32/m08.html m. 8] (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> Hawise remarried to Hubert Husse, taking Narborough as her ''maritagium'' with her, and in 1235 Hubert obtained a renewal of the market, which had by then lapsed.<ref>''Close Rolls of the Reign of Henry III'', 1234-1237 (HMSO 1908), [https://archive.org/details/closerollsreign00britgoog/page/n240/mode/2up p. 210] (Internet Archive).</ref><ref>\"Rex concessit Huberto Hues' quod mercatum quod consuevit aliquando teneri apud manerium de Northbrug' (manerio illo existente in manu Fulconis filii Warini) et quod postea decidit, iterum relevetur et teneatur...\" There is no indication here that Fulke had died.</ref>\n\nIn 1227 the fair at Lambourn was re-granted, <ref>''Calendar of Charter Rolls, Henry III'', 1226-1257 (HMSO 1903), [https://archive.org/details/calendarofcharte01grea/page/58/mode/2up p. 58] (Internet Archive).</ref> Before 1224 [[William Marshal, Earl of Pembroke]] had by his charter<ref>Recited in ''Placita de Quo Warranto Temporibus Edw. I, II & III'' (Commissioners, 1818), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924082447990&view=1up&seq=113 pp. 81-82] (Hathi Trust).</ref> enfeoffed Fulk III in the nearby manor of [[Wantage]], Berkshire and in the Hundred of Wantage and ''Gamenefeud'': for although the King's attorney later challenged the FitzWarin right to the Hundreds, they remained in their hands.<ref>'Wantage Hundred: Introduction', in W. Page and P.H. Ditchfield (eds), ''A History of the County of Berkshire'', Vol. 4  (London, 1924), [https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/berks/vol4/pp267-268 pp. 267-68] (British History Online).</ref> The King claimed Wantage manor against him as ''terra Flandrensium'' - the land of Robert de B\u00e9thune - in 1236-37,<ref>F.W. Maitland (ed.), ''Bracton's Note Book: A Collection of Cases Decided in the King's Courts during the Reign of Henry the Third'', 3 Vols (C.J. Clay & Sons, London 1887), III, [https://archive.org/details/bractonsnoteboo03maitgoog/page/n245/mode/2up No. 1220, pp. 232-34] (Internet Archive).</ref> but his possession of it was warranted by [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert Marshal]],<ref>''Placitorum in Domo Capitulari Westmonasteriensi Asservati Abbreviatio'' (Commissioners, 1811), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=epk0AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA105#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 105] (Google).</ref> and he defended his possession again in 1241 against Robert de B\u00e9thune himself.<ref>'Parishes: Wantage', ''A History of the County of Berkshire'', Vol. 4, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/berks/vol4/pp319-332 pp. 319-32] (British History Online).</ref> In due course Fulk by charter granted his entire manor of Lambourn to his daughter Mabil and to the heirs of her body, and made acknowledgement of the fact before the Court of King's Bench in 1249.<ref>J. Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf and Fitz Warin Families, 1066-1272'' (University of Nebraska Press, Lincoln 1980), p. 96.</ref> \n\n===The second marriage===\nMabil was the daughter of Fulk's second wife, Clarice de Auberville, who (as the [[Fine rolls]] record) was certainly living in 1250.<ref>Fine Rolls, C 60/47, [http://www.finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_047.html 34 Henry III, membrane 2, no. 786], i.e. the penultimate entry in the membrane imaged as [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/fimages/C60_47/m16.html \"m. 16\"]. (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> The marriage features in the Romance narrative, which calls her \"une molt gentile dame\", and is said to have occurred \"a good while\" after the death of Maud. The legend tells that after their marriage Fulk was struck blind for the last seven years of his life, and that he outlived Clarice by one year.<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club (London 1855): [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up see pp. 177-83] (Internet Archive).</ref> It has been accepted that Clarice was the daughter (rather than the widow) of Sir [[Robert de Auberville]], of [[Iden, Sussex|Iden]] and Iham (Higham, in [[Icklesham]]<ref>i.e. the settlement around the now demolished church of St Leonard, immediately north-west of New Winchelsea. 'Higham, (\"Iham\" or \"Ihomme\"), an old name of Winchelsea' - E. Ekwall, ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-Names'', 4th edition (Clarendon Press, Oxford 1960), p. 238.</ref>), near [[Winchelsea]], Sussex.<ref>W. Dugdale, ''The Baronage of England After the Norman Conquest'' (Thomas Newcomb, for Abel Roper, John Martin and Herny Herringman, London 1675-76), I, [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A36794.0001.001/1:6.129?rgn=div2;view=fulltext pp. 443-47] (Umich/eebo); R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1858), VII, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6UtNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 66-83, esp. p. 76 notes 52 and 53] (Google).</ref> Sir Robert, of an influential Norman family, was a grandson of [[Ranulf de Glanvill]], and on the death of his father William, c. 1195, became a ward of [[Hubert Walter]]'s.<ref>S.J. Bailey, 'Ranulf de Glanvill and His Children', ''The Cambridge Law Journal'' Vol. 15, No. 2 (Nov., 1957), pp. 163-182, at p. 186 note 51.</ref> He was a Constable of [[Hastings Castle]], and Keeper of the Coast in 1228-1229. Robert's wife Clarice was daughter of Robert and granddaughter of Samson de Gestling, patrons of [[Robertsbridge Abbey]].<ref>'Quitclaim', The National Archives Discovery Catalogue, item description: [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/0b6b4574-0f22-4cdf-8c89-1c12dde9a4de CCA-DCc-ChAnt/A/117] (Canterbury Cathedral Archives). See also C.T. Flower (ed.), ''Curia Regis Rolls: 7-9 Henry III'' (HMSO 1955), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=nXVpAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sansonem p. 325] (Google snippet).</ref> Robert de Auberville is supposed to have died c. 1230.<ref>G. Paget, ''An Official, Genealogical and Heraldic Baronage of England'' (1957), 11: 1-2.</ref> \n\nIn 1230 Fulk commenced a suit against Philip de Burwardsley (i.e. of Broseley, Shropshire), apparently a FitzWarin cousin, concerning lands in Shropshire and Staffordshire which had been disputed between their grandfathers, and which did not come to a full Assize until after 1233.<ref>R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1855), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-oFJAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 10-11] (Google).</ref><ref>'Banco Rolls no. 6. Tower Records (April 1231)', in G. Wrottesley (ed.), 'Plea Rolls for Staffordshire: 1231-39', ''Staffordshire Historical Collections'', IV (London 1883), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/staffs-hist-collection/vol4/pp81-89 p. 81] (British History Online).</ref>\n\n===Service===\nFulk attended the King's court in Westminster in October 1229:<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'Carta concessa David filio Lewelini, nepoti Regis', in T. Rymer and R. Sanderson, ed. A. Clarke and F. Holbrooke, ''Foedera, Conventiones, Litterae, et cujuscunque generis Acta Publica'', New Edition, 4 Vols in 8 (London 1816), I Part 1: 1066-1272, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=340 p. 196] (Hathi Trust).</ref> he received a writ of protection during absence upon foreign service (given at Portsmouth) in April 1230, and was required to supply one knight for foreign service in aid of the Earl of Bretaigne in May 1234.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'De auxilio comiti Brittanniae ferendo', in Rymer, ''Foedera'', I Part 1, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=356 p. 212] (Hathi Trust).</ref> In July 1236 he was appointed one of the Arbitrators (for North Wales) of the truce between King Henry and Llywelyn, as William FitzWarin was among those for South Wales.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'De treugis ex parte Lewelini', in Rymer, ''Foedera'', I Part 1, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=374 p. 230] (Hathi Trust).</ref> In March 1238 he was among the powerful men summoned by the King to Oxford, to deliberate upon Llywelyn's action in causing his son [[Dafydd ap Llywelyn|Dafydd]] to receive homage from the magnates of Gwynedd and Powys.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'De treugis Walliae', in Rymer, ''Foedera'', I Part 1, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=379 p. 235] (Hathi Trust).</ref> The Romance narrative tells that, after the death of [[Joan, Lady of Wales|Joan, Lady of Snowdon]] in 1237 (who was buried at [[Beaumaris]]), [[Llywelyn ap Iorwerth]] took Eva, daughter of Fulk, as his last wife: and after Llywelyn's death in 1240, she remarried to William de Blancmouster (de Whitchurch).<ref>T.W. King, 'On the coats of arms appropriated to the Welsh princes', ''Archaeologia, or Miscellaneous Tracts Relating to Antiquity'' XXIX (London 1842), Appendix, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H1NIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA407#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 407-13] (Google).</ref>\n\nIn June 1245, faced by the rapacity of the [[Papal nuncio]] Martin (resulting in a prohibition of [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]]), an assembly of nobles at [[Dunstable]] and Linton deputed Fulk to proceed to London to order Martin out of the kingdom. As [[Matthew Paris]] relates their interview, Fulk told him to leave England immediately, but Martin questioned his authority to demand it. Fulk told him to be off within three days if he did not wish to be utterly brought down, and withdrew in anger, heaping threats upon threats with a terrible oath against him. Martin hurried off to the king, who told him that he had brought the kingdom to the brink of revolt: being asked for safe conduct the King answered, \"May the Devil take you to hell.\"<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing H.R. Luard (ed.), ''Matthaei Parisiensis, Monachus Sancti Albani, Chronica Majora'', Volume IV: 1240-1247, Rerum Britannicarum Medii Aevi Scriptores - Rolls Series (Longman & Co., Tr\u00fcbner & Co., London 1877) [https://archive.org/details/matthiparisiens03luargoog/page/n446/mode/2up pp. 420-21] (Internet Archive).</ref> A week later Fulk witnessed a charter of the King's at Windsor.\n\n===Last controversies===\nAlthough Fulk seems certainly to have lived after 1250, in this late period it is increasingly difficult to distinguish him from his two sons named Fulk, among the various references to Fulk \"senior\" and \"junior\". At a Shropshire Assize of January 1256 it was probably the younger son Fulk (called Fulk Glas) who, claiming that [[Corbet family#History|Thomas Corbet]] had disseised him of his free tenement of Alberbury, became enraged when Corbet referred to his father as \"Proditor\" (Traitor), renounced any homage that he had made to Corbet, and vowed never to hold land of him again.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, pp. 80-81, citing Shropshire Assize Rolls, The National Archives (UK), ref. JUST 1/734, rot. 15 front. View original at [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT4/JUST1/JUST1no734/aJUST1no734fronts/IMG_0920.htm AALT image 0920] (last full entry): \"ita quod idem Thomas vocavit Fulconem patrem ipsius Fulconis proditorem...\", etc.</ref> The Hundred Feodary of 1255 showed that Fulk FitzWarin held two [[hide (unit)|hides]] [[Land Tax|geldable]] in Alberbury of the fee of Caus (of which Thomas Corbet of [[Caus Castle]] was lord), and that the Grandmontensian brothers there held two [[virgate]]s by the gift of Fulk FitzWarin ''senior'' (i.e. Fulk III in 1232), and of the fee of Caus.<ref>'Hundredum de Forde, Com. Salop.', in ''Rotuli Hundredorum Temp. Hen. III & Edw. I'' (Commissioners, 1818), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wBtDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA66#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 66-67] (Google).</ref> The services owing by Fulk FitzWarin for a knight's fee held from Corbet at Alberbury had been set forth in a concord of 1248,<ref>Feet of Fines, ref. CP 25(1)/193/4, no. 31: view original at [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/CP25(1)/CP25_1_193_4/IMG_0324.htm AALT].</ref> the Fine for which was recorded in the Pipe Roll for 1250 and remained unpaid in 1252.\n\nIn 1245 the king had appointed Fulk FitzWarin, John le Strange and Henry de Audley to settle a land-dispute between Gruffydd ap Madog, whose land had been seized by [[Dafydd ap Llywelyn]] during the king's last war, and which had been seized back from Dafydd and was now claimed by [[Gruffydd ap Gwenwynwyn]]<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Henry III'', 1232-1247 (HMSO 1906), [https://archive.org/details/patentrollsreig01lytegoog/page/n490/mode/2up p. 466] (Internet Archive).</ref> (whose mother was Margaret Corbet, and whose wife Hawise was daughter of John le Strange of [[Knockin Castle]]). On the occasion of Thomas Corbet's outrageous accusation, in 1255, the court had been been hearing and attempting to settle contentions between Thomas Corbet and Gruffydd ap Gwenwynwyn.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, pp. 80-81, citing Shropshire Assize, as above; ''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Henry III'', 1247-1258 (HMSO 1908), [https://archive.org/details/patentrollsreig00offigoog/page/n449/mode/2up p. 438] (Internet Archive).</ref> In time, Gruffydd's daughter Margaret became the wife of [[Fulk FitzWarin, 1st Baron FitzWarin|Fulk V FitzWarin]], son of Fulk IV.\n\n==Marriages and progeny==\nFulk III FitzWarin married, in about 1207, to [[Maud le Vavasour, Baroness Butler|Maud le Vavasour]] (d.1226), (''alias'' Matilda), daughter of Robert le Vavasour and widow of the powerful Lancashire baron Theobald Walter.<ref>G.E. Cokayne, ed. Vicary Gibbs, ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', Vol. II (The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., London 1912), p. 448</ref> He secured pledges for the marriage from his brother William and from Maud's father, Robert le Vavasour, who was a tenant of the [[English feudal barony|feudal barony]] of [[Skipton]] in Yorkshire.<ref>Max Lieberman, ''The Medieval Marches of Wales: The Creation and Perception of a Frontier, 1066'' (Cambridge University Press 2010), pp. 87-97</ref><ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/> Maud died in 1226 and was buried at Alberbury Priory (''alias'' New Abbey, Alberbury) in Shropshire.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/><ref>Sir Bernard Burke, C.B., LL.D., Ulster King of Arms, ''Genealogical History of the Dormant, Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire'', (Burke's Peerage/Genealogical Publishing Co., 1883), Reprinted 1985; 1996; p. 213</ref><ref>G.E. Cokayne, ed. Vicary Gibbs, ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', Volume II: Bass to Canning (The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., London 1912), p. 448</ref> They had the following progeny:\n* Fulk IV FitzWarin (d.1264).<ref name=\"BWF37\">Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 37</ref> He received the manor of Edlington, Yorkshire, as part of his inheritance.<ref>W. Farrer and C.T. Clay (eds), ''Early Yorkshire Charters'', XI: The Percy Fee (Cambridge University Press, 1963), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EkB2UdPlD4sC&pg=PA121#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 119-22] (Google).</ref> He married Constance de Tosny.\n* Fulk Glas<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n* Hawise FitzWarin, married (first) William Pantulf, a [[Marcher Lord]] (who died in 1233), and (secondly) Hubert Huse.<ref name=\"BWF37\"/> She received the manor of Narborough.\n* Joan FitzWarin<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n* Eva FitzWarin,<ref name=\"BWF37\"/> married (first) c. 1238 to [[Llywelyn ap Iorwerth]] (who died in 1240), and (secondly) William de Blanchminister.\n\nThe Romance narrative attributes to Fulk III FitzWarin a second marriage, to Clarice de Auberville. Clarice is taken to have been the daughter and heiress of [[Robert de Auberville]] of [[Iden, Sussex|Iden]] and Iham (Higham, in [[Icklesham]]<ref>i.e. the settlement around the now demolished church of St Leonard, immediately north-west of New Winchelsea. 'Higham, (\"Iham\" or \"Ihomme\"), an old name of Winchelsea' - E. Ekwall, ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-Names'', 4th edition (Clarendon Press, Oxford 1960), p. 238.</ref>), Sussex, and his wife Claricia de Gestling.<ref>As shown in a deed of quitclaim, see The National Archives Discovery Catalogue, item description: [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/0b6b4574-0f22-4cdf-8c89-1c12dde9a4de CCA-DCc-ChAnt/A/117] (Canterbury Cathedral Archives). See also C.T. Flower (ed.), ''Curia Regis Rolls: 7-9 Henry III'' (HMSO 1955), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=nXVpAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sansonem p. 325] (Google snippet).</ref> The daughter of this marriage was:\n* Mabel FitzWarin (\u22121297), who married (first) William de Crevequer (no issue), and (secondly) John de Tregoz, Lord Tregoz (died before 6 Sept 1300), by whom she had two daughters and coheirs, Clarice and Sybil.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/><ref name=\"BWF37\"/> She received the manor of Lambourn.\n\nThe identification of Clarice as second wife of Fulk III was accepted as factual, in his ''Baronage'', by Sir [[William Dugdale]]<ref>W. Dugdale, ''The Baronage of England After the Norman Conquest'' (Thomas Newcomb, for Abel Roper, John Martin and Herny Herringman, London 1675-76), I, [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A36794.0001.001/1:6.129?rgn=div2;view=fulltext pp. 443-47] (Umich/eebo).</ref> and, despite occasional doubts, later accounts of the family have accepted this precedent.<ref>R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1858), VII, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6UtNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 66-83, esp. p. 76 notes 52 and 53] (Google).</ref>\n\n==Death & burial==\nFulk III lived to a great age. At some time before his death in 1258 he handed over control of a great portion of his responsibilities to his son and heir Fulk IV. In 1252 he made his will in which he stated his wish to be buried at the priory he had founded at Alberbury.<ref>''[http://www.discovershropshire.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/theme:20070423145036 Discover Shropshire'']''</ref>\n\n==Romance of ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''==\nAfter Foulk's death he became the subject of the famous \"ancestral romance\" known as '''''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''''',<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club, [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up (London 1855)] (Internet Archive).</ref> which contains a highly embellished account of his life and family history.<ref>Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L. Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), pp. 99\u201399</ref>\n\nThe biography of Fulk III survives in a French prose \"ancestral [[romance (heroic literature)|romance]]\", extant in a  manuscript containing English, French and [[Latin]] texts, which is based on a lost French verse romance.<ref>The French verse form was seen by Leland: T. Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', 2nd, enlarged edition, 6 vols (W. and J. Richardson, London 1770), I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=376 pp. 236-37, representing fols. 268-69] (Hathi Trust).</ref> A 16th-century summary by [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]] of an otherwise lost [[Middle English]] verse version, ''The Nobile Actes of the Guarines'', has also been preserved.<ref>Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=370 pp. 230-36, representing fols. 261-68] (Hathi Trust).</ref> The work is part of the [[Matter of England]].<ref name=boundaries>Neil Cartlidge ''Boundaries in Medieval Romance'',  D. S. Brewer, 2008, {{ISBN|1-84384-155-X}}, 9781843841555. pp. 29\u201342</ref> The outline of the work is as follows. As a young boy, Fulk was sent to the court of King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189), where he grew up with the king's younger son, the future King [[John of England|John]] (1199\u20131216). John became his enemy after a childhood quarrel during a game of chess. As an adult, King John retained his animosity toward Fulk whom he stripped of his ancestral holdings. Fulk thereupon took to the woods as an outlaw and lived a life of adventure. The story may in fact  have confused aspects of the lives of two FitzWarins, Fulk I (d. 1171) and Fulk II (d. 1197), father and son. The romance of Fulk FitzWarin is noted for its parallels to the legend of [[Robin Hood]].<ref>Introduction to ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', edited by Stephen Knight and Thomas H. Ohlgren, originally published in ''Robin Hood and Other Outlaw Tales'', Kalamazoo, Michigan: Medieval Institute Publications, 1997.</ref>\n\n;Editions\n* F. Michel (ed.), ''Histoire de Foulques Fitz-Warin, d'apr\u00e8s un Manuscrit du Mus\u00e9e Britannique'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZOk9AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false (Silvestre Libraire, Paris 1840)]. (Google) (Edition without translation, but includes the Leland abstracts).\n* T. Wright (ed. and translator), ''The History of Fulk FitzWarin, an Outlawed Baron, in the Reign of King John'', edited from a manuscript preserved in the British Museum, with an English translation and illustrative notes (Printed for the Warton Club, London, 1855). [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/n5/mode/2up at pp.&nbsp;1\u2013183 text, pp.&nbsp;183\u2013231 notes].\n* J. Stephenson (ed. and translator), 'The Legend of Fulk FitzWarin' (parallel French text and English translation), in ''Rerum Britannicarum Medii Aevi Scriptores'', Rolls Series Vol. 66: ''Radulphi de Coggeshall Chronicon Anglicanum'' (etc.) (Longman & Co., Tr\u00fcbner & Co., London 1875), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mdvUAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA277#v=onepage&q&f=false at pp. 277-415] (Google).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Dolmans, Emily, 'Locating the Border: Britain and the Welsh Marches in ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'',' in L. Ashe, W. Scase and D. Lawton (eds), [https://boydellandbrewer.com/new-medieval-literatures-16-hb.html ''New Medieval Literatures 16''] (Boydell and Brewer, 2016), pp. 109\u2013134. {{ISBN|9781843844334}}\n*Hanna, Ralph, 'The Matter of Fulk: Romance and History in the Marches', ''The Journal of English and Germanic Philology'' 110 no 3 (University of Illinois Press, July 2011), pp. 337-58.\n*Rock, Catherine A., 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn and King John: Rebellion and Reconciliation,' in A.L. Kaufman (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=ogTytW5dZKcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: Essays on Medieval and Early Modern Figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty''] (McFarland & Co., Jefferson, NC 2011). {{ISBN|0-7864-5877-1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulk Fitzwarin}}\n[[Category:1160s births]]\n[[Category:1258 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:13th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:English heroic legends]]\n[[Category:English outlaws|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:English rebels]]\n[[Category:Medieval legends]]\n[[Category:People from Shropshire|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood]]\n[[Category:Marcher lords]]\n[[Category:Norman warriors]]\n[[Category:Medieval English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from Alveston]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n[[File:Arms of Fitzwarin.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of FitzWarin: ''Quarterly per fess indented argent and gules'' <ref>Arms of Fulk V FitzWarin, St George's [[Roll of Arms]], 1285, briantimms.com, St George's Roll, part 1, no. E69</ref>]]\n'''Fulk III FitzWarin''' (c. 1160\u20131258), variant spellings, [[List of Latinised names|Latinized]] as ''Fulco filius Warini'', was a powerful [[marcher lord]] seated at [[Whittington Castle]] in [[Shropshire]] on the English border with [[Wales]], and at [[Alveston]] in [[Gloucestershire]]. He rebelled against [[John, King of England|King John]] (1199\u20131216) from 1200 to 1203,<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\">Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British outlaws of literature and history: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), p. 97</ref> mainly over a dispute concerning his familial right to Whittington Castle, and was declared an [[outlaw]]. Between 1221 and 1226 he founded [[Alberbury Priory]] in Shropshire, which was the smallest and last of the three English houses dependent upon the [[Order of Grandmont]].\n\nAfter his death Fulk became the subject of a popular \"ancestral romance\" in French verse, ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', relating his life as an outlaw and his struggle to regain his patrimony from the king.<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club, [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up (London 1855)] (Internet Archive).</ref> This survives in a prose version, and combines historical material with [[legend]]ary and fantastical elements which are heroic rather than strictly biographical. His grandson was [[Fulk V FitzWarin, 1st Baron FitzWarin]] (1251\u20131315).<ref>[[George Cokayne|George Edward Cokayne]] ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', ed. Vicary Gibbs; vol. V, p. 495, Baron FitzWarin</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe patriarch of the Fitz-Warins was considered to be \"Warin of Metz\", from [[Lorraine (duchy)|Lorraine]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\">G.E. Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage'', V, p. 495, note (c)</ref><ref>Suppe, F., 'Fitzwarine family (per. c. 1145-1315)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (2004), Vol. \"F\", pp.&nbsp;953\u20134.</ref> His son was [[Fulk I FitzWarin]] (d.1170/1) of Whittington and Alveston (\"Fitz-\" being the Norman French equivalent of modern French \"Fils\", i.e. \"son of\"). Fulk's son and heir Fulk II FitzWarin (died 1197) was a [[marcher lord]] of Shropshire,<ref>Sidney Painter, ''The Reign of King John'' (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins Press 1964), p. 49</ref> and married Hawise le Dinan, a daughter and\nco-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]].<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\">G.E. Cokayne, ''The Complete Peerage'', V, p. 495, note (c)</ref> Their son was Fulk FitzWarin III.\n\nWarin (Guarine) of Metz the patriarch is however a \"shadowy or [[myth]]ical figure\",<ref name=\"GEC Complete Peerage p.495\"/> about whom little is certain. The later mediaeval romance ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'' gives his name as \"Warin de Meer\". Whatever his true place of origin it is however generally believed that the head of the Warin family came to England during the reign of [[William the Conqueror]] (1066\u20131087). Neither the father nor his sons were, during that reign, [[tenant-in-chief|tenants-in-chief]] (i.e. important [[vassal]]s or [[English feudal barony|feudal barons]]): rather, their grants of lands were obtained from later kings.<ref>Janet Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf, and Fitz Warin Families 1066\u20131272'', (Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1980), p. 34</ref>\n\nFulk I (died 1170/1) was rewarded by King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189) for his support of the king's mother [[Empress Matilda]] in [[The Anarchy|her civil war]] with [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] (1135\u20131154): in 1153 Henry conferred upon him the royal [[manor]] of [[Alveston]] in Gloucestershire and in 1149 the manor of Whadborough (in [[Loddington, Leicestershire|Loddington]]<ref>J. Nichols, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester'', Vol. 3 part 1: East Goscote Hundred (John Nichols, London 1800), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000032377095&view=1up&seq=476 pp. 332-34] (Hathi Trust).</ref>), Leicestershire. Fulk II [[Feudal land tenure in England|held]] those properties after the death of his father in 1171.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 34, 35</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===The lordship of Whittington===\nAt some time before 1178 Fulk II (d. 1197) married Hawise de Dinan, a wealthy heiress, a daughter and co-heiress of [[Josce de Dinan]].<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-qfHDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT49#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 49] (Google).</ref> Josce held [[Ludlow Castle]] in the Welsh Marches for the [[Empress Matilda]], daughter of King [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] (1100\u20131135), during the civil war (the \"[[The Anarchy|Anarchy]]\") between herself and [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]] (1135\u20131154) arising from their struggle for the throne.<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=zvzWAAAAMAAJ&pg=PAxi p. xi] (Google, no preview).</ref>\n \nThroughout his lifetime, Fulk II encountered many problems in receiving his patrimony and his other claims to land. These disputes concerned estates his father held [[Tenant-in-chief|in chief]] from the crown, but also others which he had held from [[Honour of Peverel|the Peverel family]] as [[Lord|overlords]]. They included particularly [[Whittington Castle]], held by the Peverels during the reign of King Stephen. Whittington Castle stands on the English side of [[Offa's Dyke]], which before and during the Norman era formed the border between England and [[Wales]]. The site was fortified with a castle by [[William Peverel the Younger]] in 1138 in support of the Empress Matilda.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 35</ref>\n\nIn the late 1140s the [[Marcher lord|lordship]] of [[Whittington, Shropshire|Whittington]], as with [[Oswestry]] and Overton, ceased to be part of England and became a Welsh [[marcher lord]]ship within the [[Kingdom of Powys]].<ref>P. Brown, P. King, and P. Remfry, 'Whittington Castle: The marcher fortress of the Fitz Warin family', ''Shropshire Archaeology and History'' LXXIX (2004), pp. 106\u2013127.</ref> In 1165 [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] granted the castle of Whittington to [[Roger de Powis]], a Welsh leader, and in about 1173 gave him funds for its repair.<ref>D. Stephenson, ''Medieval Powys: Kingdom, Principality and Lordships, 1132-1293'' (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge 2016), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6ERJDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA286#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 286] (Google); citing F. Suppe, 'Roger of Powys, Henry II's Anglo-Welsh Middleman, and His Lineage', ''The Welsh History Review'', Vol. 21 part 1 (2002), pp. 1-23.</ref> Roger de Powis was succeeded by his son Meurig (Maurice), and he in turn by his son Werennoc. \n\nAlthough Fulk II won the right to Whittington in or about 1195, he never received formal legal ''[[seisin]]'', and it remained in Welsh hands at the time of his death in 1197.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 35</ref> After the death of his father, Fulk III maintained his father's claim to Whittington,<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\">Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', p. 52</ref> and in 1197 he offered [[feudal relief|relief]] of \u00a3100 for it as his inheritance. However, on 11 April 1200 [[John, King of England|King John]] granted it to Maurice (son of Roger of Powis), who had offered half that sum. Again, after Maurice's death in August 1200, King John granted it to Maurice's heirs.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 36</ref><ref>If Fulk was really that \"Warin of London\" at whose bidding one William Brunus was killed in 1199 in an affray at Dublin Castle, and who was ordered to undergo trial by fire, some cause for his disfavour might be inferred. See Plea in F. Palgrave (ed.), ''Rotuli Curi\u00e6 Regis'', II: The First Year of King John (Commissioners, 1835), [https://archive.org/details/rotulicuriregis01commgoog/page/n206/mode/2up pp. 172-73] (Internet Archive): transcript, translation and attribution in J.S. Furlong, ''A Treatise on the Law of Landlord and Tenant'', 2 vols (Hodges and Smith, Dublin  1845), II: Appendix Pt. VI, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bYIDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA1251#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1251-53] (Google).</ref>\n\n===Rebellions===\nIt is not known why King John refused to recognise Fulk's claim to Whittington as his rightful inheritance, but by April 1201 Fulk was in open rebellion against the King. He was accompanied by approximately fifty-two followers including his brothers William, Phillip and John, by his cousins, and by the family's many tenants and allies in the Marches.<ref name=\"FFWOCH97\"/><ref name=\"Sidney Painter 1964 p. 52\"/>\n\nFulk's rebellion is not related in detail by chroniclers, but it was clearly considerable, for in the spring of 1201, when King John crossed into [[Normandy]] and [[Poitou]] to suppress a revolt by the [[Lusignan dynasty|Lusignans]],<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', p. 157</ref> he ordered [[Hubert de Burgh, 1st Earl of Kent|Hubert de Burgh]] with 100 knights to counter the rebellion of Fulk and of William Marsh, a [[Somerset]]shire knight who was raiding shipping off the coast of [[Devon]].<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', pp. 48, 84</ref> In July 1202 Fulk and his men were reported to have taken refuge in [[Stanley Abbey]] in Wiltshire. Another man, Gilbert de Duure, is mentioned in records as \"...having been an outlaw associated with Fulk Fitz Warin\". One other, Eustace de Kivilly, had been pardoned earlier in 1202 by King John for \"being associated with Fulk\".<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 38</ref>\n\n===Settlement and status===\nAfter years as an outlaw, on 11 November 1203 Fulk was pardoned, together with over thirty of his followers including his brothers William, Phillip and John, and their cousins. In October 1204, on payment of a fine of 200 marks, Fulk at last received \"right and inheritance\" in Whittington.<ref>A. Kemp-Welch (translator), L. Brandin (ed.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz-Warine'' (Alexander Moring Ltd., De La More Press, London 1904), p. xii.</ref> The castle thereafter descended in the [[Baron FitzWarin|FitzWarin family]], all subsequent holders bearing the first-name Fulk, until the death of [[Fulk XI FitzWarin, 7th Baron FitzWarin]] (1405\u20131420) in 1420.<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', pp. 51\u201352</ref>\n\nThe high regard in which Fulk III was held by many of the king's barons in 1207 is shown by the names of the men who stood surety for the fine of 1,200 marks demanded of him to marry [[Maud le Vavasour|Maud (Matilda)]], the heiress daughter of Robert le Vavasour and relict of [[Theobald Walter, 1st Chief Butler of Ireland|Theobald Walter]].<ref>T.D. Hardy, ''Rotuli de Oblatis et Finibus in Turri Londinensi Asservati, tempore Regis Johannis'' (Commissioners, 1835), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RqEUAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA405#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 405-06] (Google).</ref> The suretors included the Peverels, [[Alan Basset]], [[William de Braose (died 1230)]], a de Lacy, [[William Longesp\u00e9e, 3rd Earl of Salisbury]] and [[Henry de Bohun, 1st Earl of Hereford]].<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 39</ref> On 9 February 1214, when King John again set sail for [[Poitou]], Fulk was among the barons who accompanied him. He is believed then to have been  a vassal of [[Geoffrey FitzGeoffrey de Mandeville, 2nd Earl of Essex|Geoffrey de Mandeville]], Earl of Gloucester.<ref>Painter, ''The Reign of King John'', pp. 280, 294.</ref>\n\n===Further confrontations===\nIn 1215 Fulk was one of many giving great trouble to the [[Sheriff of Shropshire]]. Before the accession of the infant king [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] (John's son) in 1216, Fulk's manor of Alveston had already been seized by the crown: in the following year (1217) all of his other lands in Gloucestershire were likewise seized. By 1218, however, Fulk had made peace and his lands were ordered to be restored to him by the king's regents:<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 41, 43</ref> his market at his manor of [[Narborough, Leicestershire]], was withdrawn from him as \"a manifest enemy\" of the king's in 1217,<ref>T.D. Hardy, ''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum in Turri Londinensi Asservati'', 2 vols (Commissioners, 1833), I: 1204-1224, [https://digitale-bibliothek-mv.de/viewer/image/PPN848631250/379/ p. 321] (Mecklenberg Verpommern Digital).</ref> but regranted in 1218. In the latter year the king also granted a fair for his manor of [[Lambourn]] in Berkshire,<ref>Fine Rolls, 3 Henry III, ref C 60/11, [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_011.html nos. 436 and 437], image at [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_011.html m. 1] (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> which Fulk's mother Hawise and her sister Sybil (de Plugenet) had inherited in two parts from Joce de Dinant. Hawise died at about this time.<ref>'Parishes: Lambourn', in W. Page and P.H. Ditchfield (eds), ''A History of the County of Berkshire'', Vol. 4, ed. (London, 1924), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/berks/vol4/pp251-266 pp. 251-66] (British History Online).</ref> \n\nBy 1220 Fulk had regained some favour with the young King Henry III and had been allowed to rebuild and fortify Whittington,<ref>T.D. Hardy (ed.), ''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum in Turri Londinensi Asservati'' (Commissioners, 1833), I: 1204-1224, [https://digitale-bibliothek-mv.de/viewer/fullscreen/PPN848631250/518/ p. 460] (Mecklenberg Verpommern).</ref> and to hold a weekly market and annual two-day fair there.<ref>Fine Rolls, 4 Henry III, ref C 60/12, [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_012.html item 16], image at [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/fimages/C60_12/m09.html m. 9] (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> In 1223 however Whittington Castle fell to [[Llywelyn the Great]], Prince of Wales. Fulk regained it the following year, although his disputes with Llywelyn continued and more of Fulk's lands were seized. By 1228 a truce seems to have been reached between Fulk and Llywelyn following the intervention of the king.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 41-42</ref><ref>I.J. Sanders, 'Fitz Warin lords of Whittington and Alderbury (Salop) and Alveston (Gloucs.)', ''Y Bywgraffiadur Cymreig '' (1959), [https://biography.wales/article/s-FITZ-WAR-1130 (Welsh Dictionary of National Biography online)].</ref>\n\nThroughout these years Fulk's relations with the King were changeable and seemed to be directly dependent on the state of affairs in Wales. As a marcher lord Fulk's role as a protector of the English border against the Welsh was vital to the English King. He arbitrated several border disputes on behalf of the King and although there were more personal disagreements, there were no more rebellions on the part of Fulk III.<ref>Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', pp. 42, 43, 45</ref>\n\n==Pious uses==\n===Alberbury Priory===\nBetween 1221 and 1226 Fulk began to build his priory at [[Alberbury Priory|Alberbury]] on a moated site at a bend in the [[river Severn]] on the border of England and Wales.<ref>M.J. Angold, G.C. Baugh, M.M. Chibnall, D.C. Cox, D.T.W. Price, M. Tomlinson and B.S. Trinder, 'House of Grandmontine monks: Priory of Alberbury', in A.T. Gaydon and R.B. Pugh, ''A History of the County of Shropshire'', Vol. 2 (V.C.H., London 1973), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/salop/vol2/pp47-50 pp. 47-50] (British History Online): citing the Alberbury documents in the muniments of All Souls' College, Oxford.</ref> He first intended it as a house of [[Augustinian canons]] following the [[Arrouaise Abbey|Arrouasian rule]], and invited Alan, the Abbot of [[Lilleshall Abbey|Lilleshall]], to establish the convent. However his endowments were found insufficient, and Alan's successor Abbot William renounced any interest in the project.<ref>R. Graham and A.W. Clapham, 'Alberbury Priory', ''Transactions of the Shropshire Archaeological and Natural History Society'', Series 4 vol. XI (1927-1928), pp. 257-303.</ref> Fulk therefore turned instead to the [[Grandmontines|Grandmontine Order]], following the example of [[Walter de Lacy, Lord of Meath|Walter de Lacy]]'s house founded at [[Craswall Priory]] in [[Herefordshire]] c. 1220-1225, but placing Alberbury under the immediate authority of Grandmont Abbey in [[Limousin]].<ref>'The Order of Grandmont and its houses in England', in R. Graham, ''English Ecclesiastical Studies, being Some Essays in Research in Mediaeval History'' (S.P.C.K., London 1929), pp. 209-46.</ref> In addition to the priory site with its lands and rights in Alberbury with Pecknall, a fishery in the Severn, and the right to construct mills, Fulk's endowments included his manor of Whadborough at Loddington in eastern Leicestershire. These were confirmed by King Henry III's charter of 1232.<ref>'Priory of Alberbury, or Abberbury, in Shropshire', in W. Dugdale, ''Monasticon Anglicanum'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nllVAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA1031#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 1031-1032, Num. I] (Google); ''Calendar of Charter Rolls, Henry III'', 1226-1257 (HMSO 1903), [https://archive.org/details/calendarofcharte01grea/page/172/mode/2up p. 172] (Internet Archive).</ref>\n\n===Estates and suits===\nIn 1226 Maud the wife of Fulk FitzWarin died, which was no doubt a stimulus to the completion of the priory, where she was buried.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\">Emma Cavell, 'The Burial of Noblewomen in Thirteenth-Century Shropshire,' in B. Weiler, J. Burton, P. Schofield and K. St\u00f6ber (eds), ''Thirteenth Century England'' XI (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge 2007), p. 174 & note 2.</ref> In that year Theobald Walter the younger (son of Maud's first marriage) unsuccessfully challenged William Pantolf and Hawise his wife for title to the manor of Narborough in Leicestershire,<ref>T.D. Hardy (ed.), ''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum in Turri Londinensi Asservati'', II: 1224-1227 (Commissioners, 1844), [https://digitale-bibliothek-mv.de/viewer/image/PPN848631404/153/ p. 147 b] (Mecklenberg Verpommern Digital).</ref> a Vavasour hereditament.<ref>W. Farrer and C.T. Clay, ''Early Yorkshire Charters'', XI: The Percy Fee (Cambridge University Press, 1963 edition), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EkB2UdPlD4sC&pg=PA130#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 130] (Google).</ref> Fulke's market at Narborough had received the Kings re-confirmation in 1220, but it is shown in a suit of 1276 that the manor had been given by Maud to her daughter Hawise,<ref>\"Robertus [Vavasor] dedit premissa Matilde filie sue; que dedit premissa Hawisie filie sue\": Plea quoted in 'Narborough', in J. Nichols, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester'', Reprint, 4 volumes in 8 (John Nichols, London 1811/Leicester County Council with S.R. Publishing Ltd., 1971), Vol. 4 Part 2: Sparkenhoe Hundred, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000001252729&view=1up&seq=584 at p. 814] (Hathi Trust).</ref> who by her marriage to Pantolf became Lady of the barony of [[Wem]],<ref>I.J. Sanders, ''English Baronies: A Study of Their Origin and Descent 1086\u20131327'' (Clarendon Press, Oxford 1960), pp. 94-95.</ref>, as the ''FitzWarin Romance'' reminds us.<ref>R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1858), VII, pp. 66-83, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6UtNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA75#v=onepage&q&f=false at pp. 75-76] (Google).</ref> Theobald simultaneously challenged Fulk for the manor of [[Edlington]] in Yorkshire, another part of the same inheritance.<ref>''Rotuli Litterarum Clausarum'', II, p. 147 b (as above).</ref> After Pantolf died in 1233, and Fulk paid 600 marks for custody of his heirs and lands,<ref>Fine Rolls, 17 Henry III, ref. C 60/32, [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_032.html item 108], image at [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/fimages/C60_32/m08.html m. 8] (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> Hawise remarried to Hubert Husse, taking Narborough as her ''maritagium'' with her, and in 1235 Hubert obtained a renewal of the market, which had by then lapsed.<ref>''Close Rolls of the Reign of Henry III'', 1234-1237 (HMSO 1908), [https://archive.org/details/closerollsreign00britgoog/page/n240/mode/2up p. 210] (Internet Archive).</ref><ref>\"Rex concessit Huberto Hues' quod mercatum quod consuevit aliquando teneri apud manerium de Northbrug' (manerio illo existente in manu Fulconis filii Warini) et quod postea decidit, iterum relevetur et teneatur...\" There is no indication here that Fulke had died.</ref>\n\nIn 1227 the fair at Lambourn was re-granted, <ref>''Calendar of Charter Rolls, Henry III'', 1226-1257 (HMSO 1903), [https://archive.org/details/calendarofcharte01grea/page/58/mode/2up p. 58] (Internet Archive).</ref> Before 1224 [[William Marshal, Earl of Pembroke]] had by his charter<ref>Recited in ''Placita de Quo Warranto Temporibus Edw. I, II & III'' (Commissioners, 1818), [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=coo.31924082447990&view=1up&seq=113 pp. 81-82] (Hathi Trust).</ref> enfeoffed Fulk III in the nearby manor of [[Wantage]], Berkshire and in the Hundred of Wantage and ''Gamenefeud'': for although the King's attorney later challenged the FitzWarin right to the Hundreds, they remained in their hands.<ref>'Wantage Hundred: Introduction', in W. Page and P.H. Ditchfield (eds), ''A History of the County of Berkshire'', Vol. 4  (London, 1924), [https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/berks/vol4/pp267-268 pp. 267-68] (British History Online).</ref> The King claimed Wantage manor against him as ''terra Flandrensium'' - the land of Robert de B\u00e9thune - in 1236-37,<ref>F.W. Maitland (ed.), ''Bracton's Note Book: A Collection of Cases Decided in the King's Courts during the Reign of Henry the Third'', 3 Vols (C.J. Clay & Sons, London 1887), III, [https://archive.org/details/bractonsnoteboo03maitgoog/page/n245/mode/2up No. 1220, pp. 232-34] (Internet Archive).</ref> but his possession of it was warranted by [[Gilbert Marshal, 4th Earl of Pembroke|Gilbert Marshal]],<ref>''Placitorum in Domo Capitulari Westmonasteriensi Asservati Abbreviatio'' (Commissioners, 1811), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=epk0AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA105#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 105] (Google).</ref> and he defended his possession again in 1241 against Robert de B\u00e9thune himself.<ref>'Parishes: Wantage', ''A History of the County of Berkshire'', Vol. 4, [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/berks/vol4/pp319-332 pp. 319-32] (British History Online).</ref> In due course Fulk by charter granted his entire manor of Lambourn to his daughter Mabil and to the heirs of her body, and made acknowledgement of the fact before the Court of King's Bench in 1249.<ref>J. Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier: The Corbet, Pantulf and Fitz Warin Families, 1066-1272'' (University of Nebraska Press, Lincoln 1980), p. 96.</ref> \n\n===The second marriage===\nMabil was the daughter of Fulk's second wife, Clarice de Auberville, who (as the [[Fine rolls]] record) was certainly living in 1250.<ref>Fine Rolls, C 60/47, [http://www.finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/calendar/roll_047.html 34 Henry III, membrane 2, no. 786], i.e. the penultimate entry in the membrane imaged as [https://finerollshenry3.org.uk/content/fimages/C60_47/m16.html \"m. 16\"]. (Henry III Fine Rolls Project).</ref> The marriage features in the Romance narrative, which calls her \"une molt gentile dame\", and is said to have occurred \"a good while\" after the death of Maud. The legend tells that after their marriage Fulk was struck blind for the last seven years of his life, and that he outlived Clarice by one year.<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club (London 1855): [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up see pp. 177-83] (Internet Archive).</ref> It has been accepted that Clarice was the daughter (rather than the widow) of Sir [[Robert de Auberville]], of [[Iden, Sussex|Iden]] and Iham (Higham, in [[Icklesham]]<ref>i.e. the settlement around the now demolished church of St Leonard, immediately north-west of New Winchelsea. 'Higham, (\"Iham\" or \"Ihomme\"), an old name of Winchelsea' - E. Ekwall, ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-Names'', 4th edition (Clarendon Press, Oxford 1960), p. 238.</ref>), near [[Winchelsea]], Sussex.<ref>W. Dugdale, ''The Baronage of England After the Norman Conquest'' (Thomas Newcomb, for Abel Roper, John Martin and Herny Herringman, London 1675-76), I, [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A36794.0001.001/1:6.129?rgn=div2;view=fulltext pp. 443-47] (Umich/eebo); R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1858), VII, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6UtNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 66-83, esp. p. 76 notes 52 and 53] (Google).</ref> Sir Robert, of an influential Norman family, was a grandson of [[Ranulf de Glanvill]], and on the death of his father William, c. 1195, became a ward of [[Hubert Walter]]'s.<ref>S.J. Bailey, 'Ranulf de Glanvill and His Children', ''The Cambridge Law Journal'' Vol. 15, No. 2 (Nov., 1957), pp. 163-182, at p. 186 note 51.</ref> He was a Constable of [[Hastings Castle]], and Keeper of the Coast in 1228-1229. Robert's wife Clarice was daughter of Robert and granddaughter of Samson de Gestling, patrons of [[Robertsbridge Abbey]].<ref>'Quitclaim', The National Archives Discovery Catalogue, item description: [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/0b6b4574-0f22-4cdf-8c89-1c12dde9a4de CCA-DCc-ChAnt/A/117] (Canterbury Cathedral Archives). See also C.T. Flower (ed.), ''Curia Regis Rolls: 7-9 Henry III'' (HMSO 1955), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=nXVpAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sansonem p. 325] (Google snippet).</ref> Robert de Auberville is supposed to have died c. 1230.<ref>G. Paget, ''An Official, Genealogical and Heraldic Baronage of England'' (1957), 11: 1-2.</ref> \n\nIn 1230 Fulk commenced a suit against Philip de Burwardsley (i.e. of Broseley, Shropshire), apparently a FitzWarin cousin, concerning lands in Shropshire and Staffordshire which had been disputed between their grandfathers, and which did not come to a full Assize until after 1233.<ref>R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1855), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-oFJAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 10-11] (Google).</ref><ref>'Banco Rolls no. 6. Tower Records (April 1231)', in G. Wrottesley (ed.), 'Plea Rolls for Staffordshire: 1231-39', ''Staffordshire Historical Collections'', IV (London 1883), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/staffs-hist-collection/vol4/pp81-89 p. 81] (British History Online).</ref>\n\n===Service===\nFulk attended the King's court in Westminster in October 1229:<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'Carta concessa David filio Lewelini, nepoti Regis', in T. Rymer and R. Sanderson, ed. A. Clarke and F. Holbrooke, ''Foedera, Conventiones, Litterae, et cujuscunque generis Acta Publica'', New Edition, 4 Vols in 8 (London 1816), I Part 1: 1066-1272, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=340 p. 196] (Hathi Trust).</ref> he received a writ of protection during absence upon foreign service (given at Portsmouth) in April 1230, and was required to supply one knight for foreign service in aid of the Earl of Bretaigne in May 1234.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'De auxilio comiti Brittanniae ferendo', in Rymer, ''Foedera'', I Part 1, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=356 p. 212] (Hathi Trust).</ref> In July 1236 he was appointed one of the Arbitrators (for North Wales) of the truce between King Henry and Llywelyn, as William FitzWarin was among those for South Wales.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'De treugis ex parte Lewelini', in Rymer, ''Foedera'', I Part 1, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=374 p. 230] (Hathi Trust).</ref> In March 1238 he was among the powerful men summoned by the King to Oxford, to deliberate upon Llywelyn's action in causing his son [[Dafydd ap Llywelyn|Dafydd]] to receive homage from the magnates of Gwynedd and Powys.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing 'De treugis Walliae', in Rymer, ''Foedera'', I Part 1, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951002098035k&view=1up&seq=379 p. 235] (Hathi Trust).</ref> The Romance narrative tells that, after the death of [[Joan, Lady of Wales|Joan, Lady of Snowdon]] in 1237 (who was buried at [[Beaumaris]]), [[Llywelyn ap Iorwerth]] took Eva, daughter of Fulk, as his last wife: and after Llywelyn's death in 1240, she remarried to William de Blancmouster (de Whitchurch).<ref>T.W. King, 'On the coats of arms appropriated to the Welsh princes', ''Archaeologia, or Miscellaneous Tracts Relating to Antiquity'' XXIX (London 1842), Appendix, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H1NIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA407#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 407-13] (Google).</ref>\n\nIn June 1245, faced by the rapacity of the [[Papal nuncio]] Martin (resulting in a prohibition of [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]]), an assembly of nobles at [[Dunstable]] and Linton deputed Fulk to proceed to London to order Martin out of the kingdom. As [[Matthew Paris]] relates their interview, Fulk told him to leave England immediately, but Martin questioned his authority to demand it. Fulk told him to be off within three days if he did not wish to be utterly brought down, and withdrew in anger, heaping threats upon threats with a terrible oath against him. Martin hurried off to the king, who told him that he had brought the kingdom to the brink of revolt: being asked for safe conduct the King answered, \"May the Devil take you to hell.\"<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, 66-83, citing H.R. Luard (ed.), ''Matthaei Parisiensis, Monachus Sancti Albani, Chronica Majora'', Volume IV: 1240-1247, Rerum Britannicarum Medii Aevi Scriptores - Rolls Series (Longman & Co., Tr\u00fcbner & Co., London 1877) [https://archive.org/details/matthiparisiens03luargoog/page/n446/mode/2up pp. 420-21] (Internet Archive).</ref> A week later Fulk witnessed a charter of the King's at Windsor.\n\n===Last controversies===\nAlthough Fulk seems certainly to have lived after 1250, in this late period it is increasingly difficult to distinguish him from his two sons named Fulk, among the various references to Fulk \"senior\" and \"junior\". At a Shropshire Assize of January 1256 it was probably the younger son Fulk (called Fulk Glas) who, claiming that [[Corbet family#History|Thomas Corbet]] had disseised him of his free tenement of Alberbury, became enraged when Corbet referred to his father as \"Proditor\" (Traitor), renounced any homage that he had made to Corbet, and vowed never to hold land of him again.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, pp. 80-81, citing Shropshire Assize Rolls, The National Archives (UK), ref. JUST 1/734, rot. 15 front. View original at [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT4/JUST1/JUST1no734/aJUST1no734fronts/IMG_0920.htm AALT image 0920] (last full entry): \"ita quod idem Thomas vocavit Fulconem patrem ipsius Fulconis proditorem...\", etc.</ref> The Hundred Feodary of 1255 showed that Fulk FitzWarin held two [[hide (unit)|hides]] [[Land Tax|geldable]] in Alberbury of the fee of Caus (of which Thomas Corbet of [[Caus Castle]] was lord), and that the Grandmontensian brothers there held two [[virgate]]s by the gift of Fulk FitzWarin ''senior'' (i.e. Fulk III in 1232), and of the fee of Caus.<ref>'Hundredum de Forde, Com. Salop.', in ''Rotuli Hundredorum Temp. Hen. III & Edw. I'' (Commissioners, 1818), II, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wBtDAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA66#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 66-67] (Google).</ref> The services owing by Fulk FitzWarin for a knight's fee held from Corbet at Alberbury had been set forth in a concord of 1248,<ref>Feet of Fines, ref. CP 25(1)/193/4, no. 31: view original at [http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT7/CP25(1)/CP25_1_193_4/IMG_0324.htm AALT].</ref> the Fine for which was recorded in the Pipe Roll for 1250 and remained unpaid in 1252.\n\nIn 1245 the king had appointed Fulk FitzWarin, John le Strange and Henry de Audley to settle a land-dispute between Gruffydd ap Madog, whose land had been seized by [[Dafydd ap Llywelyn]] during the king's last war, and which had been seized back from Dafydd and was now claimed by [[Gruffydd ap Gwenwynwyn]]<ref>''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Henry III'', 1232-1247 (HMSO 1906), [https://archive.org/details/patentrollsreig01lytegoog/page/n490/mode/2up p. 466] (Internet Archive).</ref> (whose mother was Margaret Corbet, and whose wife Hawise was daughter of John le Strange of [[Knockin Castle]]). On the occasion of Thomas Corbet's outrageous accusation, in 1255, the court had been been hearing and attempting to settle contentions between Thomas Corbet and Gruffydd ap Gwenwynwyn.<ref>Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'', VII, pp. 80-81, citing Shropshire Assize, as above; ''Calendar of Patent Rolls, Henry III'', 1247-1258 (HMSO 1908), [https://archive.org/details/patentrollsreig00offigoog/page/n449/mode/2up p. 438] (Internet Archive).</ref> In time, Gruffydd's daughter Margaret became the wife of [[Fulk FitzWarin, 1st Baron FitzWarin|Fulk V FitzWarin]], son of Fulk IV.\n\n==Marriages and progeny==\nFulk III FitzWarin married, in about 1207, to [[Maud le Vavasour, Baroness Butler|Maud le Vavasour]] (d.1226), (''alias'' Matilda), daughter of Robert le Vavasour and widow of the powerful Lancashire baron Theobald Walter.<ref>G.E. Cokayne, ed. Vicary Gibbs, ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', Vol. II (The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., London 1912), p. 448</ref> He secured pledges for the marriage from his brother William and from Maud's father, Robert le Vavasour, who was a tenant of the [[English feudal barony|feudal barony]] of [[Skipton]] in Yorkshire.<ref>Max Lieberman, ''The Medieval Marches of Wales: The Creation and Perception of a Frontier, 1066'' (Cambridge University Press 2010), pp. 87-97</ref><ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/> Maud died in 1226 and was buried at Alberbury Priory (''alias'' New Abbey, Alberbury) in Shropshire.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/><ref>Sir Bernard Burke, C.B., LL.D., Ulster King of Arms, ''Genealogical History of the Dormant, Abeyant, Forfeited, and Extinct Peerages of the British Empire'', (Burke's Peerage/Genealogical Publishing Co., 1883), Reprinted 1985; 1996; p. 213</ref><ref>G.E. Cokayne, ed. Vicary Gibbs, ''The Complete Peerage of England Scotland Ireland Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant Extinct or Dormant'', Volume II: Bass to Canning (The St. Catherine Press, Ltd., London 1912), p. 448</ref> They had the following progeny:\n* Fulk IV FitzWarin (d.1264).<ref name=\"BWF37\">Meisel, ''Barons of the Welsh Frontier'', p. 37</ref> He received the manor of Edlington, Yorkshire, as part of his inheritance.<ref>W. Farrer and C.T. Clay (eds), ''Early Yorkshire Charters'', XI: The Percy Fee (Cambridge University Press, 1963), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EkB2UdPlD4sC&pg=PA121#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 119-22] (Google).</ref> He married Constance de Tosny.\n* Fulk Glas<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n* Hawise FitzWarin, married (first) William Pantulf, a [[Marcher Lord]] (who died in 1233), and (secondly) Hubert Huse.<ref name=\"BWF37\"/> She received the manor of Narborough.\n* Joan FitzWarin<ref name=\"BWF37\"/>\n* Eva FitzWarin,<ref name=\"BWF37\"/> married (first) c. 1238 to [[Llywelyn ap Iorwerth]] (who died in 1240), and (secondly) William de Blanchminister.\n\nThe Romance narrative attributes to Fulk III FitzWarin a second marriage, to Clarice de Auberville. Clarice is taken to have been the daughter and heiress of [[Robert de Auberville]] of [[Iden, Sussex|Iden]] and Iham (Higham, in [[Icklesham]]<ref>i.e. the settlement around the now demolished church of St Leonard, immediately north-west of New Winchelsea. 'Higham, (\"Iham\" or \"Ihomme\"), an old name of Winchelsea' - E. Ekwall, ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-Names'', 4th edition (Clarendon Press, Oxford 1960), p. 238.</ref>), Sussex, and his wife Claricia de Gestling.<ref>As shown in a deed of quitclaim, see The National Archives Discovery Catalogue, item description: [http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/0b6b4574-0f22-4cdf-8c89-1c12dde9a4de CCA-DCc-ChAnt/A/117] (Canterbury Cathedral Archives). See also C.T. Flower (ed.), ''Curia Regis Rolls: 7-9 Henry III'' (HMSO 1955), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?redir_esc=y&id=nXVpAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Sansonem p. 325] (Google snippet).</ref> The daughter of this marriage was:\n* Mabel FitzWarin (\u22121297), who married (first) William de Crevequer (no issue), and (secondly) John de Tregoz, Lord Tregoz (died before 6 Sept 1300), by whom she had two daughters and coheirs, Clarice and Sybil.<ref name=\"Emma Cavell 2007, p. 174\"/><ref name=\"BWF37\"/> She received the manor of Lambourn.\n\nThe identification of Clarice as second wife of Fulk III was accepted as factual, in his ''Baronage'', by Sir [[William Dugdale]]<ref>W. Dugdale, ''The Baronage of England After the Norman Conquest'' (Thomas Newcomb, for Abel Roper, John Martin and Herny Herringman, London 1675-76), I, [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A36794.0001.001/1:6.129?rgn=div2;view=fulltext pp. 443-47] (Umich/eebo).</ref> and, despite occasional doubts, later accounts of the family have accepted this precedent.<ref>R.W. Eyton, ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (John Russell Smith, London 1858), VII, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6UtNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA76#v=onepage&q&f=false pp. 66-83, esp. p. 76 notes 52 and 53] (Google).</ref>\n\n==Death & burial==\nFulk III lived to a great age. At some time before his death in 1258 he handed over control of a great portion of his responsibilities to his son and heir Fulk IV. In 1252 he made his will in which he stated his wish to be buried at the priory he had founded at Alberbury.<ref>''[http://www.discovershropshire.org.uk/html/search/verb/GetRecord/theme:20070423145036 Discover Shropshire'']''</ref>\n\n==Romance of ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''==\nAfter Foulk's death he became the subject of the famous \"ancestral romance\" known as '''''Fouke le Fitz Waryn''''',<ref>T. Wright (ed. and transl.), ''The History of Fulk Fitz Warine, an Outlawed Baron in the Reign of King John'', Warton Club, [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/176/mode/2up (London 1855)] (Internet Archive).</ref> which contains a highly embellished account of his life and family history.<ref>Kathryn Bedford, 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn: Outlaw or Chivalric Hero?', ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: essays on medieval and early modern figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty'', ed. Alexander L. Kaufman (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Co., 2011), pp. 99\u201399</ref>\n\nThe biography of Fulk III survives in a French prose \"ancestral [[romance (heroic literature)|romance]]\", extant in a  manuscript containing English, French and [[Latin]] texts, which is based on a lost French verse romance.<ref>The French verse form was seen by Leland: T. Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', 2nd, enlarged edition, 6 vols (W. and J. Richardson, London 1770), I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=376 pp. 236-37, representing fols. 268-69] (Hathi Trust).</ref> A 16th-century summary by [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]] of an otherwise lost [[Middle English]] verse version, ''The Nobile Actes of the Guarines'', has also been preserved.<ref>Hearne (ed.), ''Joannis Lelandi Antiquarii De Rebvs Britannicis Collectanea'', I, [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433075905665&view=1up&seq=370 pp. 230-36, representing fols. 261-68] (Hathi Trust).</ref> The work is part of the [[Matter of England]].<ref name=boundaries>Neil Cartlidge ''Boundaries in Medieval Romance'',  D. S. Brewer, 2008, {{ISBN|1-84384-155-X}}, 9781843841555. pp. 29\u201342</ref> The outline of the work is as follows. As a young boy, Fulk was sent to the court of King [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] (1154\u20131189), where he grew up with the king's younger son, the future King [[John of England|John]] (1199\u20131216). John became his enemy after a childhood quarrel during a game of chess. As an adult, King John retained his animosity toward Fulk whom he stripped of his ancestral holdings. Fulk thereupon took to the woods as an outlaw and lived a life of adventure. The story may in fact  have confused aspects of the lives of two FitzWarins, Fulk I (d. 1171) and Fulk II (d. 1197), father and son. The romance of Fulk FitzWarin is noted for its parallels to the legend of [[Robin Hood]].<ref>Introduction to ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'', edited by Stephen Knight and Thomas H. Ohlgren, originally published in ''Robin Hood and Other Outlaw Tales'', Kalamazoo, Michigan: Medieval Institute Publications, 1997.</ref>\n\n;Editions\n* F. Michel (ed.), ''Histoire de Foulques Fitz-Warin, d'apr\u00e8s un Manuscrit du Mus\u00e9e Britannique'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZOk9AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false (Silvestre Libraire, Paris 1840)]. (Google) (Edition without translation, but includes the Leland abstracts).\n* T. Wright (ed. and translator), ''The History of Fulk FitzWarin, an Outlawed Baron, in the Reign of King John'', edited from a manuscript preserved in the British Museum, with an English translation and illustrative notes (Printed for the Warton Club, London, 1855). [https://archive.org/details/historyoffulkfit00wriguoft/page/n5/mode/2up at pp.&nbsp;1\u2013183 text, pp.&nbsp;183\u2013231 notes].\n* J. Stephenson (ed. and translator), 'The Legend of Fulk FitzWarin' (parallel French text and English translation), in ''Rerum Britannicarum Medii Aevi Scriptores'', Rolls Series Vol. 66: ''Radulphi de Coggeshall Chronicon Anglicanum'' (etc.) (Longman & Co., Tr\u00fcbner & Co., London 1875), [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mdvUAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA277#v=onepage&q&f=false at pp. 277-415] (Google).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Dolmans, Emily, 'Locating the Border: Britain and the Welsh Marches in ''Fouke le Fitz Waryn'',' in L. Ashe, W. Scase and D. Lawton (eds), [https://boydellandbrewer.com/new-medieval-literatures-16-hb.html ''New Medieval Literatures 16''] (Boydell and Brewer, 2016), pp. 109\u2013134. {{ISBN|9781843844334}}\n*Hanna, Ralph, 'The Matter of Fulk: Romance and History in the Marches', ''The Journal of English and Germanic Philology'' 110 no 3 (University of Illinois Press, July 2011), pp. 337-58.\n*Rock, Catherine A., 'Fouke le Fitz Waryn and King John: Rebellion and Reconciliation,' in A.L. Kaufman (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=ogTytW5dZKcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false ''British Outlaws of Literature and History: Essays on Medieval and Early Modern Figures from Robin Hood to Twm Shon Catty''] (McFarland & Co., Jefferson, NC 2011). {{ISBN|0-7864-5877-1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulk Fitzwarin}}\n[[Category:1160s births]]\n[[Category:1258 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:13th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:English heroic legends]]\n[[Category:English outlaws|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:English rebels]]\n[[Category:Medieval legends]]\n[[Category:People from Shropshire|FitzWarin, Fulk]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood]]\n[[Category:Marcher lords]]\n[[Category:Norman warriors]]\n[[Category:Medieval English nobility]]\n[[Category:People from Alveston]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePious uses:twk", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fulk_FitzWarin"}
{"title_page": "Politics of India", "text_new": "{{short description|Political system of India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox political system\n| name                          = Politics of India\n| native_name                   =\n| image                         = Emblem of India.svg\n| image_size                    = 100\n| caption                       = [[State Emblem of India]]\n| type                          = [[Federation|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Constitutionalism|constitutional]] [[republic]]\n| constitution                  = [[Constitution of India]]\n| legislature                   = [[Parliament of India|Parliament]]\n| legislature_type              = [[Bicameralism|Bicameral]]\n| legislature_place             = [[Parliament House (India)|Parliament House]]\n| legislature_speaker           = \n| legislature_speaker_title     =\n| upperhouse                    = [[Rajya Sabha|Council of States]]\n| upperhouse_speaker            = [[Venkaiah Naidu]]\n| upperhouse_speaker_title      = [[Chairman of the Rajya Sabha|Chairman of the Council of States]]\n| upperhouse_appointer          = [[Electoral College (India)|Electoral College]]\n| lowerhouse                    = [[Lok Sabha|House of the People]]\n| lowerhouse_speaker            = [[Om Birla]]\n| lowerhouse_speaker_title      = [[Speaker of the Lok Sabha|Speaker of the House of the People]]\n| lowerhouse_appointer          = \n| title_hos                     = [[President of India|President]]\n| current_hos                   = [[Ram Nath Kovind]]\n| appointer_hos                 = Electoral College\n| title_hog                     = [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]]\n| current_hog                   = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| appointer_hog                 = President\n| title_hosag                   = \n| current_hosag                 =\n| appointer_hosag               =\n| cabinet                       = [[Union Council of Ministers]]\n| current_cabinet               = [[Second Modi ministry]]\n| cabinet_leader                = Prime Minister\n| cabinet_deputyleader          = \n| cabinet_appointer             = President\n| cabinet_hq                    =\n| cabinet_ministries            = [[Union Government ministries of India|52]]\n| judiciary                     = [[Judiciary of India|Judiciary]]\n| judiciary_head                = [[Sharad Arvind Bobde]]\n| courts                        =\n| court                         = [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]]\n| chief_judge                   = [[Sharad Arvind Bobde]]\n| court_seat                    = \n| court1                        =\n| chief_judge1                  =\n| court_seat1                   =\n}}\n{{Politics of India}}\nThe '''politics of India''' works within the framework of the country's [[Constitution of India|constitution]]. India is a [[Federation|federal]] [[Parliamentary republic|parliamentary]] [[democratic republic]] in which the  [[President of India]]  is the [[head of state]] and the [[Prime Minister of India]] is the [[head of government]]. India follows the dual polity system, i.e. a double government (federal in nature) that consists of the central authority at the centre and [[States and union territories of India|states]] at the periphery. The constitution defines the organisational powers and limitations of both central and state governments, and it is well recognised, rigid and considered supreme; i.e. the [[Law of India|laws]] of the nation must confirm to it.\n\nThere is a provision for a [[Bicameralism|bicameral]] [[legislature]] consisting of an [[upper house]], the [[Rajya Sabha]] (Council of States), which represents the states of the Indian federation, and a [[lower house]], the [[Lok Sabha]] (House of the People), which represents the people of India as a whole. The Indian constitution provides for an [[Judicial independence|independent]] [[judiciary]], which is headed by the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]]. The court's mandate is to protect the constitution, to settle disputes between the central government and the states, to settle inter-state disputes, to nullify any central or state laws that go against the constitution and to protect the fundamental rights of citizens, issuing [[writs]] for their enforcement in cases of violation.<ref>{{cite book|title=Public Administration|publisher=Tata Mcgraw Hill|isbn=978-0071074827|pages=389\u2013390|author=M.Lakshmikanth|edition=9th|year=2012}}</ref>\nThere are 543 members in the Lok Sabha, who are elected from the 543 Indian constituencies.\nThere are 245 members in the Rajya Sabha, out of which 233 are elected by indirect elections by single transferable vote by the members of the state legislative assemblies and other 12 members are elected/nominated by the President of India.\nGovernments are formed through [[Elections in India|elections]] held every five years (unless otherwise specified), by parties that secure a majority of members in their respective lower houses (Lok Sabha in the central government and [[Vidhan Sabha]] in states). India had [[1951 Indian general election|its first general election]] in 1951, which was won by the [[Indian National Congress]], a political party that went on to dominate subsequent elections until [[1977 Indian general election|1977]], when a non-Congress government was formed for the first time in independent India. The 1990s saw the end of [[Dominant-party system|single-party domination]] and the rise of coalition governments. The [[2014 Indian general election|elections]] for the [[16th Lok Sabha]], held from April 2014 to May 2014, once again brought back single-party rule in the country, with the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] being able to claim a majority in the Lok Sabha.<ref>{{cite web|title=General Election 2014|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main1/GE2014/ge.html|work=[[Election Commission of India]]|accessdate=21 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523005228/http://eci.nic.in/eci_main1/GE2014/ge.html|archive-date=23 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn recent decades, Indian politics has become a dynastic affair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/edit/need-for-accountability-in-politics-of-dynasty.html|title=Need for accountability in politics of dynasty|website=www.dailypioneer.com|access-date=17 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117002832/http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/edit/need-for-accountability-in-politics-of-dynasty.html|archive-date=17 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Possible reasons for this could be the party stability, absence of party organisations, independent civil society associations that mobilise support for the parties and centralised financing of elections.<ref name=\"ppq.sagepub.com\">{{cite journal|last1=Chhibber\u21d1|first1=Pradeep|title=Dynastic parties Organization, finance and impact|journal=Party Politics by Sage Journals|date=March 2013|volume=19|issue=2|pages=277\u2013295|doi=10.1177/1354068811406995}}</ref> {{Democracy Index rating|India|flawed democracy|2019}}\n\n== Political parties and alliances ==\n{{elect|List of political parties in India|Elections in India}}\n{{Main|2019 Indian general election}}\n\nWhen compared to other democracies, India has had a large number of political parties during its history under democratic governance. It has been estimated that over 200 parties were formed after India became independent in 1947.<ref name=CPIR>{{cite book|title=Comparative Politics & International Relations|publisher=Cosmos Bookhive|isbn=817729035-5|pages=129\u2013134|author=Prakash Chander, Prem Arora|chapter=Nature of Party System in India|year=2001}}</ref> Leadership of political parties in India is commonly interwoven with well-known families whose dynastic leaders actively play the dominant role in a party. Further, party leadership roles are often transferred to subsequent generations in the same families. The two main parties in India are the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], also known as the BJP, which is the leading right-wing party, and the [[Indian National Congress]], commonly called the INC or Congress, which is the leading centre-left leaning party. These two parties currently dominate national politics, both adhering their policies loosely to their places on the [[left\u2013right political spectrum]]. At present, there are seven national parties and many more state parties. [[File:Sansad Bhavan-1.jpg|thumb|right|280px|[[Parliament of India]]]]\n\n=== Types of political parties ===\n{{Main|List of political parties in India}}\nEvery political party in India - whether a national or regional/state party - must have a symbol and must be registered with the [[Election Commission of India]]. Symbols are used in the Indian political system to identify political parties in part so that illiterate people can vote by recognizing the party symbols.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/11/the-curious-stories-of-indian-party-symbols/|title=The Curious Stories of Indian Party Symbols|work=[[The Diplomat]]|author=Krzysztof Iwanek|date=2 November 2016|accessdate=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193824/http://thediplomat.com/2016/11/the-curious-stories-of-indian-party-symbols/|archive-date=19 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the current amendment to the Symbols Order, the Commission has asserted the following five principles:<ref name=ECI />\n# A party, National or State, must have a legislative presence.\n# A National party's legislative presence must be in the Lok Sabha. A State party's legislative presence must be in the State Assembly.\n# A party can set up a candidate only from amongst its own members.\n# A party that loses its recognition shall not lose its symbol immediately but shall be allowed to use that symbol for some time to try and retrieve its status. (However, the grant of such facility to the party will not mean the extension of other facilities to it, as are available to recognized parties, such as free time on [[Doordarshan]] or [[All India Radio|AIR]], free supply of copies of electoral rolls, etc.)\n# Recognition should be given to a party only on the basis of its own performance in elections and not because it is a splinter group of some other recognized party.\n\n'''Criteria'''\n* A political party shall be eligible to be recognized as a '''''National''''' party if:<ref name=\"ECI\">{{cite web|title=Election Commission Of India Press Note|url=http://eci.nic.in/archive/press/current/PN05122k.htm|accessdate=13 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305090629/http://eci.nic.in/archive/press/current/PN05122k.htm|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n# it secures at least '''six percent (6%)''' of the valid votes polled in any four or more states, at a general election to the House of the People or, to the State Legislative Assembly; and\n# in addition, it wins at least '''four''' seats in the House of the People from any State or States.\n;OR\nit wins at least '''two percent (2%)''' seats in the House of the People (i.e., 11 seats in the existing House having 543 members), and these members are elected from at least '''three''' different States.\n* Likewise, a political party shall be entitled to be recognized as a '''''State''''' party, if:\n\n# it secures at least '''six percent (6%)''' of the valid votes polled in the State at a general election, either to the House of the People or to the Legislative Assembly of the State concerned; and\n# in addition, it wins at least '''two''' seats in the Legislative Assembly of the State concerned.\n;OR\nit wins at least '''three percent (3%)''' of the total number of seats in the Legislative Assembly of the State, or at least '''three''' seats in the Assembly, whichever is more.\n\n===Party proliferation===\nSince 1984, when a strict anti-defection law was passed, there has been a tendency amongst the Indian politicians to float their own parties rather than join a broad based party such as the Congress or the BJP. For example, between the 1984 and 1989 elections, the number of parties contesting elections increased from 33 to 113. In the decades since, this fragmentation has continued.<ref name=\"HickenKuhonta2014\">{{cite book|author1=Allen Hicken|author2=Erik Martinez Kuhonta|title=Party System Institutionalization in Asia: Democracies, Autocracies, and the Shadows of the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZmiBQAAQBAJ&pg=PR13|date=29 December 2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-04157-8|page=205}}</ref>\n\n=== Alliances ===\nIndia has a history of party alliances and breakdown of alliances. However, there are three party alliances regularly aligning on a national level in competing for Government positions. The member parties work in harmony for gratifying national interests, although parties can jump ships. The three alliances are\u2013\n* [[National Democratic Alliance]] (NDA) - Centre-Right coalition led by [[Bhartiya Janata Party]] (BJP) was formed in 1998 after the [[1998 Indian general election|elections]]. NDA formed a government, although the government didn't last long as [[All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|AIADMK]] withdrew support from it resulting in [[1999 Indian general election|1999 general elections]], in which NDA won and resumed power. The coalition government went on to complete the full five-years term, becoming the first non-Congress government to do so. In the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 General Elections]], NDA once again returned to power for the second time, with a historic mandate of 336 out of 543 Lok Sabha seats. BJP itself won 282 seats, thereby electing [[Narendra Modi]] as the head of the government. In a historic win, the NDA stormed to power for the third term in 2019 with a combined strength of 353 seats, with the BJP itself winning an absolute majority with 303 seats\n* [[United Progressive Alliance]] (UPA) - Centre-Left coalition led by [[Indian National Congress]]; this alliance was created after the [[2004 Indian general election|2004 general elections]], with the alliance forming the Government. The alliance even after losing some of its members, was reelected in [[2009 Indian general election|2009 General Elections]] with [[Manmohan Singh]] as head of the government. The alliance has been in the opposition since the 2014 elections, with the INC being the principal opposition party, but without the official status of the Leader of Opposition since they failed to win the minimum required seats.\n* [[Third Front (India)|Third Front]] - A coalition of parties which do not belong to any of the above camps due to certain issues. One of the party in the alliance, the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]], prior to [[2009 Indian general election|2009 general elections]], was a member party of the UPA. The alliance has no official leading party, and smaller parties often enter and leave the alliance according to political convenience. Many of these parties ally at national level but contest against each other at state level. The inherent problem with such a third front is that they are only bound together by the fact that they are not aligned to either of the two 'main' alliances, and not through similar ideological stances. This often means that this alliance is merely an alliance in name and does not really provide a united front which can serve as an alternative to the two historically prominent alliances. Therefore, despite the presence of this \"Third front,\" and other seeming alternatives for those seeking options outside the INC or BJP, Indian politics by and large remains a de facto two party system at the national level.\n\n===Corruption===\n[[Corruption in India|India has seen political corruption]] for decades. After the British left the subcontinent, the corruption became to be increasingly pronounced in the country. Democratic institutions soon became federally owned, dissent was eliminated and a majority of citizens paid the price. The political corruption in India is weakening its democracy and has led to the erosion of trust by the general public in the political system. A good amount of money is required in elections which is source of political-capitalist nexus.<ref>https://www.indianmirror.com/corruption/political-corruption.html</ref>\n\n===Candidate Selection===\nPre-election alliances are common in India with parties deciding to share seats. This is seen mainly on a state by state basis rather than on the national level. Candidate selection starts after seat sharing has been agreed by alliance partners.\n\nIndian political parties have low level of internal party democracy and therefore, in Indian elections, both at the state or national level, party candidates are typically selected by the party elites, more commonly called the party high command. The party elites use a number of criteria for selecting candidates. These include the ability of the candidates to finance their own election, their educational attainment, and the level of organization the candidates have in their respective constituencies.<ref>{{cite news |title=How political parties choose their candidates to win elections |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/how-political-parties-choose-their-candidates-to-win-elections/story-26nqJKdMEQfYm8Uq29tbwJ.html |accessdate=22 April 2019 |issue=26 March 2018 |newspaper=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422184718/https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/how-political-parties-choose-their-candidates-to-win-elections/story-26nqJKdMEQfYm8Uq29tbwJ.html |archive-date=22 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Quite often the last criterion is associated with candidate criminality.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Caste Politics, Credibility and Criminality: Political Selection in India|first=Milan|last=Vaishnav|date=10 December 2011|ssrn = 1899847}}</ref>\n\n== Local governance ==\n{{Main|Municipal governance in India|Panchayati raj in India|Local self-government in India}}\nPanchayati Raj Institutions or Local self-government bodies play a crucial role in Indian politics, as it focuses on grassroot-level administration in India.\n\nOn 24 April 1993, the Constitutional (73rd Amendment) Act, 1992 came into force to provide constitutional status to the Panchayati Raj institutions. This Act was extended to Panchayats in the tribal areas of eight States, namely Andhra Pradesh, Bihar, Gujarat, Himachal Pradesh, Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, Odisha and Rajasthan from 24 December 1996.\n\nThe Act aims to provide 3-tier system of Panchayati Raj for all States having population of over 2 million, to hold Panchayat elections regularly every 5 years, to provide reservation of seats for Scheduled Castes, Scheduled Tribes and Women, to appoint State Finance Commission to make recommendations as regards the financial powers of the Panchayats and to constitute District Planning Committee to prepare draft development plan for the district.\n\n== Role of political parties ==\n{{Party politics}}\n{{elect|List of political parties in India|Elections in India}}\nAs with any other democracy, political parties represent different sections among the Indian society and regions, and their core values play a major role in the politics of India. Both the executive branch and the legislative branch of the government are run by the representatives of the political parties who have been elected through the elections. Through the electoral process, the people of India choose which representative and which political party should run the government. Through the elections any party may gain simple majority in the lower house. Coalitions are formed by the political parties, in case no single party gains a simple majority in the lower house. Unless a party or a coalition have a majority in the lower house, a government cannot be formed by that party or the coalition.\n\n[[File:State- and union territory-level parties.svg|thumb|344x344px|Current ruling parties in the states and union territories of India\n{{legend|#ff9933|[[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] (12)}}\n{{legend|#ffc969|[[National Democratic Alliance|Coalition with BJP]] (6)}}\n{{legend|#00bfff|[[Indian National Congress|INC]] (4)}}\n{{legend|#00ebff|[[United Progressive Alliance|Coalition with INC]] (2)}}\n{{legend|#ff0000|Other parties<br />([[Aam Aadmi Party|AAP]], [[All India Trinamool Congress|AITC]], [[Biju Janata Dal|BJD]], [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]], [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi|TRS]] and [[YSR Congress Party|YSRCP]]) (6)}}\n{{legend|#000000|[[President's rule]] (1)}}\n{{legend|#808080|[[Union territory|No legislature]] (5)}}]]\n\nIndia has a [[multi-party system]], where there are a number of national as well as regional parties. A regional party may gain a majority and rule a particular state. If a party is represented in more than 4 states, it would be labelled a national party. Out of the 72 years of India's independence, India has been ruled by the [[Indian National Congress]] (INC) for 53 of those years, as of January 2020.\n\nThe party enjoyed a parliamentary majority save for two brief periods during the 1970s and late 1980s. This rule was interrupted between 1977 and 1980, when the [[Janata Party]] coalition won the election owing to public discontent with the [[Indian Emergency (1975 - 77)|controversial state of emergency]] declared by the then Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]]. The [[Janata Dal]] won elections in 1989, but its government managed to hold on to power for only two years.\n\nBetween 1996 and 1998, there was a period of political flux with the government being formed first by the nationalist [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) followed by a left-leaning [[United Front (India)|United Front]] coalition. In 1998, the BJP formed the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] with smaller regional parties, and became the first non-INC and coalition government to complete a full five-year term. The [[2004 Indian general elections|2004 Indian elections]] saw the INC winning the largest number of seats to form a government leading the [[United Progressive Alliance]], and supported by left-parties and those opposed to the BJP.\n\nOn 22 May 2004, [[Manmohan Singh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianembassy.org/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126154402/https://www.indianembassy.org/India_Review/2009/June%202009.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Welcome to Embassy of India, Washington D C, USA|archivedate=26 January 2012|website=www.indianembassy.org}}</ref> was appointed the [[Prime Minister of India]] following the victory of the [[Indian National Congress|INC]] & the left front in the [[2004 Indian general election|2004 Lok Sabha election]]. The [[United Progressive Alliance|UPA]]  ruled India without the support of the left front. Previously, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]<ref name=\" Priyanka Shah\">{{cite news|title=13 Amazing Facts about Atal Ji, the Bhishma Pitamah of Indian Politics|url=http://topyaps.com/n-amazing-facts-about-atalji-the-bhishma-pitamah-of-indian-politics|accessdate=16 May 2014|newspaper=Topyaps|date=1 November 2014|author=Priyanka Shah|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911030525/http://topyaps.com/n-amazing-facts-about-atalji-the-bhishma-pitamah-of-indian-politics|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> had taken office in October 1999 after a general election in which a BJP-led coalition of 13 parties called the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] emerged with a majority. In May 2014, Narendra Modi of BJP was elected as Prime Minister of India.\n\nFormation of coalition governments reflects the transition in Indian politics away from the national parties toward smaller, more narrowly based [[regional party|regional parties]]. Some regional parties, especially in South India, are deeply aligned to the ideologies of the region unlike the national parties and thus the relationship between the central government and the state government in various states has not always been free of rancor. Disparity between the ideologies of the political parties ruling the centre and the state leads to severely skewed allocation of resources between the states.\n\n== Political Issues ==\n{{Main|Socio-economic issues in India}}\n{{See also|Corruption in India}}\n\n=== Social issues ===\nThe [[Demographics of India|lack of homogeneity]] in the Indian population causes division between different sections of the people based on [[Communalism (South Asia)|religion]], [[Regionalism (politics)|region]], [[Language politics|language]], [[Caste politics|caste]] and [[Dravidian politics|ethnicity]]. This has led to the rise of political parties with agendas catering to one or a mix of these groups. Parties in India also target people who are not in favour of other parties and use them as an asset.\n\nSome parties openly profess their focus on a particular group; for example, the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]]'s and the [[All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]]'s focus on the [[Dravidian peoples|Dravidian]] population and [[Tamil people|Tamil]] identity; [[Biju Janata Dal]]'s championing of [[Odia culture]]; the [[Shiv Sena]]'s pro-[[Marathi people|Marathi]] agenda; [[Naga People's Front]]'s demand for protection of [[Naga people|Naga]] tribal identity; [[Jammu and Kashmir Peoples Democratic Party|People's Democratic Party]] ;[[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference|National Conference]]'s calling for [[Kashmiri Muslim]] identity and The [[Telugu Desam Party]] was formed in United Andhra Pradesh by late Shri [[N.T.Rama Rao]] which demands for rights and needs of people of the state only. Some other parties claim to be universal in nature, but tend to draw support from particular sections of the population. For example, the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]] (translated as National People's Party) has a vote bank among the [[Yadav caste|Yadav]] and [[Muslim]] population of [[Bihar]] and the [[All India Trinamool Congress]] does not have any significant support outside [[West Bengal]].\n\nThe narrow focus and [[Votebank|votebank politics]] of most parties, even in the central government and central legislature, supplements national issues such as economic welfare and national security. Moreover, internal security is also threatened as incidences of political parties instigating and leading violence between two opposing groups of people is a frequent occurrence.\n\n=== Economic problems ===\n[[File:Door-to-door campaigning - Flickr - Al Jazeera English.jpg|thumb|Door-to-door campaigning of a political party workers]]\nEconomic issues like [[Poverty in India|poverty]], [[Unemployment in India|unemployment]], [[Economic development|development]] are main issues that influence politics. ''Garibi Hatao'' (eradicate poverty) has been a slogan of the [[Indian National Congress]] for a long time. The well known [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] encourages a [[free market]] economy. The more popular slogan in this field is ''Sabka Saath, Sabka Vikas'' (Cooperation with all, progress of all). The [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] vehemently supports [[left-wing]] politics like [[Land reform|land-for-all]], [[right to work]] and strongly opposes neoliberal policies such as [[globalisation]], [[capitalism]] and [[privatisation]].\n\n=== Law and order ===\n[[Terrorism in India|Terrorism]], [[Naxalism]], [[Religious violence in India|religious violence]] and [[Caste-related violence in India|caste-related violence]] are important issues that affect the political environment of the Indian nation. Stringent anti-terror legislation such as [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act|TADA]], [[Prevention of Terrorism Act, 2002|POTA]] and [[Maharashtra Control of Organised Crime Act|MCOCA]] have received much political attention, both in favour and opposed and some of these laws were disbanded eventually due to human rights violations,<ref name=\"human_rights_violation\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/asia/india-bck1121.htm|title=Anti-Terrorism Legislation|work=Human rights watch|date=20 November 2001|accessdate=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703041343/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/asia/india-bck1121.htm|archive-date=3 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> however [[UAPA]] was put into force again in 2019 after a new legislation.\n\nTerrorism has affected politics India since its conception, be it the [[Pakistan and state sponsored terrorism|terrorism supported from Pakistan]] or the internal guerrilla groups such as [[Naxalites]]. In 1991 the former prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was [[Assassination of Rajiv Gandhi|assassinated]] during an election campaign.<ref name=IAG>{{cite book|last=Guha|first=Ramachandra|title=India after Gandhi : the history of the world's largest democracy|year=2008|publisher=Picador|location=India|isbn=9780330505543\n|pages=637\u2013659|edition=Indian}}</ref> The suicide bomber was later linked to the Sri Lankan terrorist group [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]], as it was later revealed the killing was an act of vengeance for Rajiv Gandhi [[Indian intervention in the Sri Lankan Civil War|sending troops in Sri Lanka]] against them in 1987.<ref name=IAG />\n\nThe [[Demolition of Babri Masjid|Babri Masjid demolition]] on 6 December 1992 by Hindu [[Karsevaks]] and the Godhra Train Killings resulted in nationwide communal riots in two months, with worst occurring in [[Mumbai]] with at least 900 dead.<ref name=IAG /><ref>{{cite web|title=Shiv Sainiks will maintain peace post-Ayodhya verdict: Uddhav |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/shiv-sainiks-will-maintain-peace-post-ayodhya-verdict-uddhav/article1-603031.aspx |work=Hindustan Times |publisher=HT Media Ltd. |accessdate=13 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303165635/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/shiv-sainiks-will-maintain-peace-post-ayodhya-verdict-uddhav/article1-603031.aspx |archivedate=3 March 2014 }}</ref> The riots were followed by [[1993 Bombay bombings|1993 Mumbai Bomb Blasts]], which resulted in more deaths.\n\nLaw and order issues, such as action against [[Organised crime in India|organised crime]] are issues which do not affect the outcomes of elections. On the other hand, there is a criminal\u2013politician nexus. Many elected legislators have criminal cases against them. In July 2008, the ''[[Washington Post]]'' reported that nearly a fourth of the 540 [[Indian Parliament]] members faced criminal charges, \"including [[human trafficking]], [[Prostitution in India|child prostitution]] immigration rackets, [[embezzlement]], [[rape]] and even [[murder]]\".<ref name=\"wtcorruption\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/23/AR2008072303390.html|title=With Indian Politics, the Bad Gets Worse|work=The Washington Post|first=Emily|last=Wax|date=24 July 2008|accessdate=22 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108050648/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/23/AR2008072303390.html|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== High Political Offices in India ==\n=== President of India ===\n{{main|President of India}}\n\nThe Constitution of India lays down that the Head of State and Union Executive is the President of India. She/He is elected for a five-year term by an electoral college consisting of members of both Houses of Parliament and members of legislative assemblies of the states. The President is eligible for re-elections; however, in India's independent history, only one president has been re-elected, [[Rajendra Prasad]].\n\nThe President appoints the Prime Minister of India from the party or coalition which commands maximum support of the Lok Sabha, on whose recommendation he/she nominates the other ministers. The President also appoints judges of the Supreme Court and High Court. It is on the President's recommendation that the Houses of Parliament meet, and only the president has the power to dissolve the Lok Sabha. Furthermore, no bill passed by Parliament can become law without the president's assent.\n\nHowever, the role of the president of India is highly ceremonial. All the powers of the president mentioned above are exercised on recommendation of the Union [[Indian Cabinet|Cabinet]], and the president does not have much discretion in any of these matters. The president also does not have discretion in the exercise of his executive powers, as the real executive authority lies in the cabinet. The current President is [[Ram Nath Kovind]].\n\n=== Vice President of India ===\n{{main|Vice President of India}}\n\nThe Office of the Vice-President of India is constitutionally the second most senior office in the country, after the President. The vice-president is also elected by an electoral college, consisting of members of both houses of parliament.\n\nLike the president, the role of the Vice-President is also ceremonial, with no real authority vested in him/her. The Vice-President fills in a vacancy in the office of President (till the election of a new president). His only regular function is that he functions as the Chairman of the [[Rajya Sabha]]. No other duties/powers are vested in the office. The current Vice President is [[Venkaiah Naidu]].\n\n=== The Prime Minister and the Union Council of Ministers ===\n{{further|Prime Minister of India|Union Council of Ministers|Second Modi ministry}}\nThe Union Council of Ministers, headed by the Prime Minister, is the body with which the real executive power resides. The Prime Minister is the recognized head of the government.\n\nThe Union Council of Ministers is the body of ministers with which the PM works with on a day-to-day basis. Work is divided between various ministers into various departments and ministries. The Union cabinet is a smaller body of ministers which lies within the Council of Ministers, which is the most powerful set of people in the country, playing an instrumental role in legislation and execution alike. \n\nAll members of the Union Council of ministers must be members of either House of Parliament at the time of appointment or must get elected/nominated to either House within six months of their appointment.\n\nIt is the Union Cabinet that co-ordinates all foreign and domestic policy of the Union. It exercises immense control over administration, finance, legislation, military, etc. The Head of the Union Cabinet is the Prime Minister. The current Prime Minister of India is [[Narendra Modi]].\n\n== State Governments ==\n{{main|State governments of India}}\nIndia has a [[Federalism in India|federal form]] of government, and hence each state also has its own government. The executive of each state is the Governor (equivalent to the president of India), whose role is ceremonial. The real power resides with the Chief Minister (equivalent to the Prime Minister) and the state council of ministers. States may either have a unicameral or bicameral legislature, varying from state to state. The Chief Minister and other state ministers are also members of the legislature.\n\n== [[Nepotism]] in Indian Politics ==\n{{main|Political families of India}}\nSince the 1980s, Indian politics has become dynastic, possibly due to the absence of a party organization, independent civil society associations that mobilize support for the party, and centralized financing of elections.<ref name=\"ppq.sagepub.com\"/> This phenomenon is seen from national level down to district level. One example of dynastic politics has been the [[Nehru\u2013Gandhi family]] which produced [[List of prime ministers of India|three]] [[Prime Minister of India|Indian prime ministers]]. Family members have also led the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] for most of the period since 1978 when Indira Gandhi floated the then Congress(I) faction of the party.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Basu|first1=Amrita|last2=Chandra (Editor)|first2=Kanchan|title=Democratic Dynasties: State, Party and Family in Contemporary Indian Politics|date=2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, UK|isbn=978-1-107-12344-1|page=136|edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tesIDAAAQBAJ&pg=PR10&dq=%22political+dynasties%22+india#v=onepage&q=sonia&f=false|accessdate=23 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110030054/https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=tesIDAAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR10&dq=%22political+dynasties%22+india&ots=panvSUPVV9&sig=rBLRMVvTQ2f7mX6q3bm6Gj6eyfw#v=onepage&q=sonia&f=false|archive-date=10 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Dynastic politics is prevalent also in a  number of political parties with regional presence such as [[All India Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen]], [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]], [[Indian National Lok Dal]], [[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference]], [[Jammu and Kashmir Peoples Democratic Party]], [[Janata Dal (Secular)]], [[Jharkhand Mukti Morcha]], [[National People's Party (India)|National People's Party]], [[Nationalist Congress Party]], [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]], [[Rashtriya Lok Dal]], [[Samajwadi Party]], [[Shiromani Akali Dal]], [[Shiv Sena]], [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]] and [[Telugu Desam Party]]. <ref name=\"Chandra2016\">{{cite book|author=Kanchan Chandra|title=Democratic Dynasties: State, Party, and Family in Contemporary Indian Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VwbFDAAAQBAJ&pg=PR10|date=28 April 2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-316-59212-0|page=131,136}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Government of India]]\n* [[State governments of India]]\n* [[Law of India]]\n* [[Indian political scandals]]\n* [[Disqualification of convicted representatives in India]]\n* [[Political families of India]]\n* [[List of think tanks in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [[Satyabrata Rai Chowdhuri|Chowdhuri, Satyabrata Rai]]. [http://www.palgrave.com/products/title.aspx?PID=278315 ''Leftism in India, 1917-1947'']. '''Palgrave''', [[U.K.]], 2007.\n* Shively, W. Phillips. ''Power and Choice: An Introduction to Political Science\u2014Chapter 14 Example: Parliamentary Government in India.'' McGraw Hill Higher Education, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-07-340391-5}}\n* Mitra, Subrata K. and Singh, V.B.. ''Democracy and Social Change in India: A Cross-Sectional Analysis of the National Electorate''. New Delhi: Sage Publications, 1999. {{ISBN|81-7036-809-X}} (India HB) {{ISBN|0-7619-9344-4}} (U.S. HB).\n* Shourie, Arun (2007). The parliamentary system: What we have made of it, what we can make of it. New Delhi: Rupa & Co.\n* Shourie, Arun (2005). Governance and the sclerosis that has set in. New Delhi: ASA Publications.\n* Tawa Lama-Rewal, St\u00e9phanie. [http://samaj.revues.org/index2784.html ''\"Studying Elections in India: Scientific and Political Debates\"'']. ''South Asia Multidisciplinary Academic Journal, 3, 2009.\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Politics of India}}\n* [http://india.gov.in/ Outline of the Indian Government]\n*'''[https://www.patriotictech.com/2020/02/indian-political-system.html How Indian political system work]''' \n\n{{-}}\n{{Asia topic|Politics of}}\n{{India topics}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of India| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Political system of India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox political system\n| name                          = Politics of India\n| native_name                   =\n| image                         = Emblem of India.svg\n| image_size                    = 100\n| caption                       = [[State Emblem of India]]\n| type                          = [[Federation|Federal]] [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[Constitutionalism|constitutional]] [[republic]]\n| constitution                  = [[Constitution of India]]\n| legislature                   = [[Parliament of India|Parliament]]\n| legislature_type              = [[Bicameralism|Bicameral]]\n| legislature_place             = [[Parliament House (India)|Parliament House]]\n| legislature_speaker           = \n| legislature_speaker_title     =\n| upperhouse                    = [[Rajya Sabha|Council of States]]\n| upperhouse_speaker            = [[Venkaiah Naidu]]\n| upperhouse_speaker_title      = [[Chairman of the Rajya Sabha|Chairman of the Council of States]]\n| upperhouse_appointer          = [[Electoral College (India)|Electoral College]]\n| lowerhouse                    = [[Lok Sabha|House of the People]]\n| lowerhouse_speaker            = [[Om Birla]]\n| lowerhouse_speaker_title      = [[Speaker of the Lok Sabha|Speaker of the House of the People]]\n| lowerhouse_appointer          = \n| title_hos                     = [[President of India|President]]\n| current_hos                   = [[Ram Nath Kovind]]\n| appointer_hos                 = Electoral College\n| title_hog                     = [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]]\n| current_hog                   = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| appointer_hog                 = President\n| title_hosag                   = \n| current_hosag                 =\n| appointer_hosag               =\n| cabinet                       = [[Union Council of Ministers]]\n| current_cabinet               = [[Second Modi ministry]]\n| cabinet_leader                = Prime Minister\n| cabinet_deputyleader          = \n| cabinet_appointer             = President\n| cabinet_hq                    =\n| cabinet_ministries            = [[Union Government ministries of India|52]]\n| judiciary                     = [[Judiciary of India|Judiciary]]\n| judiciary_head                = [[Sharad Arvind Bobde]]\n| courts                        =\n| court                         = [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]]\n| chief_judge                   = [[Sharad Arvind Bobde]]\n| court_seat                    = \n| court1                        =\n| chief_judge1                  =\n| court_seat1                   =\n}}\n{{Politics of India}}\nThe '''politics of India''' works within the framework of the country's [[Constitution of India|constitution]]. India is a [[Federation|federal]] [[Parliamentary republic|parliamentary]] [[democratic republic]] in which the  [[President of India]]  is the [[head of state]] and the [[Prime Minister of India]] is the [[head of government]]. India follows the dual polity system, i.e. a double government (federal in nature) that consists of the central authority at the centre and [[States and union territories of India|states]] at the periphery. The constitution defines the organisational powers and limitations of both central and state governments, and it is well recognised, rigid and considered supreme; i.e. the [[Law of India|laws]] of the nation must confirm to it.\n\nThere is a provision for a [[Bicameralism|bicameral]] [[legislature]] consisting of an [[upper house]], the [[Rajya Sabha]] (Council of States), which represents the states of the Indian federation, and a [[lower house]], the [[Lok Sabha]] (House of the People), which represents the people of India as a whole. The Indian constitution provides for an [[Judicial independence|independent]] [[judiciary]], which is headed by the [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]]. The court's mandate is to protect the constitution, to settle disputes between the central government and the states, to settle inter-state disputes, to nullify any central or state laws that go against the constitution and to protect the fundamental rights of citizens, issuing [[writs]] for their enforcement in cases of violation.<ref>{{cite book|title=Public Administration|publisher=Tata Mcgraw Hill|isbn=978-0071074827|pages=389\u2013390|author=M.Lakshmikanth|edition=9th|year=2012}}</ref>\nThere are 543 members in the Lok Sabha, who are elected from the 543 Indian constituencies.\nThere are 245 members in the Rajya Sabha, out of which 233 are elected by indirect elections by single transferable vote by the members of the state legislative assemblies and other 12 members are elected/nominated by the President of India.\nGovernments are formed through [[Elections in India|elections]] held every five years (unless otherwise specified), by parties that secure a majority of members in their respective lower houses (Lok Sabha in the central government and [[Vidhan Sabha]] in states). India had [[1951 Indian general election|its first general election]] in 1951, which was won by the [[Indian National Congress]], a political party that went on to dominate subsequent elections until [[1977 Indian general election|1977]], when a non-Congress government was formed for the first time in independent India. The 1990s saw the end of [[Dominant-party system|single-party domination]] and the rise of coalition governments. The [[2014 Indian general election|elections]] for the [[16th Lok Sabha]], held from April 2014 to May 2014, once again brought back single-party rule in the country, with the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] being able to claim a majority in the Lok Sabha.<ref>{{cite web|title=General Election 2014|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main1/GE2014/ge.html|work=[[Election Commission of India]]|accessdate=21 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523005228/http://eci.nic.in/eci_main1/GE2014/ge.html|archive-date=23 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn recent decades, Indian politics has become a dynastic affair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/edit/need-for-accountability-in-politics-of-dynasty.html|title=Need for accountability in politics of dynasty|website=www.dailypioneer.com|access-date=17 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117002832/http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/edit/need-for-accountability-in-politics-of-dynasty.html|archive-date=17 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Possible reasons for this could be the party stability, absence of party organisations, independent civil society associations that mobilise support for the parties and centralised financing of elections.<ref name=\"ppq.sagepub.com\">{{cite journal|last1=Chhibber\u21d1|first1=Pradeep|title=Dynastic parties Organization, finance and impact|journal=Party Politics by Sage Journals|date=March 2013|volume=19|issue=2|pages=277\u2013295|doi=10.1177/1354068811406995}}</ref> {{Democracy Index rating|India|flawed democracy|2019}}\n\n== Political parties and alliances ==\n{{elect|List of political parties in India|Elections in India}}\n{{Main|2019 Indian general election}}\n\nWhen compared to other democracies, India has had a large number of political parties during its history under democratic governance. It has been estimated that over 200 parties were formed after India became independent in 1947.<ref name=CPIR>{{cite book|title=Comparative Politics & International Relations|publisher=Cosmos Bookhive|isbn=817729035-5|pages=129\u2013134|author=Prakash Chander, Prem Arora|chapter=Nature of Party System in India|year=2001}}</ref> Leadership of political parties in India is commonly interwoven with well-known families whose dynastic leaders actively play the dominant role in a party. Further, party leadership roles are often transferred to subsequent generations in the same families. The two main parties in India are the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], also known as the BJP, which is the leading right-wing party, and the [[Indian National Congress]], commonly called the INC or Congress, which is the leading centre-left leaning party. These two parties currently dominate national politics, both adhering their policies loosely to their places on the [[left\u2013right political spectrum]]. At present, there are seven national parties and many more state parties. [[File:Sansad Bhavan-1.jpg|thumb|right|280px|[[Parliament of India]]]]\n\n=== Types of political parties ===\n{{Main|List of political parties in India}}\nEvery political party in India - whether a national or regional/state party - must have a symbol and must be registered with the [[Election Commission of India]]. Symbols are used in the Indian political system to identify political parties in part so that illiterate people can vote by recognizing the party symbols.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/11/the-curious-stories-of-indian-party-symbols/|title=The Curious Stories of Indian Party Symbols|work=[[The Diplomat]]|author=Krzysztof Iwanek|date=2 November 2016|accessdate=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419193824/http://thediplomat.com/2016/11/the-curious-stories-of-indian-party-symbols/|archive-date=19 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the current amendment to the Symbols Order, the Commission has asserted the following five principles:<ref name=ECI />\n# A party, National or State, must have a legislative presence.\n# A National party's legislative presence must be in the Lok Sabha. A State party's legislative presence must be in the State Assembly.\n# A party can set up a candidate only from amongst its own members.\n# A party that loses its recognition shall not lose its symbol immediately but shall be allowed to use that symbol for some time to try and retrieve its status. (However, the grant of such facility to the party will not mean the extension of other facilities to it, as are available to recognized parties, such as free time on [[Doordarshan]] or [[All India Radio|AIR]], free supply of copies of electoral rolls, etc.)\n# Recognition should be given to a party only on the basis of its own performance in elections and not because it is a splinter group of some other recognized party.\n\n'''Criteria'''\n* A political party shall be eligible to be recognized as a '''''National''''' party if:<ref name=\"ECI\">{{cite web|title=Election Commission Of India Press Note|url=http://eci.nic.in/archive/press/current/PN05122k.htm|accessdate=13 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305090629/http://eci.nic.in/archive/press/current/PN05122k.htm|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n# it secures at least '''six percent (6%)''' of the valid votes polled in any four or more states, at a general election to the House of the People or, to the State Legislative Assembly; and\n# in addition, it wins at least '''four''' seats in the House of the People from any State or States.\n;OR\nit wins at least '''two percent (2%)''' seats in the House of the People (i.e., 11 seats in the existing House having 543 members), and these members are elected from at least '''three''' different States.\n* Likewise, a political party shall be entitled to be recognized as a '''''State''''' party, if:\n\n# it secures at least '''six percent (6%)''' of the valid votes polled in the State at a general election, either to the House of the People or to the Legislative Assembly of the State concerned; and\n# in addition, it wins at least '''two''' seats in the Legislative Assembly of the State concerned.\n;OR\nit wins at least '''three percent (3%)''' of the total number of seats in the Legislative Assembly of the State, or at least '''three''' seats in the Assembly, whichever is more.\n\n===Party proliferation===\nSince 1984, when a strict anti-defection law was passed, there has been a tendency amongst the Indian politicians to float their own parties rather than join a broad based party such as the Congress or the BJP. For example, between the 1984 and 1989 elections, the number of parties contesting elections increased from 33 to 113. In the decades since, this fragmentation has continued.<ref name=\"HickenKuhonta2014\">{{cite book|author1=Allen Hicken|author2=Erik Martinez Kuhonta|title=Party System Institutionalization in Asia: Democracies, Autocracies, and the Shadows of the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZmiBQAAQBAJ&pg=PR13|date=29 December 2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-04157-8|page=205}}</ref>\n\n=== Alliances ===\nIndia has a history of party alliances and breakdown of alliances. However, there are three party alliances regularly aligning on a national level in competing for Government positions. The member parties work in harmony for gratifying national interests, although parties can jump ships. The three alliances are\u2013\n* [[National Democratic Alliance]] (NDA) - Centre-Right coalition led by [[Bhartiya Janata Party]] (BJP) was formed in 1998 after the [[1998 Indian general election|elections]]. NDA formed a government, although the government didn't last long as [[All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam|AIADMK]] withdrew support from it resulting in [[1999 Indian general election|1999 general elections]], in which NDA won and resumed power. The coalition government went on to complete the full five-years term, becoming the first non-Congress government to do so. In the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 General Elections]], NDA once again returned to power for the second time, with a historic mandate of 336 out of 543 Lok Sabha seats. BJP itself won 282 seats, thereby electing [[Narendra Modi]] as the head of the government. In a historic win, the NDA stormed to power for the third term in 2019 with a combined strength of 353 seats, with the BJP itself winning an absolute majority with 303 seats\n* [[United Progressive Alliance]] (UPA) - Centre-Left coalition led by [[Indian National Congress]]; this alliance was created after the [[2004 Indian general election|2004 general elections]], with the alliance forming the Government. The alliance even after losing some of its members, was reelected in [[2009 Indian general election|2009 General Elections]] with [[Manmohan Singh]] as head of the government. The alliance has been in the opposition since the 2014 elections, with the INC being the principal opposition party, but without the official status of the Leader of Opposition since they failed to win the minimum required seats.\n* [[Third Front (India)|Third Front]] - A coalition of parties which do not belong to any of the above camps due to certain issues. One of the party in the alliance, the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]], prior to [[2009 Indian general election|2009 general elections]], was a member party of the UPA. The alliance has no official leading party, and smaller parties often enter and leave the alliance according to political convenience. Many of these parties ally at national level but contest against each other at state level. The inherent problem with such a third front is that they are only bound together by the fact that they are not aligned to either of the two 'main' alliances, and not through similar ideological stances. This often means that this alliance is merely an alliance in name and does not really provide a united front which can serve as an alternative to the two historically prominent alliances. Therefore, despite the presence of this \"Third front,\" and other seeming alternatives for those seeking options outside the INC or BJP, Indian politics by and large remains a de facto two party system at the national level.\n\n===Corruption===\n[[Corruption in India|India has seen political corruption]] for decades. After the British left the subcontinent, the corruption became to be increasingly pronounced in the country. Democratic institutions soon became federally owned, dissent was eliminated and a majority of citizens paid the price. The political corruption in India is weakening its democracy and has led to the erosion of trust by the general public in the political system. A good amount of money is required in elections which is source of political-capitalist nexus.<ref>https://www.indianmirror.com/corruption/political-corruption.html</ref>\n\n===Candidate selection===\nPre-election alliances are common in India with parties deciding to share seats. This is seen mainly on a state by state basis rather than on the national level. Candidate selection starts after seat sharing has been agreed by alliance partners.\n\nIndian political parties have low level of internal party democracy and therefore, in Indian elections, both at the state or national level, party candidates are typically selected by the party elites, more commonly called the party high command. The party elites use a number of criteria for selecting candidates. These include the ability of the candidates to finance their own election, their educational attainment, and the level of organization the candidates have in their respective constituencies.<ref>{{cite news |title=How political parties choose their candidates to win elections |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/how-political-parties-choose-their-candidates-to-win-elections/story-26nqJKdMEQfYm8Uq29tbwJ.html |accessdate=22 April 2019 |issue=26 March 2018 |newspaper=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422184718/https://www.hindustantimes.com/opinion/how-political-parties-choose-their-candidates-to-win-elections/story-26nqJKdMEQfYm8Uq29tbwJ.html |archive-date=22 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Quite often the last criterion is associated with candidate criminality.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Caste Politics, Credibility and Criminality: Political Selection in India|first=Milan|last=Vaishnav|date=10 December 2011|ssrn = 1899847}}</ref>\n\n== Local governance ==\n{{Main|Municipal governance in India|Panchayati raj in India|Local self-government in India}}\nPanchayati Raj Institutions or Local self-government bodies play a crucial role in Indian politics, as it focuses on grassroot-level administration in India.\n\nOn 24 April 1993, the Constitutional (73rd Amendment) Act, 1992 came into force to provide constitutional status to the Panchayati Raj institutions. This Act was extended to Panchayats in the tribal areas of eight States, namely Andhra Pradesh, Bihar, Gujarat, Himachal Pradesh, Maharashtra, Madhya Pradesh, Odisha and Rajasthan from 24 December 1996.\n\nThe Act aims to provide 3-tier system of Panchayati Raj for all States having population of over 2 million, to hold Panchayat elections regularly every 5 years, to provide reservation of seats for Scheduled Castes, Scheduled Tribes and Women, to appoint State Finance Commission to make recommendations as regards the financial powers of the Panchayats and to constitute District Planning Committee to prepare draft development plan for the district.\n\n== Role of political parties ==\n{{Party politics}}\n{{elect|List of political parties in India|Elections in India}}\nAs with any other democracy, political parties represent different sections among the Indian society and regions, and their core values play a major role in the politics of India. Both the executive branch and the legislative branch of the government are run by the representatives of the political parties who have been elected through the elections. Through the electoral process, the people of India choose which representative and which political party should run the government. Through the elections any party may gain simple majority in the lower house. Coalitions are formed by the political parties, in case no single party gains a simple majority in the lower house. Unless a party or a coalition have a majority in the lower house, a government cannot be formed by that party or the coalition.\n\n[[File:State- and union territory-level parties.svg|thumb|344x344px|Current ruling parties in the states and union territories of India\n{{legend|#ff9933|[[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] (12)}}\n{{legend|#ffc969|[[National Democratic Alliance|Coalition with BJP]] (6)}}\n{{legend|#00bfff|[[Indian National Congress|INC]] (4)}}\n{{legend|#00ebff|[[United Progressive Alliance|Coalition with INC]] (2)}}\n{{legend|#ff0000|Other parties<br />([[Aam Aadmi Party|AAP]], [[All India Trinamool Congress|AITC]], [[Biju Janata Dal|BJD]], [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]], [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi|TRS]] and [[YSR Congress Party|YSRCP]]) (6)}}\n{{legend|#000000|[[President's rule]] (1)}}\n{{legend|#808080|[[Union territory|No legislature]] (5)}}]]\n\nIndia has a [[multi-party system]], where there are a number of national as well as regional parties. A regional party may gain a majority and rule a particular state. If a party is represented in more than 4 states, it would be labelled a national party. Out of the 72 years of India's independence, India has been ruled by the [[Indian National Congress]] (INC) for 53 of those years, as of January 2020.\n\nThe party enjoyed a parliamentary majority save for two brief periods during the 1970s and late 1980s. This rule was interrupted between 1977 and 1980, when the [[Janata Party]] coalition won the election owing to public discontent with the [[Indian Emergency (1975 - 77)|controversial state of emergency]] declared by the then Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]]. The [[Janata Dal]] won elections in 1989, but its government managed to hold on to power for only two years.\n\nBetween 1996 and 1998, there was a period of political flux with the government being formed first by the nationalist [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) followed by a left-leaning [[United Front (India)|United Front]] coalition. In 1998, the BJP formed the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] with smaller regional parties, and became the first non-INC and coalition government to complete a full five-year term. The [[2004 Indian general elections|2004 Indian elections]] saw the INC winning the largest number of seats to form a government leading the [[United Progressive Alliance]], and supported by left-parties and those opposed to the BJP.\n\nOn 22 May 2004, [[Manmohan Singh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indianembassy.org/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126154402/https://www.indianembassy.org/India_Review/2009/June%202009.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Welcome to Embassy of India, Washington D C, USA|archivedate=26 January 2012|website=www.indianembassy.org}}</ref> was appointed the [[Prime Minister of India]] following the victory of the [[Indian National Congress|INC]] & the left front in the [[2004 Indian general election|2004 Lok Sabha election]]. The [[United Progressive Alliance|UPA]]  ruled India without the support of the left front. Previously, [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]]<ref name=\" Priyanka Shah\">{{cite news|title=13 Amazing Facts about Atal Ji, the Bhishma Pitamah of Indian Politics|url=http://topyaps.com/n-amazing-facts-about-atalji-the-bhishma-pitamah-of-indian-politics|accessdate=16 May 2014|newspaper=Topyaps|date=1 November 2014|author=Priyanka Shah|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911030525/http://topyaps.com/n-amazing-facts-about-atalji-the-bhishma-pitamah-of-indian-politics|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> had taken office in October 1999 after a general election in which a BJP-led coalition of 13 parties called the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] emerged with a majority. In May 2014, Narendra Modi of BJP was elected as Prime Minister of India.\n\nFormation of coalition governments reflects the transition in Indian politics away from the national parties toward smaller, more narrowly based [[regional party|regional parties]]. Some regional parties, especially in South India, are deeply aligned to the ideologies of the region unlike the national parties and thus the relationship between the central government and the state government in various states has not always been free of rancor. Disparity between the ideologies of the political parties ruling the centre and the state leads to severely skewed allocation of resources between the states.\n\n== Political issues ==\n{{Main|Socio-economic issues in India}}\n{{See also|Corruption in India}}\n\n=== Social issues ===\nThe [[Demographics of India|lack of homogeneity]] in the Indian population causes division between different sections of the people based on [[Communalism (South Asia)|religion]], [[Regionalism (politics)|region]], [[Language politics|language]], [[Caste politics|caste]] and [[Dravidian politics|ethnicity]]. This has led to the rise of political parties with agendas catering to one or a mix of these groups. Parties in India also target people who are not in favour of other parties and use them as an asset.\n\nSome parties openly profess their focus on a particular group; for example, the [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]]'s and the [[All India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]]'s focus on the [[Dravidian peoples|Dravidian]] population and [[Tamil people|Tamil]] identity; [[Biju Janata Dal]]'s championing of [[Odia culture]]; the [[Shiv Sena]]'s pro-[[Marathi people|Marathi]] agenda; [[Naga People's Front]]'s demand for protection of [[Naga people|Naga]] tribal identity; [[Jammu and Kashmir Peoples Democratic Party|People's Democratic Party]] ;[[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference|National Conference]]'s calling for [[Kashmiri Muslim]] identity and The [[Telugu Desam Party]] was formed in United Andhra Pradesh by late Shri [[N.T.Rama Rao]] which demands for rights and needs of people of the state only. Some other parties claim to be universal in nature, but tend to draw support from particular sections of the population. For example, the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]] (translated as National People's Party) has a vote bank among the [[Yadav caste|Yadav]] and [[Muslim]] population of [[Bihar]] and the [[All India Trinamool Congress]] does not have any significant support outside [[West Bengal]].\n\nThe narrow focus and [[Votebank|votebank politics]] of most parties, even in the central government and central legislature, supplements national issues such as economic welfare and national security. Moreover, internal security is also threatened as incidences of political parties instigating and leading violence between two opposing groups of people is a frequent occurrence.\n\n=== Economic problems ===\n[[File:Door-to-door campaigning - Flickr - Al Jazeera English.jpg|thumb|Door-to-door campaigning of a political party workers]]\nEconomic issues like [[Poverty in India|poverty]], [[Unemployment in India|unemployment]], [[Economic development|development]] are main issues that influence politics. ''Garibi Hatao'' (eradicate poverty) has been a slogan of the [[Indian National Congress]] for a long time. The well known [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] encourages a [[free market]] economy. The more popular slogan in this field is ''Sabka Saath, Sabka Vikas'' (Cooperation with all, progress of all). The [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] vehemently supports [[left-wing]] politics like [[Land reform|land-for-all]], [[right to work]] and strongly opposes neoliberal policies such as [[globalisation]], [[capitalism]] and [[privatisation]].\n\n=== Law and order ===\n[[Terrorism in India|Terrorism]], [[Naxalism]], [[Religious violence in India|religious violence]] and [[Caste-related violence in India|caste-related violence]] are important issues that affect the political environment of the Indian nation. Stringent anti-terror legislation such as [[Terrorist and Disruptive Activities (Prevention) Act|TADA]], [[Prevention of Terrorism Act, 2002|POTA]] and [[Maharashtra Control of Organised Crime Act|MCOCA]] have received much political attention, both in favour and opposed and some of these laws were disbanded eventually due to human rights violations,<ref name=\"human_rights_violation\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/asia/india-bck1121.htm|title=Anti-Terrorism Legislation|work=Human rights watch|date=20 November 2001|accessdate=6 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703041343/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/asia/india-bck1121.htm|archive-date=3 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> however [[UAPA]] was put into force again in 2019 after a new legislation.\n\nTerrorism has affected politics India since its conception, be it the [[Pakistan and state sponsored terrorism|terrorism supported from Pakistan]] or the internal guerrilla groups such as [[Naxalites]]. In 1991 the former prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was [[Assassination of Rajiv Gandhi|assassinated]] during an election campaign.<ref name=IAG>{{cite book|last=Guha|first=Ramachandra|title=India after Gandhi : the history of the world's largest democracy|year=2008|publisher=Picador|location=India|isbn=9780330505543\n|pages=637\u2013659|edition=Indian}}</ref> The suicide bomber was later linked to the Sri Lankan terrorist group [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]], as it was later revealed the killing was an act of vengeance for Rajiv Gandhi [[Indian intervention in the Sri Lankan Civil War|sending troops in Sri Lanka]] against them in 1987.<ref name=IAG />\n\nThe [[Demolition of Babri Masjid|Babri Masjid demolition]] on 6 December 1992 by Hindu [[Karsevaks]] and the Godhra Train Killings resulted in nationwide communal riots in two months, with worst occurring in [[Mumbai]] with at least 900 dead.<ref name=IAG /><ref>{{cite web|title=Shiv Sainiks will maintain peace post-Ayodhya verdict: Uddhav |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/shiv-sainiks-will-maintain-peace-post-ayodhya-verdict-uddhav/article1-603031.aspx |work=Hindustan Times |publisher=HT Media Ltd. |accessdate=13 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303165635/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/shiv-sainiks-will-maintain-peace-post-ayodhya-verdict-uddhav/article1-603031.aspx |archivedate=3 March 2014 }}</ref> The riots were followed by [[1993 Bombay bombings|1993 Mumbai Bomb Blasts]], which resulted in more deaths.\n\nLaw and order issues, such as action against [[Organised crime in India|organised crime]] are issues which do not affect the outcomes of elections. On the other hand, there is a criminal\u2013politician nexus. Many elected legislators have criminal cases against them. In July 2008, the ''[[Washington Post]]'' reported that nearly a fourth of the 540 [[Indian Parliament]] members faced criminal charges, \"including [[human trafficking]], [[Prostitution in India|child prostitution]] immigration rackets, [[embezzlement]], [[rape]] and even [[murder]]\".<ref name=\"wtcorruption\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/23/AR2008072303390.html|title=With Indian Politics, the Bad Gets Worse|work=The Washington Post|first=Emily|last=Wax|date=24 July 2008|accessdate=22 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108050648/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/23/AR2008072303390.html|archive-date=8 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== High Political Offices in India ==\n=== President of India ===\n{{main|President of India}}\n\nThe Constitution of India lays down that the Head of State and Union Executive is the President of India. She/He is elected for a five-year term by an electoral college consisting of members of both Houses of Parliament and members of legislative assemblies of the states. The President is eligible for re-elections; however, in India's independent history, only one president has been re-elected, [[Rajendra Prasad]].\n\nThe President appoints the Prime Minister of India from the party or coalition which commands maximum support of the Lok Sabha, on whose recommendation he/she nominates the other ministers. The President also appoints judges of the Supreme Court and High Court. It is on the President's recommendation that the Houses of Parliament meet, and only the president has the power to dissolve the Lok Sabha. Furthermore, no bill passed by Parliament can become law without the president's assent.\n\nHowever, the role of the president of India is highly ceremonial. All the powers of the president mentioned above are exercised on recommendation of the Union [[Indian Cabinet|Cabinet]], and the president does not have much discretion in any of these matters. The president also does not have discretion in the exercise of his executive powers, as the real executive authority lies in the cabinet. The current President is [[Ram Nath Kovind]].\n\n=== Vice President of India ===\n{{main|Vice President of India}}\n\nThe Office of the Vice-President of India is constitutionally the second most senior office in the country, after the President. The vice-president is also elected by an electoral college, consisting of members of both houses of parliament.\n\nLike the president, the role of the Vice-President is also ceremonial, with no real authority vested in him/her. The Vice-President fills in a vacancy in the office of President (till the election of a new president). His only regular function is that he functions as the Chairman of the [[Rajya Sabha]]. No other duties/powers are vested in the office. The current Vice President is [[Venkaiah Naidu]].\n\n=== The Prime Minister and the Union Council of Ministers ===\n{{further|Prime Minister of India|Union Council of Ministers|Second Modi ministry}}\nThe Union Council of Ministers, headed by the Prime Minister, is the body with which the real executive power resides. The Prime Minister is the recognized head of the government.\n\nThe Union Council of Ministers is the body of ministers with which the PM works with on a day-to-day basis. Work is divided between various ministers into various departments and ministries. The Union cabinet is a smaller body of ministers which lies within the Council of Ministers, which is the most powerful set of people in the country, playing an instrumental role in legislation and execution alike. \n\nAll members of the Union Council of ministers must be members of either House of Parliament at the time of appointment or must get elected/nominated to either House within six months of their appointment.\n\nIt is the Union Cabinet that co-ordinates all foreign and domestic policy of the Union. It exercises immense control over administration, finance, legislation, military, etc. The Head of the Union Cabinet is the Prime Minister. The current Prime Minister of India is [[Narendra Modi]].\n\n== State Governments ==\n{{main|State governments of India}}\nIndia has a [[Federalism in India|federal form]] of government, and hence each state also has its own government. The executive of each state is the Governor (equivalent to the president of India), whose role is ceremonial. The real power resides with the Chief Minister (equivalent to the Prime Minister) and the state council of ministers. States may either have a unicameral or bicameral legislature, varying from state to state. The Chief Minister and other state ministers are also members of the legislature.\n\n== [[Nepotism]] in Indian Politics ==\n{{main|Political families of India}}\nSince the 1980s, Indian politics has become dynastic, possibly due to the absence of a party organization, independent civil society associations that mobilize support for the party, and centralized financing of elections.<ref name=\"ppq.sagepub.com\"/> This phenomenon is seen from national level down to district level. One example of dynastic politics has been the [[Nehru\u2013Gandhi family]] which produced [[List of prime ministers of India|three]] [[Prime Minister of India|Indian prime ministers]]. Family members have also led the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] for most of the period since 1978 when Indira Gandhi floated the then Congress(I) faction of the party.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Basu|first1=Amrita|last2=Chandra (Editor)|first2=Kanchan|title=Democratic Dynasties: State, Party and Family in Contemporary Indian Politics|date=2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, UK|isbn=978-1-107-12344-1|page=136|edition=1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tesIDAAAQBAJ&pg=PR10&dq=%22political+dynasties%22+india#v=onepage&q=sonia&f=false|accessdate=23 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110030054/https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=tesIDAAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR10&dq=%22political+dynasties%22+india&ots=panvSUPVV9&sig=rBLRMVvTQ2f7mX6q3bm6Gj6eyfw#v=onepage&q=sonia&f=false|archive-date=10 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Dynastic politics is prevalent also in a  number of political parties with regional presence such as [[All India Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen]], [[Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam]], [[Indian National Lok Dal]], [[Jammu & Kashmir National Conference]], [[Jammu and Kashmir Peoples Democratic Party]], [[Janata Dal (Secular)]], [[Jharkhand Mukti Morcha]], [[National People's Party (India)|National People's Party]], [[Nationalist Congress Party]], [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]], [[Rashtriya Lok Dal]], [[Samajwadi Party]], [[Shiromani Akali Dal]], [[Shiv Sena]], [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]] and [[Telugu Desam Party]]. <ref name=\"Chandra2016\">{{cite book|author=Kanchan Chandra|title=Democratic Dynasties: State, Party, and Family in Contemporary Indian Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VwbFDAAAQBAJ&pg=PR10|date=28 April 2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-316-59212-0|page=131,136}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Government of India]]\n* [[State governments of India]]\n* [[Law of India]]\n* [[Indian political scandals]]\n* [[Disqualification of convicted representatives in India]]\n* [[Political families of India]]\n* [[List of think tanks in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [[Satyabrata Rai Chowdhuri|Chowdhuri, Satyabrata Rai]]. [http://www.palgrave.com/products/title.aspx?PID=278315 ''Leftism in India, 1917-1947'']. '''Palgrave''', [[U.K.]], 2007.\n* Shively, W. Phillips. ''Power and Choice: An Introduction to Political Science\u2014Chapter 14 Example: Parliamentary Government in India.'' McGraw Hill Higher Education, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-07-340391-5}}\n* Mitra, Subrata K. and